4.4 The Strong Law of Large Numbers
In reality, it is possible to prove that convergence does not only occur through the characteristic function, but it is the empirical mean itself that converges to \(\mu\); in this formulation, the law of large numbers is called strong.
Before we can write this law, it is necessary to introduce two concepts: that of convergence in probability and that of almost sure convergence.

A sequence of random variables $x_n$ **converges in probability** to a random variable $x$ if

\begin{equation}
    \lim_{n\to\infty}P\left(\abs{x_n-x}&gt;\epsilon\right)=0   \forall\epsilon&gt;0
\end{equation}

In this way, the probability that \(x_n\) deviates from \(x\) by an amount greater than \(\epsilon\) goes to zero as the number of variables considered increases. However, this does not guarantee that \(x_n\) converges to \(x\) for \(n\to\infty\); to understand why, let’s consider the following example of a sequence of random variables:
\[\begin{equation*}
    x_n=
    \begin{cases}
        0 \ \   \text{with probability} \ p(n)=\frac{1}{n}\\
        1 \ \   \text{with probability} \ 1-p(n)=1-\frac{1}{n}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
A realization of such a sequence will consist of \(0\)s and \(1\)s in sequence, with the various \(1\)s becoming increasingly rare:
\[\begin{equation*}
    010010000010000000000100000000000000\dots
\end{equation*}\]
The sequence converges in probability according to the definition, and it is equally evident that, regardless of the number \(n\), it will always be possible to draw a \(1\), however small that probability may be. If there existed a number \(N\) such that for every \(n&gt;N\) we had \(x_n=0\) with probability equal to \(1\) (or similarly \(x_n=1\) with probability \(0\)) the convergence would be called almost certain.

A sequence of random variables $x_n$ **converges almost surely** to a random variable $x$ if

\begin{equation}
    P\left(\lim_{n\to\infty}x_n=x\right)=1
\end{equation}

We can easily guess that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \text{**Almost sure convergence**}\ \ \ \genfrac{}{}{0pt}{}{\Longrightarrow}{\cancel{\Longleftarrow}} \ \ \ \text{**Convergence in probability**}
\end{equation*}\]
The strong law of large numbers makes use of almost sure convergence, stating that
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nx_i=\mu \ \              \text{**almost surely**}}
\end{equation}\]
The proof in this case is very elaborate and is therefore not reported.

4.5 Central Limit Theorem
With the law of large numbers we know that as \(n\) grows we have
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^nx_i\sim n\mu
\end{equation*}\]
This means that for a finite \(n\), that is, when not at the limit, the difference \(\sum x_i-n\mu\) will return non-zero values that coincide with the statistical fluctuations around \(n\mu\).
In this regard, it is natural to ask what trend these fluctuations have, that is, how that difference behaves. A first important result is that, as \(n\) increases, it is shown that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^nx_i-n\mu\sim\sqrt{n}
\end{equation*}\]
Knowing this trend, it is therefore possible to “normalize” the difference at the limit by dividing by \(\sqrt{n}\). The study of this normalized difference, moreover, allows us to demonstrate that its distribution converges to a normalized Gaussian with \(\mu=0\) and \(\sigma=1\) regardless of the distribution followed by the \(\boldsymbol{x_i}\).
It is important to underline that the two results just written are valid only if the variance \(\sigma^2\) associated with the variables \(x_i\) is finite.
What is written is the heart of one of the most important theorems in statistics and probability theory: the central limit theorem.

Given $n$ *independent* and *identically distributed* random variables with a finite mean $\mu$ and a finite and non-zero variance $\sigma^2$, we have that

\begin{equation}
   \boxed{Y_n=\frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^nx_i-n\mu}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\xrightarrow{\text{$n\to\infty$}} \ \mathcal{N}(0,1)}
\end{equation}

where $\mathcal{N}(0,1)$ is a Gaussian distribution with $\mu=0$ and $\sigma=1$

Before proceeding with the proof, it is useful to calculate the mean and variance of \(Y_n\) at the limit for \(n\to\infty\), using the result obtained from the central limit theorem:
\[\begin{align*}
    &\left\langle Y_n\right\rangle=\frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^n\left\langle x_i\right\rangle-n\mu}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}=\frac{n\mu-n\mu}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\to0\\
    &Var\left(Y_n\right)=\frac{Var\left(\sum\limits_{i=1}^nx_i-n\mu\right)}{n\sigma^2}=\frac{Var\left(\sum\limits_{i=1}^nx_i\right)}{n\sigma^2}=\frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^nVar\left(x_i\right)}{n\sigma^2}=\frac{n\sigma^2}{n\sigma^2}\to1
\end{align*}\]
In particular for the variance, the following properties have been exploited:
\[\begin{align*}
    &Var(ax)=a^2Var(x)\\   &Var(x+b)=Var(x)
\end{align*}\]
where \(a\) and \(b\) are constants.
Let’s now proceed with the proof.

First, let's calculate the characteristic function $\varphi(k)$ associated with $Y_n$:

\begin{equation*}
    \varphi(k)=\left\langle e^{ikY_n}\right\rangle=\int q\left(x_1\right)\dots q\left(x_n\right)e^{ik\frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^nx_i-n\mu}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}}dx_1\dots dx_n
\end{equation*}

We can now factor out $e^{-i\frac{kn}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu}=e^{-i\frac{k\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}\mu}$ and factorize the multiple integral exactly as we did in (eq:legge-dei-grandi-numeri-debole-funzione-caratteristica):

\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        \varphi(k)&=e^{-i\frac{k\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}\mu}\int q\left(x_1\right)e^{i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}x_1}dx_1\dotsc\int q\left(x_n\right)e^{i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}x_n}dx_n=\\
        &=e^{-i\frac{k\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}\mu}\left(\int q\left(x_i\right)e^{i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}x_i}dx_i\right)^n=e^{-i\frac{k\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}\mu}\varphi_i^n\left(\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\right)
    \end{split}
\end{align}

Continuing in the direction of the proof of the weak law of large numbers, we expand the $i$-th characteristic function found in series:

\begin{align*}
    \varphi_i\left(\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\right)&=\int q\left(x_i\right)e^{i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}x_i}dx_i=\
    &=\int q\left(x_i\right)\left[1+i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}x_i-\frac{k^2}{2n\sigma^2}x_i^2+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n^3}}\right)\right]dx_i=\\
    &=1+i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\left\langle x_i\right\rangle-\frac{k^2}{2n\sigma^2}\left\langle x_i^2\right\rangle+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n^3}}\right)
\end{align*}

Substituting $\mu=\left\langle x_i\right\rangle$ and $\sigma^2=\left\langle x_i^2\right\rangle-\left\langle x_i\right\rangle^2 \ \iff \ \left\langle x_i^2\right\rangle=\sigma^2+\mu^2$ we find:

\begin{align*}
    \varphi_i\left(\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\right)&=1+i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu-\frac{k^2}{2n\sigma^2}\left(\sigma^2+\mu^2\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n^3}}\right)=\\
    &=1+i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu-\frac{k^2}{2n}-\frac{k^2}{2n\sigma^2}\mu^2+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n^3}}\right)
\end{align*}

What is written is nothing more than the series expansion of the following exponential:

\begin{align*}
    e^{i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu-\frac{k^2}{2n}}&\simeq1+i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu-\frac{k^2}{2n}+\frac{1}{2}\left(i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu-\frac{k^2}{2n}\right)^2=\\
    &=1+i\frac{k}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu-\frac{k^2}{2n}-\frac{k^2}{2n\sigma^2}\mu^2+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n^3}}\right)
\end{align*}

Substituting in (eq:leggi-dei-grandi-numeri-funzione-caratteristica-limite-centrale) the characteristic function finally results in:

\begin{equation*}
    \varphi(k)=e^{-i\frac{k\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}\mu}\cdot e^{i\frac{kn}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\mu-\frac{k^2n}{2n}}=e^{-\cancel{i\frac{k\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}\mu}+\cancel{i\frac{k\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}\mu}-\frac{k^2}{2}}=e^{-\frac{k^2}{2}}
\end{equation*}

that is, the characteristic function associated with the normalized Gaussian with $\mu=0$ and $\sigma=1$, just as predicted by the theorem.


Show that


Solution. 
From the central limit theorem we know that

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^nx_i-n\mu}{\sqrt{n}\sigma}\sim\mathcal{N}(0,1)
\end{equation*}

Multiplying both sides by $\sqrt{n}\sigma$:

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^nx_i-n\mu\sim\sqrt{n}\sigma\mathcal{N}(0,1)=\mathcal{N}\left(0,n\sigma^2\right)
\end{equation*}

Adding $n\mu$ to both sides:

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^nx_i\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,n\sigma^2\right)+n\mu=\mathcal{N}\left(n\mu,n\sigma^2\right)
\end{equation*}

In this way we have proved the first relation; to obtain the second one it is sufficient to divide both sides of the last equation by $n$:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nx_i\sim\frac{1}{n}\mathcal{N}\left(n\mu,n\sigma^2\right)=\mathcal{N}\left(\frac{n\mu}{n},\frac{n\sigma^2}{n^2}\right)=\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\frac{\sigma^2}{n}\right)
\end{equation*}

5.1 First case: internal point
Let \(x_1&lt;x_0&lt;x_2\) with \(f'\left(x_0\right)=0\) being the maximum point for the function in the whole interval; for the same reason we will have that \(f''\left(x_0\right)&lt;0\).

As we expect, the major contribution will come in the neighborhood of \(x_0\), so it is useful to expand \(f(x)\) in series precisely at that point:
\[\begin{equation*}
    f(x)=f\left(x_0\right)+\cancel{f'\left(x_0\right)\left(x-x_0\right)}+\frac{f''\left(x_0\right)}{2}\left(x-x_0\right)^2+\mathcal{O}\left(\abs{x-x_0}^3\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Substituting in (eq:metodo-di-laplace-integrale-iniziale):
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)=\int_{x_1}^{x_2}g(x)e^{\lambda\left[f\left(x_0\right)+\frac{f''\left(x_0\right)}{2}\left(x-x_0\right)^2+\mathcal{O}\left(\abs{x-x_0}^3\right)\right]}dx
\end{equation*}\]
In the limit for \(x\to x_0\) we will have \(g(x)\to g\left(x_0\right)\) and all the terms \(\mathcal{O}\left(\abs{x-x_0}^3\right)\) can be considered null:
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)\int_{x_1}^{x_2}e^{\lambda\left[f\left(x_0\right)+\frac{f''\left(x_0\right)}{2}\left(x-x_0\right)^2\right]}dx=g\left(x_0\right)e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}\int_{x_1}^{x_2}e^{\frac{\lambda f''\left(x_0\right)}{2}\left(x-x_0\right)^2}dx
\end{equation*}\]
Furthermore, remembering that \(f''\left(x_0\right)&lt;0\), we can write:
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}\int_{x_1}^{x_2}e^{-\frac{\lambda \abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}{2}\left(x-x_0\right)^2}dx
\end{equation*}\]
At this point we set
\[\begin{equation}{}
    s=\sqrt{\frac{\lambda\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}{2}}\left(x-x_0\right)
\end{equation}\]
so as to have a Gaussian-type exponential in the integral:
\[\begin{equation}{}
    I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}\sqrt{\frac{2}{\lambda\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}}\int_{s_1}^{s_2}e^{-s^2}ds
\end{equation}\]
The limits of the integral are given by the substitution in equation (eq:metodo-di-laplace-sostituzione-s) of \(x=x_1\) in one case and of \(x=x_2\) in the other, so we will have \(s_1&lt;0\) and \(s_2&gt;0\). Since the two limits are proportional to \(\sqrt{\lambda}\) in the limit for \(\lambda\to\infty\) we have:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_{s_1}^{s_2}e^{-s^2}ds \ \xrightarrow{\lambda\to\infty} \ \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-s^2}ds=\sqrt{\pi}
\end{equation*}\]
We can therefore approximate the integral to
\[\begin{equation}{}
    \boxed{I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}}}
\end{equation}\]
This is the dominant term, that is, the one that provides the major contribution in the limit for \(\lambda\to\infty\): considering the successive terms in the expansion of \(f(x)\) and \(g(x)\) it is also possible to obtain the other contributions, as we will see below in exercise (ex:metodo-di-laplace-sviluppi-successivi).

*Show that a better approximation of equation (eq:metodo-di-laplace-termine-dominante* is given by)

\begin{equation}{}
    I(\lambda)\simeq e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}}\left(g\left(x_0\right)+\frac{c}{\lambda}\right)
\end{equation}

*where* $c$ *is a constant that depends on the derivatives of* $f(x)$ *up to the fourth order (calculated at* $x_0$*), on* $g\left(x_0\right)$ *and on* $g'\left(x_0\right)$.

I start from the assumption that the text is actually *misleading*, in the sense that the constant $c$ does not depend only on $g\left(x_0\right)$ and $g'\left(x_0\right)$ but also on $g''\left(x_0\right)$, as we will see below due to the series expansions of the functions.

For simplicity of writing I will use the following notations:

\begin{itemize}
    \item $x-x_0=z$
    \item $f\left(x_0\right)=f_0$
\end{itemize}

As suggested by the text, let's expand both $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ in series around $x_0$, remembering that $f_0'=0$ and that $f_0''=-\abs{f_0''}$:

\begin{align*}
    &f(x)=f_0-\frac{\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2+\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\\
    &g(x)=g_0+g_0'z+\frac{g_0''}{2}z^2+\dots
\end{align*}

Let's now make the integral explicit as a function of $\lambda$:

\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)=\int_{z_1}^{z_2}\left[g_0+g_0'z+\frac{g_0''}{2}z^2+\dots\right]e^{\lambda\left[f_0-\frac{\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2+\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]}dz
\end{equation*}

Let's now focus only on the exponential, which we can also write as

\begin{equation*}
    e^{\lambda\left[f_0-\frac{\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2+\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]}=e^{\lambda f_0}e^{-\frac{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2}e^{\lambda\left[\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]}
\end{equation*}

The term $e^{\lambda f_0}e^{-\frac{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2}$ we had already obtained in the previous calculation; to this is added the last exponential, which we can include in the calculation by expanding it in series:

\begin{align*}
    &e^{\lambda\left[\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]}=\\
    &=1+\lambda\left[\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]+\frac{\lambda^2}{2}\left[\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]^2+\dots
\end{align*}

Let's remember that all these terms must be multiplied by the expansion of $g(x)$, by $e^{\lambda f_0}$ and by $e^{-\frac{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2}$. Net of multiplicative factors, we will find ourselves solving integrals of the type:

\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}z^ne^{-\frac{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2}dz
\end{equation*}

already considering the limit $\lambda\to\infty$.

We immediately understand that if $n$ is odd the integral will be zero, as it is an integral in a symmetric interval of an odd function.

Considering therefore only even powers, we can rewrite the integral in the following way:

\begin{align*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}z^ne^{-\frac{a}{2}z^2}dz&=\frac{\partial^{\frac{n}{2}}}{\partial\left(-\frac{a}{2}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-\frac{a}{2}z^2}dz=(-2)^{\frac{n}{2}}\frac{\partial^{\frac{n}{2}}}{\partial a^{\frac{n}{2}}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-\frac{a}{2}z^2}dz=\\
    &=(-2)^{\frac{n}{2}}\frac{\partial^{\frac{n}{2}}}{\partial a^{\frac{n}{2}}}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a}}
\end{align*}

having set $a=\lambda\abs{f_0''}$.

To find the general formula, let's calculate the results for the smallest $n$, remembering that $n$ can only be even:

\begin{align*}
    &n=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ (-2)^0\frac{\partial^0}{\partial a^0}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a}}=\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a}}\\
    &n=2 \ \Longrightarrow \ (-2)\frac{\partial}{\partial a}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a}}=-2\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a^3}}=\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a^3}}\\
    &n=4 \ \Longrightarrow \ (-2)^2\frac{\partial^2}{\partial a^2}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a}}=4\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(-\frac{3}{2}\right)\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a^5}}=3\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a^5}}\\
    &n=6 \ \Longrightarrow \ (-2)^3\frac{\partial^3}{\partial a^3}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a}}=-8\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(-\frac{3}{2}\right)\left(-\frac{5}{2}\right)\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a^7}}=15\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a^7}}
\end{align*}

In general it will result

\begin{equation}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}z^ne^{-\frac{a}{2}z^2}dz=(n-1)!!\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a^{n+1}}}=\frac{(n-1)!!}{a^{\frac{n}{2}}}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{a}}
\end{equation}

Substituting $a=\lambda\abs{f_0''}$ we find

\begin{equation}{}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}z^ne^{-\frac{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}{2}z^2}dz=\frac{(n-1)!!}{\lambda^{\frac{n}{2}}\abs{f_0''}^{\frac{n}{2}}}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}}
\end{equation}

Looking at the form we need to arrive at (equation (eq:metodo-di-laplace-soluzione-esercizio-famigerato)), we note that the term $e^{\lambda f_0}$ and the term $\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}}$ (which results from each integral, and we can therefore factor out for all contributions) are already made explicit in front of the factor. This means that we will only have to focus on the rest, that is, on the products that come out of the expansion of $g(x)$ and the expansion of $e^{\lambda\left[\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]}$:

\begin{align*}
    &\left[g_0+g_0'z+\frac{g_0''}{2}z^2+\dots\right]\cdot1+\\
    &+\left[g_0+g_0'z+\frac{g_0''}{2}z^2+\dots\right]\cdot\lambda\left[\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]+\\
    &+\left[g_0+g_0'z+\frac{g_0''}{2}z^2+\dots\right]\cdot\frac{\lambda^2}{2}\left[\frac{f_0'''}{6}z^3+\frac{f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\dots\right]^2+\\
    &+\dots
\end{align*}

From (eq:metodo-di-laplace-esercizio-famigerato-relazione-z-lambda) we know that from a term of the type $\propto z^n$ a result $\propto\lambda^{-\frac{n}{2}}$ comes out. Since we only want the terms up to $\frac{1}{\lambda}$ then

\begin{itemize}
    \item of all the terms multiplied by $\lambda^0$ we will have to consider only those up to $z^2$
    \item of all the terms multiplied by $\lambda^1$ we will have to consider only those up to $z^4$
    \item of all the terms multiplied by $\lambda^2$ we will have to consider only those up to $z^6$
\end{itemize}

Remembering that all odd powers give a null contribution, it will result:

\begin{align*}
    &\left[g_0+\cancel{g_0'z}+\frac{g_0''}{2}z^2\right]+\\
    &+\lambda\left[\cancel{\frac{g_0f_0'''}{6}z^3}+\frac{g_0f_0^{IV}}{24}z^4+\frac{g_0'f_0'''}{6}z^4\right]+\\
    &+\frac{\lambda^2}{2}\left[\frac{g_0\left(f_0'''\right)^2}{36}z^6\right]
\end{align*}

Let's write the results by referring to (eq:metodo-di-laplace-esercizio-famigerato-relazione-z-lambda):

\begin{align*}
    &g_0+\frac{g_0''}{2\lambda\abs{f_0''}}+\lambda\left[\frac{3g_0f_0^{IV}}{24\lambda^2\abs{f_0''}^2}+\frac{3g_0'f_0'''}{6\lambda^2\abs{f_0''}^2}\right]+\frac{\lambda^2}{2}\left[\frac{15g_0\left(f_0'''\right)^2}{36\lambda^3\abs{f_0''}^3}\right]=\\
    &=g_0+\frac{g_0''}{2\lambda\abs{f_0''}}+\frac{g_0f_0^{IV}}{8\lambda\abs{f_0''}^2}+\frac{g_0'f_0'''}{2\lambda\abs{f_0''}^2}+\frac{5g_0\left(f_0'''\right)^2}{24\lambda\abs{f_0''}^3}
\end{align*}

Putting all the terms together, it finally results:

\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)=e^{\lambda f_0}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda\abs{f_0''}}}\left[g_0+\frac{1}{\lambda}\left(\frac{g_0''}{2\abs{f_0''}}+\frac{g_0f_0^{IV}}{8\abs{f_0''}^2}+\frac{g_0'f_0'''}{2\abs{f_0''}^2}+\frac{5g_0\left(f_0'''\right)^2}{24\abs{f_0''}^3}\right)\right]
\end{equation*}

From which we find a constant

\begin{equation*}
    c=\frac{1}{2\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}\left[\frac{g\left(x_0\right)}{4}\left(\frac{5f'''\left(x_0\right)^2}{3\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}^2}+\frac{f^{IV}\left(x_0\right)}{\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}\right)+\frac{g'\left(x_0\right)f'''\left(x_0\right)}{\abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}}+g''\left(x_0\right)\right]
\end{equation*}

