5.3 Third case: non-stationary end point
Let \(x_0=x_1\) or \(x_0=x_2\) but with \(f'\left(x_0\right)\neq0\).
Since this time the first derivative does not vanish at \(x_0\), the expansion of the function can be stopped at the first order:
\[\begin{equation*}
    f(x)=f\left(x_0\right)+f'\left(x_0\right)\left(x-x_0\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\abs{x-x_0}^2\right)
\end{equation*}\]
At this point we proceed as in the previous cases. First, let’s go to the limit for \(x\to x_0\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}\int_{x_1}^{x_2}e^{\lambda f'\left(x_0\right)\left(x-x_0\right)}dx
\end{equation*}\]
Without loss of generality, let’s assume that \(f'\left(x_0\right)&lt;0\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}\int_{x_1}^{x_2}e^{-\lambda\abs{f'\left(x_0\right)}\left(x-x_0\right)}dx
\end{equation*}\]
Now let’s set
\[\begin{equation}{}
    s=\lambda\abs{f'\left(x_0\right)}\left(x-x_0\right)
\end{equation}\]
so as to have:
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)\frac{e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}}{\lambda\abs{f'\left(x_0\right)}}\int_{s_1}^{s_2}e^{-s}ds
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s now assume that \(x_0=x_1\); from (eq:metodo-di-laplace-sostituzione-s-caso-3) it is clear that \(s_1=0\), and by sending \(\lambda\to\infty\) we have instead that \(s_2\to\infty\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)\frac{e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}}{\lambda\abs{f'\left(x_0\right)}}\int_0^\infty e^{-s}ds=g\left(x_0\right)\frac{e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}}{\lambda\abs{f'\left(x_0\right)}}\left(-e^{-s}\right)\bigg|_0^\infty
\end{equation*}\]
From which the final formula is obtained:
\[\begin{equation}{}
    \boxed{I(\lambda)\simeq g\left(x_0\right)\frac{e^{\lambda f\left(x_0\right)}}{\lambda\abs{f'\left(x_0\right)}}}
\end{equation}\]

Obtain the dominant order approximation (for \(\lambda\to\infty\)) of:


Solution. \[\begin{equation*}
        \int_{-2}^0 x^m h(x)dx \ \  *where* \ h(x)=e^{\lambda\left(2x^3+3x^2\right)} *and* \ m *is a fixed positive parameter.*
    \end{equation*}\]
First, let's observe where the stationary points of $f(x)=2x^3+3x^2$ are by seeing where its derivative vanishes:

\begin{equation*}
    f'(x)=6x\left(x+1\right)=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ x=-1,0
\end{equation*}

To understand if they are maximum or minimum points, let's evaluate the sign that the second derivative assumes at these points:

\begin{equation*}
    f''(x)=6(2x+1) \ \Longrightarrow \ f''(-1)=-6, \ f''(0)=6
\end{equation*}

This means that the relative maximum point for $f(x)$ is $x_0=-1$.

Let's then evaluate the first integral. Since for $x\to-\infty$ the behavior of the function is $f(x)\to-\infty$ then the function grows up to $x_0=-1$, so $x_0$ will be an internal maximum point in the interval $[-2,0]$; this means that we fall into the first case and we will have to apply the formula (eq:metodo-di-laplace-termine-dominante).

\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-2}^0 x^m h(x)dx\simeq(-1)^me^\lambda\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{6\lambda}}=(-1)^me^\lambda\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{3\lambda}}
\end{equation*}

In the second interval considered, $x_0=-1$ constitutes an end, so we fall into the second case and therefore we will have to apply the formula (eq:metodo-di-laplace-caso-2):

\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-1}^0 x^m h(x)dx\simeq(-1)^me^\lambda\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{12\lambda}}
\end{equation*}

Since $x=0$ is a minimum point, then $f(x)$ in the interval $[0,1]$ is increasing, so the maximum point will be precisely the end $x=1$ which is not, however, a stationary point for the function. We are therefore in the third case and we must apply the (eq:metodo-di-laplace-caso-3):

\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^1 x^m h(x)dx\simeq\frac{e^{5\lambda}}{12\lambda}
\end{equation*}

5.4 Applications of the Laplace method

5.4.1 Stirling’s formula
The Laplace method is also useful for understanding how quickly the factorial of a number \(n\) grows as \(n\) itself grows.
The analytical definition of the factorial is given by the Euler’s Gamma function:
\[\begin{equation}
    \Gamma(\lambda+1)=\int_0^\infty e^{-x}x^\lambda dx
\end{equation}\]

Show that


Solution. \[\begin{equation*}
        \Gamma(\lambda+1)=\lambda\Gamma(\lambda)
    \end{equation*}\]
*from which it follows* $\lambda!=\Gamma(\lambda+1)$.

Integrating by parts, one obtains:

\begin{equation*}
    \Gamma(\lambda+1)=\int_0^\infty e^{-x}x^\lambda dx=\cancel{-e^{-x}x^\lambda\bigg|_0^\infty}+\lambda\int_0^\infty e^{-x}x^{\lambda-1}dx=\lambda\Gamma(\lambda)
\end{equation*}

To return to the cases seen in the Laplace method, it is necessary to write \(x^\lambda\) in exponential form:
\[\begin{equation}{}
    \Gamma(\lambda+1)=\int_0^\infty e^{-x}e^{\lambda\ln x} dx
\end{equation}\]
The point is that by choosing \(g(x)=e^{-x}\) and \(f(x)=\ln x\) it is not possible to apply the Laplace method, because the logarithm does not have a specific peak but grows indefinitely as \(x\) grows.
What is convenient to do is to set \(x=\lambda t\) so as to have
\[\begin{equation*}
    \Gamma(\lambda+1)=\int_0^\infty e^{-\lambda t}\lambda^\lambda t^\lambda\lambda dt=\lambda^{\lambda+1}\int_0^\infty t^\lambda e^{-\lambda t}dt
\end{equation*}\]
In this case too, the problem arises when considering \(f(t)=-t\). However, if we repeat the step written in (eq:metodo-di-laplace-formula-di-stirling-base-comune) we will have:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \Gamma(\lambda+1)=\lambda^{\lambda+1}\int_0^\infty e^{\lambda\ln t}e^{-\lambda t}dt=\lambda^{\lambda+1}\int_0^\infty e^{\lambda(\ln t-t)}dt
\end{equation*}\]
We note that \(f(t)=\ln t-t\) is a decreasing function for \(t\to\infty\) but has a stationary point at
\[\begin{equation*}
    f'(t)=\frac{1}{t}-1=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ t=1
\end{equation*}\]
It is easily verified that this point is a maximum, being
\[\begin{equation*}
    f''(t)=-\frac{1}{t^2} \ \Longrightarrow \ f''(1)=-1
\end{equation*}\]
This means that we can consider \(g(t)=1\) and \(f(t)=\ln t-t\) and apply the Laplace method which falls into the first case:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\lambda!=\Gamma(\lambda+1)\simeq\lambda^{\lambda+1}e^{-\lambda}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}}}
\end{equation}\]
Using the solution of exercise (ex:metodo-di-laplace-sviluppi-successivi) we can improve the estimate:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \lambda!\simeq\lambda^{\lambda+1}e^{-\lambda}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}}\left(1+\frac{1}{2\lambda}\left[\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{5\cdot4}{3}+\frac{-6}{1}\right)\right]\right)=\lambda^{\lambda+1}e^{-\lambda}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}}\left(1+\frac{1}{12\lambda}\right)
\end{equation*}\]


5.4.2 Lp norm
From real analysis we know that the \(p\)-norm of a function \(g(t)\) belonging to the space \(L^p([a,b])\) is defined as
\[\begin{equation}{}
    \norm{h}_p=\left(\int_a^b\abs{h(x)}^pdx\right)^{\frac{1}{p}}
\end{equation}\]
We will see how through the Laplace method we are able to study the behavior of this norm in the limit for \(p\to\infty\), that is, when the space becomes infinite-dimensional.
First, let’s define the integral:
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(p)=\int_a^b\abs{h(x)}^pdx
\end{equation*}\]
from which it follows that \(\norm{h}_p=I(p)^{\frac{1}{p}}\).
Again, it is useful to write the function in exponential form:
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(p)=\int_a^be^{p\ln\abs{h(x)}}dx
\end{equation*}\]
To apply the Laplace method, it is necessary that \(\ln\abs{h(x)}\) be differentiable in the whole interval \([a,b]\), but this turns out to be true in the case where \(h(x)\) does not vanish at some point, since the logarithm is not defined at \(0\). However, returning to equation (eq:metodo-di-laplace-norma-p), we note that for very small \(h(x)\) the contribution to the integral becomes negligible in the limit for \(p\to\infty\), so we will neglect this discontinuity at the first order of the expansion.
Let’s therefore proceed with the calculation. First, let’s calculate the second derivative of \(f(x)=\ln\abs{h(x)}\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    f'(x)=\frac{h'(x)}{h(x)} \ \Longrightarrow \ f''(x)=\frac{h''(x)}{h(x)}-\frac{h'(x)^2}{h(x)^2}=\frac{h''(x)h(x)-h'(x)^2}{h(x)^2}
\end{equation*}\]
Remembering that \(h'\left(x_0\right)=0\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \abs{f''\left(x_0\right)}=\abs{\frac{h''\left(x_0\right)}{h\left(x_0\right)}}=\frac{\abs{h''\left(x_0\right)}}{\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}}
\end{equation*}\]
Since the logarithm is a monotonically increasing function, the maximum \(x_0\) for \(h(x)\) will also be so for \(\ln\abs{h(x)}\). Assuming that this maximum is within \([a,b]\), we can substitute the functions \(g(x)=1\) and \(f(x)=\ln\abs{h(x)}\) in equation (eq:metodo-di-laplace-termine-dominante).
\[\begin{equation*}
    I(p)\simeq e^{p\ln\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}}{p\abs{h''\left(x_0\right)}}}=\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}^p\sqrt{\frac{2\pi\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}}{p\abs{h''\left(x_0\right)}}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s now try to calculate the norm:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \norm{g}_p=I(p)^{\frac{1}{p}}\simeq\abs{h\left(x_o\right)}\left(\sqrt{\frac{2\pi\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}}{p\abs{h''\left(x_0\right)}}}\right)^{\frac{1}{p}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s set \(\alpha=\sqrt{\frac{2\pi\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}}{\abs{h''\left(x_0\right)}}}\) and express in exponential form all the terms with an exponent:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \norm{g}_p\simeq\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}\alpha^{\frac{1}{p}}p^{-\frac{1}{2p}}\simeq\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}e^{\frac{\ln\alpha}{p}}e^{-\frac{\ln p}{2p}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s expand the exponentials in series, stopping at the first order:
\[\begin{align*}
    \norm{g}_p&\simeq\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}\left(1+\frac{\ln\alpha}{p}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{p^2}\right)\right)\left(1-\frac{\ln p}{2p}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{p^2}\right)\right)=\\
    &=\abs{h\left(x_0\right)}\left(1-\frac{\ln p}{2p}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\ln p}{p}\right)\right)
\end{align*}\]
We find
\[\begin{equation*}
    \norm{g}_p\simeq\max_{x\in[a,b]}\\abs{h(x)}\left(1-\frac{\ln p}{2p}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\ln p}{p}\right)\right)
\end{equation*}\]
which corresponds precisely to the norm of the space \(L^\infty\), also considering the additional corrective terms due to the series expansions.

7.2 Microscopic derivation
Moving from a mesoscopic to a microscopic scale, we will no longer approach a continuous system but a discrete one. Let’s therefore consider a one-dimensional lattice of step \(\Delta\ell\) in which a particle can only move at a unit of time distant \(\Delta t\) from the previous one.
Having discretized both time and space, we can write the two coordinates in the following way:
\[\begin{equation*}
    x_i=i\Delta\ell,   i=0,\pm1,\pm2,\dots   t_k=k\Delta t,   k=0,1,2,\dots
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s introduce the following probabilities:
Let’s impose that
\[\begin{equation}
    p_++p_-=1
\end{equation}\]
that is, that at time \(t_{k+1}\) the particle must necessarily move either one position back or one position forward, without any other possibility. In this case, for a particle to reach the position \(x_i\) at time \(t_{k+1}\) there are only two possibilities
Summing the probabilities relative to the two cases we obtain what is called the master equation:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{W_i(k+1)=W_{i-1}(k)p_++W_{i+1}(k)p_-}
\end{equation}\]
The process described here is commonly called a random walk, since it follows the random path of a particle that has a certain probability of moving in one direction or the other at each step. The master equation of a random walk does nothing more than make explicit how the probability for a coordinate \(x_i\) changes over time.
An important property to keep in mind is that the master equation must conserve normalization, that is, the sum \(\sum_iW_i(k)\) must be equal to \(1\) at all times \(t_k\). To verify this, we just need to place the summation in (eq:diffusion-master-equation):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_i(k+1)=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_{i-1}(k)p_++\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_{i+1}(k)p_-
\end{equation*}\]
Since \(i\) runs over infinite values, we can indicate both \(i+1\) and \(i-1\) with the same index \(j\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_i(k+1)=\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_j(k)p_++\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_j(k)p_-=\left(p_++p_-\right)\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_j(k)
\end{equation*}\]
From (eq:diffusione-normalizzazione-p-+-p–) it follows
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_i(k+1)=\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}W_j(k)
\end{equation*}\]
which is the initial thesis. This means that in a random walk, particles are not born from nothing and do not disappear into nothing, but remain within the lattice for the entire evolution of the system.
In general, a random walk is very simple to simulate by computer. By imposing the same parameters and the same initial conditions, in fact, the probability \(W_i(k)\) can be estimated as
\[\begin{equation*}
    W_i(k)=\frac{r}{R}
\end{equation*}\]
where \(r\) is the number of simulations in which the particle is at \(x_i\) at time \(t_k\) and \(R\) is the total number of simulations.
Despite the simplicity with respect to numerical calculation, we will see below how to derive \(W_i(k)\) analytically in general, thus formally solving the master equation.

7.2.1 Solution with generating functions
Let’s define the following generating function:
\[\begin{equation}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_i(k)
\end{equation}\]
To write the master equation as a function of the generating function, we must multiply both members by \(z^i\) and sum over all possible indices \(i\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_i(k+1)=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_{i-1}(k)p_++\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_{i+1}(k)p_-
\end{equation*}\]
On the right-hand side, let’s multiply and divide each term by \(z\) so as to have the exponent \(i-1\) in one case and \(i+1\) in the other:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_i(k+1)=zp_+\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^{i-1}W_{i-1}(k)+\frac{p_-}{z}\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^{i+1}W_{i+1}(k)
\end{equation*}\]
At this point we can substitute the definition (eq:diffusione-funzione-generatrice-definizione):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k+1)=zp_+\tilde{W}(z,k)+\frac{p_-}{z}\tilde{W}(z,k)=\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)\tilde{W}(z,k)
\end{equation*}\]
From this law it follows iteratively:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k+1)=\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)\tilde{W}(z,k)=\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^2\tilde{W}(z,k-1)=\dots
\end{equation*}\]
And therefore, in general:
\[\begin{equation}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^k\tilde{W}(z,0)
\end{equation}\]
Let’s remember that the variable \(k\) refers to the time coordinate \(t_k\). If the particle is at the coordinate \(x_{i_0}\) at time \(t=t_0\) then
\[\begin{equation*}
    W_i(0)=\delta_{i,i_0} \ \Longrightarrow \ \ \tilde{W}(z,0)=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^i\delta_{i,i_0}=z^{i_0}
\end{equation*}\]
We thus find the following expression for the generating function:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\tilde{W}(z,k)=\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^kz^{i_0}}
\end{equation}\]
It goes without saying that, by setting \(i_0=0\), it results
\[\begin{equation}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^k
\end{equation}\]
Having found an analytical expression for \(\tilde{W}(z,k)\) independent of \(W_i(k)\), we can use this to calculate the mean and variance associated with the probability distribution relative to the particle’s position.
First of all, let’s note that by deriving the generating function starting from the definition, it results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d\tilde{W}}{dz}=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}iz^{i-1}W_i(k)
\end{equation*}\]
By setting \(z=1\) we find the average position:
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{d\tilde{W}}{dz}\bigg|_{z=1}=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}iW_i(k)=\langle i(k)\rangle\equiv\mu(k)
\end{equation}\]
Let’s calculate the first member starting from (eq:diffusione-funzione-generatrice-espressione):
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{d\tilde{W}}{dz}=k\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-1}\left(p_+-\frac{p_-}{z^2}\right)z^{i_0}+\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^ki_0z^{i_0-1}
\end{equation}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d\tilde{W}}{dz}\bigg|_{z=1}=k\left(p_++p_-\right)^{k-1}\left(p_+-p_-\right)+\left(p_++p_-\right)^ki_0
\end{equation*}\]
Remembering that \(p_++p_-=1\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\mu(k)=k(p_+-p_-)+i_0}
\end{equation}\]
Intuitively, the particle will tend to move over time by a quantity proportional to \(p_+-p_-\) with respect to the starting coordinate \(x_{i_0}\).
Let’s now move on to the second derivative of \(\tilde{W}(z,k)\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d^2\tilde{W}}{dz^2}=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}i(i-1)z^{i-2}W_i(k)
\end{equation*}\]
From which it follows
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d^2\tilde{W}}{dz^2}\bigg|_{z=1}=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}i(i-1)W_i(k)=\langle i(i-1)\rangle=\left\langle i(k)^2-i(k)\right\rangle=\left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle-\langle i(k)\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
We know that the variance is given by:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sigma(k)^2=\left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle-\langle i(k)\rangle^2
\end{equation*}\]
Therefore, by adding and subtracting \(\langle i(k)\rangle\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sigma(k)^2=\left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle-\langle i(k)\rangle+\langle i(k)\rangle-\langle i(k)\rangle^2=\frac{d^2\tilde{W}}{dz^2}\bigg|_{z=1}+\langle i(k)\rangle-\langle i(k)\rangle^2
\end{equation*}\]
All we have to do, therefore, is to calculate the second derivative of \(\tilde{W}(z,k)\); let’s start directly from (eq:diffusione-funzione-generatrice-derivata-prima), coloring each term differently to better visualize each contribution dependent on \(z\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d}{dz}\left(\frac{d\tilde{W}}{dz}\right)=\frac{d}{dz}\left[\red{k\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-1}}\green{\left(p_+-\frac{p_-}{z^2}\right)}\orange{z^{i_0}}+\blue{\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^k}\purple{i_0z^{i_0-1}}\right]
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s now calculate each contribution separately:
\[\begin{align*}
    &\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {1}}}}   k\red{(k-1)\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-2}}\left(p_+-\frac{p_-}{z^2}\right)^{\red{2}}z^{i_0} \\
    &\green{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}}   k\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-1}\green{\left(\frac{2p_-}{z^3}\right)}z^{i_0} \\
    &\orange{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {3}}}}   k\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-1}\left(p_+-\frac{p_-}{z^2}\right)\orange{i_0z^{i_0-1}} \\
    &\blue{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {4}}}}   \blue{k\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-1}\left(p_+-\frac{p_-}{z^2}\right)}i_0z^{i_0-1} \\
    &\purple{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {5}}}}   \left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^k\purple{i_0\left(i_0-1\right)z^{i_0-2}}
\end{align*}\]
Let’s now set \(z=1\):
\[\begin{align*}
    &\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {1}}}}   k(k-1)\left(p_++p_-\right)^{k-2}\left(p_+-p_-\right)^2=k(k-1)\left(p_+-p_-\right)^2 \\
    &\green{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}}   k\left(p_++p_-\right)^{k-1}2p_-=2kp_- \\
    &\orange{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {3}}}}   k\left(p_++p_-\right)^{k-1}\left(p_+-p_-\right)i_0=k\left(p_+-p_-\right)i_0 \\
    &\blue{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {4}}}}   k\left(p_++p_-\right)^{k-1}\left(p_+-p_-\right)i_0=k\left(p_+-p_-\right)i_0 \\
    &\purple{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {5}}}}   \left(p_++p_-\right)^ki_0\left(i_0-1\right)=i_0\left(i_0-1\right) \\
\end{align*}\]
Returning to the expression for \(\sigma(k)^2\), we will have to sum all these contributions together with \(\mu(k)\) and \(-\mu(k)^2\):
\[\begin{align*}
    \sigma(k)^2=&k(k-1)\left(p_+-p_-\right)^2+2kp_-\cancel{+2k\left(p_+-p_-\right)i_0}\cancel{+i_0^2}\cancel{-i_0}+\\
    &+k\left(p_+-p_-\right)\cancel{+i_0}-k^2\left(p_+-p_-\right)^2\\
    & \cancel{-2k\left(p_+-p_-\right)i_0}\\
    & \cancel{-i_0^2}
\end{align*}\]
What remains is:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sigma(k)^2=\cancel{k^2\left(p_+-p_-\right)^2}-k\left(p_+-p_-\right)^2+2kp_-+k\left(p_+-p_-\right)\cancel{-k^2\left(p_+-p_-\right)^2}
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sigma(k)^2=2kp_-+k\left(p_+-p_-\right)\left[1-\left(p_+-p_-\right)\right]
\end{equation*}\]
Knowing that \(1=p_++p_-\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    1-\left(p_+-p_-\right)=\cancel{p_+}+p_- \cancel{-p_+}+p_-=2p_- \ \Longrightarrow \ \ \sigma(k)^2=2kp_-+2k_-(p_+-p_-)
\end{equation*}\]
We thus find:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sigma(k)^2=2kp_-(1+p_+-p_-)
\end{equation*}\]
Substituting once again \(1=p_++p_-\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \sigma(k)^2=2kp_-(p_+\cancel{+p_-}+p_+\cancel{-p_-})\ \Longrightarrow \ \boxed{\sigma(k)^2=4kp_+p_-}
\end{equation}\]
The variance therefore also increases proportionally to time, in this case by a factor given by the product \(p_+p_-\).
At this point, let’s try to calculate the distribution. Let’s go back to equation (eq:diffusione-funzione-generatrice-espressione) and write the binomial power using the binomial theorem:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=z^{i_0}\sum_{n=0}^k\binom{k}{n}\left(zp_+\right)^n\left(\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-n}
\end{equation*}\]
We want the summation index to run over a symmetric interval, thus going from \(n\in[0,k]\) to \(i\in[-k,k]\). Let’s therefore set \(i=2n-k\) so that \(n=0\Rightarrow i=-k\) and that \(n=k\Rightarrow i=k\), obtaining:
\[\begin{equation*}
    n=\frac{k+i}{2} \ \Longrightarrow \ \ \tilde{W}(z,k)=z^{i_0}\sum_{i=-k}^k\binom{k}{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(zp_+\right)^{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-\frac{k+i}{2}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s make the factor \(z\) explicit:
\[\begin{align*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)&=z^{i_0}\sum_{i=-k}^kz^{\frac{k+i}{2}}z^{-\frac{k-i}{2}}\binom{k}{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-i}{2}}=\\
    &=z^{i_0}\sum_{i=-k}^kz^i\binom{k}{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-i}{2}}\\
    &=\sum_{i=-k}^kz^{i+i_0}\binom{k}{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-i}{2}}
\end{align*}\]
Let’s set \(j=i+i_0\) so as to have only the index as the exponent of \(z\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\sum_{j=-k+i_0}^{k+i_0}z^{j}\binom{k}{\frac{k+j-i_0}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+\left(j-i_0\right)}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-\left(j-i_0\right)}{2}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s make a comparison with (eq:diffusione-funzione-generatrice-definizione):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_i(k)=\sum_{i=-k+i_0}^{k+i_0}z^i\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-i_0}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+\left(i-i_0\right)}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-\left(i-i_0\right)}{2}}
\end{equation*}\]
We thus find that
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{W_i(k)= \
    \begin{cases}
        \binom{k}{\frac{k+i-i_0}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+\left(i-i_0\right)}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-\left(i-i_0\right)}{2}} \ \  &i\in[-k+i_0,k+i_0]\\
                0 \ &   \text{otherwise}
    \end{cases}}
\end{equation}\]}} \end{equation}

*Find the solution* $W_i(k)$ *by imposing a generic initial condition* $W_i(0)=g_i$.

If $W_i(0)$ then

\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,0)=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_i(0)=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^ig_i
\end{equation*}

From (eq:diffusione-funzione-generatrice-funzione-di-k=0) it follows that

\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\left(zp_++\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^k\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^jg_j
\end{equation*}

Let's use the binomial theorem again this time:

\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\sum_{n=0}^k\binom{k}{n}\left(zp_+\right)^n\left(\frac{p_-}{z}\right)^{k-n}\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^jg_j
\end{equation*}

Let's make the power of $z$ explicit:

\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}\sum_{n=0}^kz^{j+n-k+n}g_j\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}
\end{equation*}

Let's pay attention to the fact that the term in $z$ is

\begin{equation*}
    z^{j+2n-k}
\end{equation*}

while we want it to be a single index as an exponent. For this reason we set:

\begin{equation*}
    i=j+2n-k
\end{equation*}

The extremes of the index $i$ will be determined by those of the index $n$:

\begin{align*}
    &n=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ \ i=j-k\\
    &n=k \ \Longrightarrow \ \ i=j+k
\end{align*}

Furthermore, to be able to make the powers of $p_+$ and $p_-$ explicit, it is convenient to derive $n$ and $k-n$ as a function of this new index:

\begin{align*}
    &2n+j-k=i \ \Longrightarrow \ \ n=\frac{k+i-j}{2}\\
    &k-n=k-\frac{k+i-j}{2}=\frac{k-(i-j)}{2}
\end{align*}

Substituting:

\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)=\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}\sum_{i=j-k}^{j+k}z^ig_j\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-(i-j)}{2}}
\end{equation*}

We note that we can invert the indices $i$ and $j$ in the two summations without modifying the summation as a whole. This is because $j$ is an index that runs through all the relative integers, and therefore since $i=j+2n-k$ then $i$ will also run in the same way through all of $\mathbb{Z}$. It is therefore clear that any pair $(i,j)$ is the same whether we consider $i\in[j-k,j+k]$ or whether we consider $j\in[i-k,i+k]$, therefore

\begin{align*}
    \tilde{W}(z,k)&=\sum_{j=-\infty}^{+\infty}\sum_{i=j-k}^{j+k}z^ig_j\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-(i-j)}{2}}\\
    &=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}\sum_{j=i-k}^{i+k}z^ig_j\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-(i-j)}{2}}
\end{align*}

Let's also make a comparison this time with (eq:diffusione-funzione-generatrice-definizione):

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^iW_i(k)=\sum_{i=-\infty}^{+\infty}z^i\sum_{j=i-k}^{i+k}g_j\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-(i-j)}{2}}
\end{equation*}

From which it follows that

\begin{equation}
    \boxed{W_i(k)=\sum_{j=i-k}^{i+k}g_j\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-(i-j)}{2}}}
\end{equation}

We note that by imposing $g_j=\delta_{j,i_0}$ we find exactly (eq:diffusione-distribuzione-finale):

\begin{align*}
    W_i(k)&=\sum_{j=i-k}^{i+k}\delta_{j,i_0}\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i-j}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-(i-j)}{2}}=\\
    &=\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-i_0}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+i-i_0}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-\left(i-i_0\right)}{2}}
\end{align*}

and this result is possible only if $i_0\in[i-k,i+k]$, or in other words if

\begin{equation*}
    i-k\leqslant i_0\leqslant i+k \ \Longrightarrow \ \
    \begin{cases}
        i-k\leqslant i_0\\
        i_0\leqslant i+k
    \end{cases}
    \iff \ \
    \begin{cases}
        i\leqslant k+i_0\\
        i\geqslant -k+i_0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}

that is $i\in[-k+i_0,k+i_0]$, since otherwise the contribution is not present in the summation and will therefore be $0$.


*Calculate the mean* $\mu(k)$ *and the variance* $\sigma(k)^2$ *directly from the distribution (eq:diffusione-distribuzione-finale*).

The mean $\mu(k)$, by definition, is given by

\begin{equation*}
    \mu(k)=\sum_{i}iW_i(k)=\sum_{i=-k+i_0}^{k+i_0}i\binom{k}{\frac{k+i-i_0}{2}}\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+\left(i-i_0\right)}{2}}\left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-\left(i-i_0\right)}{2}}
\end{equation*}

Let's go back to the starting index $n=\frac{k+i-i_0}{2}$:

\begin{align*}
    \mu(k)&=\sum_{n=0}^k\left(2n-k+i_0\right)\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}\\
    &=2\sum_{n=0}^kn\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}+\left(-k+i_0\right)\sum_{n=0}^k\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}
\end{align*}

The quantity $\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}$ is none other than a binomial distribution, which will therefore be normalized to $1$. The first summation will therefore be the mean relative to this distribution, equal to $kp_+$:

\begin{equation*}
    \mu(k)=2kp_+-k+i_0=k\left(2p_+-1\right)+i_0
\end{equation*}

Remembering that $1=p_++p_-$:

\begin{equation*}
    \mu(k)=k\left(2p_+-p_+-p_-\right)+i_0=k\left(p_+-p_-\right)+i_0
\end{equation*}

To determine the variance, we must first calculate the moment $\left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle$:
\[\begin{align*}
\left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle &= \sum_{i=-k+i_0}^{k+i_0} i^2 W_i(k)
= \sum_{i=-k+i_0}^{k+i_0} i^2 \binom{k}{\frac{k+i-i_0}{2}}
\left(p_+\right)^{\frac{k+(i-i_0)}{2}} \left(p_-\right)^{\frac{k-(i-i_0)}{2}} \\
&= \sum_{n=0}^k \left(2n-k+i_0\right)^2 \binom{k}{n} \left(p_+\right)^n \left(p_-\right)^{k-n}
\end{align*}\]
Let's separate the various contributions based on the powers of $n$, keeping in mind that the variance of a binomial is equal to $kp_+p_-$, and therefore

\begin{equation*}
    Var(n)=\mathbb{E}\left(n^2\right)-\mathbb{E}(n)^2 \ \iff \ \mathbb{E}\left(n^2\right)=Var(n)+\mathbb{E}(n)^2
\end{equation*}

We will have:

\begin{align*}
    n^2 \ \Longrightarrow \ \ &4\sum_{n=0}^kn^2\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}=4kp_+p_-+4k^2p_+^2\\
    n^1 \ \Longrightarrow \ \ &4\left(-k+i_0\right)\sum_{n=0}^kn\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}=4k\left(-k+i_0\right)p_+\\
    n^0 \ \Longrightarrow \ \ &\left(k^2-2ki_0+i_0^2\right)\sum_{n=0}^k\binom{k}{n}\left(p_+\right)^n\left(p_-\right)^{k-n}=k^2-2ki_0+i_0^2
\end{align*}

For simplicity, let's write the entire moment in the form of a polynomial in $k$:

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle=k^2\left(4p_+^2-4p_++1\right)+k\left(4p_+p_-+4p_+i_0-2i_0\right)+i_0^2
\end{equation*}

All we have to do is to expand $\mu(k)^2$, starting - for simplicity - from its exclusive form in $p_+$, that is, without the term $p_-$:

\begin{equation*}
    \mu(k)^2=k^2\left(4p_+^2-4p_++1\right)+k\left(4p_+i_0-2i_0\right)+i_0^2
\end{equation*}

We note that $\left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle$ and $\mu(k)^2$ are equal except for a term $4kp_+p_-$. The difference will therefore give

\begin{equation*}
    \sigma(k)^2=\left\langle i(k)^2\right\rangle-\mu(k)^2=4kp_+p_-
\end{equation*}

8.3 Wiener Process
We can now formalize the process underlying Brownian motion, called the Brownian process or Wiener process. It is a real-valued process in which \(T=\mathbb{R}^+\) and \(E=\mathbb{R}\) and whose sample path turns out to be a function of time \(B(t)\). For simplicity, we will only study the one-dimensional case.
This process must meet three criteria:
\(\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {1}}}}\) All trajectories at the initial time are at the origin of the reference system:
\[\begin{equation}
    B(0)=0
\end{equation}\]
\(\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}}\) For each pair of times \(\left(t_1,t_2\right)\), with \(t_2&gt;t_1\), the difference \(B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)\) is normally distributed as follows:
\[\begin{equation}
    B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,t_2-t_1\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}e^{-\frac{\Delta x^2}{2\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}
\end{equation}\]
where \(\Delta x\) is the increment of the stochastic process in the passage from a time \(t_1\) to a time \(t_2\).
\(\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {3}}}}\) For each pair of times \(\left(t_1,t_2\right)\), with \(t_2&gt;t_1\), the difference \(B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)\) is independent of any past value, that is, of \(B\left(t&lt;t_1\right)\).

8.3.1 Important Properties
Taking a time \(t=\bar{t}\) as a reference and considering the increment \(\bar{t}+\Delta t\), from criterion \(\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}}\) it follows:
\[\begin{equation}
    B\left(\bar{t}+\Delta t\right)-B\left(\bar{t}\right)\sim\mathcal{N}(0,\Delta t)
\end{equation}\]
This means that the increments are not only independent of each other, but they also do not depend on the moment in which the increment is considered, in the sense that they depend solely on the time difference \(\Delta t\): this property is called stationarity, because the distribution of the increments is invariant with respect to time translation.
Since this property is valid, then in particular for \(t=0\) it follows:
\[\begin{equation}
    B(0+\Delta t)-\cancel{B(0)}=B(\Delta t)\sim\mathcal{N}(0,\Delta t)
\end{equation}\]
If \(B(\Delta t)\) is distributed according to a normal distribution centered at zero with variance \(\Delta t\), then we can show that the expected value of its absolute value \(\abs{B(t)}\) is equal to the standard deviation, that is \(\sqrt{\Delta t}\). We will have in fact that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \langle\abs{B(\Delta t)}\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\abs{x}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\Delta t}}e^{-\frac{x^2}{2\Delta t}}dx=2\int_0^{+\infty}x\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\Delta t}}e^{-\frac{x^2}{2\Delta t}}dx
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s perform a change of variable to solve the integral:
\[\begin{equation*}
    y=\frac{x}{\sqrt{\Delta t}} \ \iff \ dx=\sqrt{\Delta t}dy
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{align*}
    \langle\abs{B}(\Delta t)\rangle&=2\int_0^{+\infty}y\sqrt{\Delta t}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\Delta t}}e^{-\frac{y^2}{2}}\sqrt{\Delta t}dy=2\sqrt{\Delta t}\int_0^{+\infty}y\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{y^2}{2}}dy=\\
    &=2\sqrt{\Delta t}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\left(-e^{-\frac{y^2}{2}}\right)\bigg|_0^{+\infty}=\sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}}\sqrt{\Delta t}
\end{align*}\]
We therefore find that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \langle\abs{B(\Delta t)}\rangle\sim\sqrt{\Delta t}
\end{equation*}\]
For \(\Delta t\to0^+\), that is, when the increments become very small, the average behavior is able to capture the global one, so we can state that
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\abs{B(\Delta t)}\sim\sqrt{\Delta t}}
\end{equation}\]
This last result will be useful in calculations that we will see later.
As we have already guessed, a realization of the Wiener process is nothing more than the fundamental solution of the diffusion equation in which \(D=1\). This solution, which corresponds to the propagator of the process, is in fact given by
\[\begin{equation*}
    w\left(x,t|x_0,t_0\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\left(t-t_0\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x-x_0\right)^2}{2\left(t-t_0\right)}}
\end{equation*}\]
which is precisely what is written in (eq:processi-stocastici-wiener-traiettoria).
By definition, the correlation function for two random variables is given by the expected value of their product, that is, by the covariance.
Considering two time instants \(t_1\) and \(t_2\), with \(t_1\leqslant t_2\), the correlation function will therefore be
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle B\left(t_1\right)B\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
To calculate the result, we add and subtract \(B\left(t_1\right)\) from \(B\left(t_2\right)\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle B\left(t_1\right)\left[B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)+B\left(t_1\right)\right]\right\rangle=\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)\left[B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)\right]\right\rangle+\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)^2\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
According to criterion \(\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {3}}}}\), the mean value of the product is nothing more than the product of the mean values:
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle B\left(t_1\right)\left[B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)\right]\right\rangle&=\left\langle\left[B\left(t_1\right)-B(0)\right]\left[B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)\right]\right\rangle=\\
    &=\left\langle\left[B\left(t_1\right)-B(0)\right]\right\rangle\left\langle\left[B\left(t_2\right)-B\left(t_1\right)\right]\right\rangle
\end{align*}\]
From criterion \(\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}}\), both expected values are zero, so what remains is:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle B\left(t_1\right)B\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)^2\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s add and subtract \(\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)\right\rangle^2\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle B\left(t_1\right)B\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)^2\right\rangle-\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)\right\rangle^2+\cancel{\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)\right\rangle}^2=Var\left[B\left(t_1\right)\right]=t_1
\end{equation*}\]
Without having to specify that \(t_1&lt;t_2\), the result in general is therefore given by
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\left\langle B\left(t_1\right)B\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)}
\end{equation}\]
This result means that, for a fixed time \(t_2\), the correlation is higher the closer \(t_1&lt;t_2\) is to \(t_2\), and conversely, the farther away \(t_1\) is, the lower the correlation.
From the other perspective, once \(t_1\) is fixed, the correlation with a future event is always equal and constant: in other words, a future event does not add any “information” to the ongoing process. This reflects nothing other than the property of incremental independence given by criterion \(\red{\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {3}}}}\).
The process described by
\[\begin{equation}
    z(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{c}}B(ct) \   \text{with} \ \ c\in\mathbb{R}^+
\end{equation}\]
is in turn the realization of a Wiener process, and as such it is distributed in the same way.
There are two ways to prove this result. The first, trivially, is to verify all the criteria that define Brownian motion:
Another way to prove it is through the use of the characteristic function: if we show that the characteristic function associated with one variable is equal to that associated with the other, then the two variables must necessarily follow the same distribution. In other words, we must show that
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle e^{i\lambda B(t)}\right\rangle=\left\langle e^{i\lambda z(t)}\right\rangle
\end{equation}\]
Let’s therefore calculate the characteristic function associated with \(B(t)\), which by definition is given by
\[\begin{align*}
    &\left\langle e^{i\lambda B(t)}\right\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{i\lambda x}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t}}e^{-\frac{x^2}{2t}}dx=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-\frac{x^2}{2t}+i\lambda x}dx=\\
    &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-\frac{1}{2t}\left(x^2-2i\lambda tx\right)}dx
\end{align*}\]
Let’s complete the square in the exponent:
\[\begin{equation*}
    x^2-2i\lambda tx=x^2-2i\lambda tx-\lambda^2t^2+\lambda^2t^2=\left(x-i\lambda t\right)^2-\lambda^2t^2
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s substitute:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle e^{i\lambda B(t)}\right\rangle=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-\frac{1}{2t}\left(x-i\lambda t\right)^2}e^{-\frac{\lambda^2t}{2}}dx=\frac{1}{\cancel{\sqrt{2\pi t}}}e^{-\frac{\lambda^2t}{2}}\cancel{\sqrt{2\pi t}}
\end{equation*}\]
We have thus found that
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\left\langle e^{i\lambda B(t)}\right\rangle=e^{-\frac{\lambda^2}{2}t}}
\end{equation}\]
At this point we can prove (eq:processi-stocastici-wiener-proprieta-riscalamento-funzioni-caratteristiche) simply by substitution:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle e^{i\lambda z(t)}\right\rangle=\left\langle e^{i\frac{\lambda}{\sqrt{c}}}B(ct)\right\rangle=e^{-\frac{\left(\frac{\lambda}{\sqrt{c}}\right)^2}{2}ct}=e^{-\frac{\lambda^2}{2c}ct}=e^{-\frac{\lambda^2}{2}t}
\end{equation*}\]
The process described by
\[\begin{equation}
    z(t)=
    \begin{cases}
        0 \ &t=0\\
        tB\left(\frac{1}{t}\right) \ &t&gt;0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
is in turn the realization of a Wiener process, and as such it is distributed in the same way.
We can proceed similarly to what we saw with rescaling, through the characteristic function:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle e^{i\lambda z(t)}\right\rangle=\left\langle e^{i\lambda tB(\frac{1}{t})}\right\rangle=e^{-\frac{\lambda^2t^2}{2}\frac{1}{t}}=e^{-\frac{\lambda^2}{2}t}
\end{equation*}\]
from which the thesis follows.
The process described by
\[\begin{equation}
    z(t)=B(T)-B(T-t) \   \text{with} \ \ t\in[0,T]
\end{equation}\]
is in turn the realization of a Wiener process, and as such it is distributed in the same way.
We can easily calculate the distribution followed by \(z(t)\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    z(t)=B(T)-B(T-t)\sim\mathcal{N}(0,T-(T-t))=\mathcal{N}(0,t)
\end{equation*}\]
It is a Gaussian with variance \(t\), whose characteristic function we know is given by (eq:integrali-gaussiani-funzione-caratteristica-gaussiana):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle e^{i\lambda z(t)}\right\rangle=e^{-\frac{\lambda^2}{2}t}
\end{equation*}\]
from which, once again, the thesis follows.

The Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process has as its trajectory the function


Solution. \[\begin{equation*}
        V(t)=e^{-t}B\left(e^{2t}\right)
    \end{equation*}\]
*where* $B(t)$ *is the trajectory associated with Brownian motion. Show that*

\begin{align*}
    &\langle V(t)\rangle=0\\
    &\left\langle V\left(t_1\right)V\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=e^{-\abs{t_1-t_2}}
\end{align*}

We recall that $B(t)\sim\mathcal{N}(0,t)$, therefore

\begin{equation*}
    B\left(e^{2t}\right)\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,e^{2t}\right) \ \Longrightarrow \ \left\langle B\left(e^{2t}\right)\right\rangle=0
\end{equation*}

It therefore follows that

\begin{equation*}
    \langle V(t)\rangle=\left\langle e^{-t}B\left(e^{2t}\right)\right\rangle=e^{-t}\left\langle B\left(e^{2t}\right)\right\rangle=e^{-t}\cdot0=0
\end{equation*}

Let's now move on to the correlation function:

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle V\left(t_1\right)V\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\left\langle e^{-t_1}B\left(e^{2t_1}\right)e^{-t_2}B\left(e^{2t_2}\right)\right\rangle=e^{-t_1-t_2}\left\langle B\left(e^{2t_1}\right)B\left(e^{2t_2}\right)\right\rangle
\end{equation*}

The correlation function for Brownian motion is given by (eq:processi-stocastici-wiener-funzione-correlazione):

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle V\left(t_1\right)V\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=e^{-t_1-t_2}\min\left(e^{2t_1},e^{2t_2}\right)
\end{equation*}

