8.3.3 Simulation of a Brownian Motion
To simulate a stochastic realization of a Brownian motion, we must put together the three criteria useful for defining the Wiener process. The second criterion, in particular, is what allows us to define an iterative formula to obtain new values of the trajectory:
\[\begin{equation*}
    B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\sim\mathcal{N}(0,\Delta t)=\sqrt{\Delta t}\mathcal{N}(0,1)
\end{equation*}\]
Indicating with \(\zeta_i\) a random variable drawn from a standard Gaussian distribution, the iterative formula necessary to simulate a Brownian motion in one dimension is the following:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\begin{cases}
        B\left(t_0\right)=0\\
        B\left(t_i\right)=B\left(t_{i-1}\right)+\sqrt{\Delta t}\zeta_i
    \end{cases}}
\end{equation}\]
assuming that \(t_0=0\).
We can generalize the motion by adding three elements:
The transformation to follow is the following:
\[\begin{equation}
    x(t)=x_0+\mu t+\sqrt{2D}B(t)
\end{equation}\]
where \(x_0\) is the starting point, \(\mu\) is the drift coefficient, and \(D\) is the diffusion coefficient.
We can easily verify that the mean and variance correspond to what we predicted:
\[\begin{align*}
    &\langle x(t)\rangle=\left\langle x_0+\mu t+\sqrt{2D}B(t)\right\rangle=x_0+\mu t+\sqrt{2D}\cancel{\langle B(t)\rangle}=x_0+\mu t\\
    &Var[x(t)]=Var\left[x_0+\mu t+\sqrt{2D}B(t)\right]=2DVar[B(t)]=2Dt
\end{align*}\]
Furthermore, by differentiating on the left and on the right, we find the following stochastic differential equation satisfied by \(x(t)\):
\[\begin{equation}
    dx(t)=\mu dt+\sqrt{2D}dB(t)
\end{equation}\]
Finally, the iterative formula useful for simulating the trajectory is
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\begin{cases}
        x\left(t_0\right)=x_0\\
        x\left(t_i\right)=x\left(t_{i-1}\right)+\mu\Delta t+\sqrt{2D\Delta t}\zeta_i
    \end{cases}}
\end{equation}\]

8.4 Markov Process
From the last paragraph, we have had the opportunity to note how a stochastic process - in this case, that of Wiener - can be understood in an iterative form through the random extraction of new points from a probability distribution; in particular, each new element depends directly on the one immediately preceding it at the temporal level: processes of this type are called Markov processes, and later we will rigorously prove that Brownian motions are part of this category of processes.
At this point, it is useful to introduce conditional probabilities, that is, those types of probabilities explicitly dependent on other realizations that have already occurred. Referring to stochastic processes, and therefore to events ordered in time, the previous realizations are nothing more than the points \(x_i\) obtained at times \(t_i\). In general, the conditional probability of the \(n\)-th point \(x_n\) at time \(t_n\) is indicated as
\[\begin{equation}
    p_{1|n-1}\left(x_n,t_n|x_{n-1},t_{n-1};x_{n-2},t_{n-2};\dots;x_{1},t_1;x_0,t_0\right)
\end{equation}\]
where the subscript indicates that the probability associated with an element depends on \(n-1\) other elements.
A Markov process is said to be such if
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p_{1|n-1}\left(x_n,t_n|x_{n-1},t_{n-1};\dots;x_0,t_0\right)=p_{1|1}\left(x_n,t_n|x_{n-1},t_{n-1}\right)}
\end{equation}\]
In other words, the prediction at time \(t_n\) depends only and solely on what happened at time \(t_{n-1}\), and therefore the information is exhausted at the next time step. The pdf \(p_{1|1}\) is called the propagator or transition probability.
We can easily show that a Markov process depends entirely on the propagator \(p_{1|1}\) and the initial distribution \(p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)\). The joint distribution relative to \(\left(x_0,t_0\right)\) and \(\left(x_1,t_1\right)\), for example, is given by
\[\begin{equation*}
    p_2\left(x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)=p_{1|1}\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
For the joint distribution at three points we will have:
\[\begin{align*}
    p_3\left(x_2,t_2;x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)&=p_{1|2}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)p_2\left(x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)=\\
    &=p_{1|2}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)p_{1|1}\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)
\end{align*}\]
Since it is a Markov process:
\[\begin{equation*}
    p_{1|2}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)=p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Substituting:
\[\begin{equation*}
    p_3\left(x_2,t_2;x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)=p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)p_{1|1}\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Repeating the same reasoning for the joint distribution at \(n\) points we will have:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p_n\left(x_n,t_n;\dots;x_0,t_0\right)=p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)\prod_{i=1}^np_{1|1}\left(x_i,t_i|x_{i-1},t_{i-1}\right)}
\end{equation}\]
We thus understand that to define a Markov process, only two quantities are needed: the initial distribution \(p_1\) and the propagator \(p_{1|1}\).

8.4.1 Stationary Markov Processes
A particular type of Markov processes are stationary Markov processes, which occur if two conditions are met:
Stationarity implies an invariance under time translations, a property that reflects the condition of equilibrium in which the system is found. Furthermore, since the initial distribution does not depend on time, it coincides exactly with the equilibrium distribution of the entire stochastic process.


8.4.2 Chapman-Kolmogorov Equation
It is important to clarify that not all functions can be chosen as propagators of a Markov process, just as not all distributions are permissible as initial distributions. We will see below, in fact, how both these quantities must verify two important identities.
For the first identity, let’s go back to the joint distribution at three points; by integrating it with respect to the variable \(x_1\), we will eliminate the dependence on \(x_1\) and \(t_1\), as we are averaging over all possible values that \(x_1\) can assume at time \(t_1\)
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_{\mathbb{R}}p_3\left(x_2,t_2;x_1,t_1;x_0,t_0\right)dx_1=p_2\left(x_2,t_2;x_0,t_0\right)=p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_0,t_0\right)p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Writing the joint distribution at three points through the Markov property:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)p_{1|1}\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)\cancel{p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)}dx_1=p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_0,t_0\right)\cancel{p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)}
\end{equation*}\]
This means that, in general, for any triplet of times \(\left(t_0,t_1,t_2\right)\) such that \(t_0&lt;t_1&lt;t_2\), the propagator satisfies the following relation, called the Chapman-Kolmogorov equation:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_0,t_0\right)=\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)p_{1|1}\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)dx_1}
\end{equation}\]
This is the first relation that must be satisfied by a propagator in order to define a Markov process. The second relation, as anticipated, concerns the initial distribution, and is actually the equation that links it to the propagator itself. To find it, it is necessary to multiply both sides of (eq:processi-stocastici-equazione-di-chapman-kolmogorov) by the initial distribution and integrate with respect to \(x_0\); the first member will give:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_0,t_0\right)p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)dx_0=p_1\left(x_2,t_2\right)
\end{equation*}\]
The second member, instead:
\[\begin{align*}
    &\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)p_1\left(x_0,t_0\right)dx_0dx_1=\\
    &=\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)p_1\left(x_1,t_1\right)dx_1
\end{align*}\]
Putting the two parts together, it results:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p_1\left(x_2,t_2\right)=\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)p_1\left(x_1,t_1\right)dx_1}
\end{equation}\]
It can be rigorously proven that given two non-negative functions \(p_1\) and \(p_{1|1}\) that satisfy (eq:processi-stocastici-equazione-di-chapman-kolmogorov) and (eq:processi-stocastici-relazione-distribuzione-iniziale-propagatore) define a Markov process.


8.4.3 Brownian Motion is a Markov Process
Having defined the mathematical criteria that define a Markov process, we can now demonstrate that Brownian motion is part of this category.
We recall that the propagator of Brownian motion is given by
\[\begin{equation*}
    w\left(x,t|x_0,t_0\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D\left(t-t_0\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x-x_0\right)^2}{4D\left(t-t_0\right)}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s try to prove (eq:processi-stocastici-equazione-di-chapman-kolmogorov):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x_2-x_1\right)^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}\cdot\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D\left(t_1-t_0\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x_1-x_0\right)^2}{4D\left(t_1-t_0\right)}}dx_1
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s focus for now on the exponent of \(e\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    -\frac{\left(x_2-x_1\right)^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}-\frac{\left(x_1-x_0\right)^2}{4D\left(t_1-t_0\right)}=-\frac{x_2^2-2x_1x_2+x_1^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}-\frac{x_1^2-2x_0x_1+x_0^2}{4D\left(t_1-t_0\right)}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s rewrite the exponent in the form of a second-degree polynomial in \(x_1\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    -\frac{1}{4D}\left(\frac{1}{t_2-t_1}+\frac{1}{t_1-t_0}\right)x_1^2+\frac{1}{2D}\left(\frac{x_2}{t_2-t_1}+\frac{x_0}{t_1-t_0}\right)x_1-\frac{x_2^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}-\frac{x_0^2}{4D\left(t_1-t_0\right)}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s set
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        A=\frac{1}{4D}\left(\frac{1}{t_2-t_1}+\frac{1}{t_1-t_0}\right)=\frac{t_2-t_0}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}\\
        B=\frac{1}{2D}\left(\frac{x_2}{t_2-t_1}+\frac{x_0}{t_1-t_0}\right)=\frac{\left(t_1-t_0\right)x_2+\left(t_2-t_1\right)x_0}{2D\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}\\
        C=-\frac{x_2^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}-\frac{x_0^2}{4D\left(t_1-t_0\right)}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
so that we can rewrite the integral as:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{1}{4\pi D\sqrt{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-Ax_1^2+Bx_1+C}dx_1
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s complete the square in the exponent:
\[\begin{align*}
    -Ax_1^2+Bx_1+C&=-A\left[x_1^2-\frac{B}{A}x_1\right]+C=\\
    &=-A\left[x_1^2-\frac{B}{A}x_1+\frac{B^2}{4A^2}-\frac{B^2}{4A^2}\right]+C=\\
    &=-A\left(x_1-\frac{B}{2A}\right)^2+\frac{B^2}{4A}+C
\end{align*}\]
Substituting in the integral:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{e^{\frac{B^2}{4A}+C}}{4\pi D\sqrt{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-A\left(x_1-\frac{B}{2A}\right)^2}dx_1=\frac{e^{\frac{B^2}{4A}+C}}{4\pi D\sqrt{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}}\cdot\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{A}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s ignore the exponent for the moment and make the multiplying factor explicit:
\[\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{4\pi D}\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)A}}=\frac{1}{4\pi D}\sqrt{\frac{4\pi D\cancel{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}}{\left(t_2-t_0\right)\cancel{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D\left(t_2-t_0\right)}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s now move on to the exponential and focus on the exponent of \(e\); let’s start first from the term \(\frac{B^2}{4A}\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{\left(t_1-t_0\right)^2x_2^2+2\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)x_2x_0+\left(t_2-t_1\right)^2x_0^2}{4D^2\left(t_2-t_1\right)^2\left(t_1-t_0\right)^2}\cdot\frac{1}{4}\frac{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}{t_2-t_0}
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{\left(t_1-t_0\right)^2x_2^2+2\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)x_2x_0+\left(t_2-t_1\right)^2x_0^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)\left(t_2-t_0\right)}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s now add \(C\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{\left(t_1-t_0\right)^2x_2^2+2\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)x_2x_0+\left(t_2-t_1\right)^2x_0^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)\left(t_2-t_0\right)}-\frac{x_2^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}-\frac{x_0^2}{4D\left(t_1-t_0\right)}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s calculate the terms in the numerator in \(x_2^2\) and in \(x_0^2\)
\[\begin{align*}
    &\left(t_1-t_0\right)^2x_2^2-\left(t_1-t_0\right)\left(t_2-t_0\right)x_2^2=\left[t_1-t_0-t_2+t_0\right]\left(t_1-t_0\right)x_2^2=-(t_2-t_1)(t_1-t_0)x_2^2\\
    &\left(t_2-t_1\right)^2x_0^2-\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_2-t_0\right)x_0^2=\left[t_2-t_1-t_2+t_0\right]\left(t_2-t_1\right)x_0^2=-(t_1-t_0)(t_2-t_1)x_0^2
\end{align*}\]
From which we find the expression for \(\frac{B^2}{4A}+C\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{-\cancel{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}x_2^2+2\cancel{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}x_2x_0-\cancel{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}x_0^2}{4D\cancel{\left(t_2-t_1\right)\left(t_1-t_0\right)}\left(t_2-t_0\right)}
\end{equation*}\]
Ultimately, we have shown that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_{\mathbb{R}}w\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)w\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)dx_1=\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D\left(t_2-t_0\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x_2-x_0\right)^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_0\right)}}=w\left(x_2,t_2|x_0,t_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
which corresponds precisely to the Chapman-Kolmogorov equation.
Let’s now move on to the proof of (eq:processi-stocastici-relazione-distribuzione-iniziale-propagatore); we recall that the initial distribution of Brownian motion is a Dirac delta centered at \(0\), so substituting:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x_2-x_1\right)^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}\delta\left(x_1-x_0\right)dx_1=\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x_2-x_0\right)^2}{4D\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}
\end{equation*}\]
Having assumed the distribution associated with \(x_1\) as the initial one, then necessarily \(t_1=t_0\), from which it follows that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi D(t_2-t_0)}}e^{-\frac{(x_2-x_0)^2}{4D(t_2-t_0)}}=w\left(x_2,t_2|x_0,t_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
which is precisely the distribution with respect to the initial point. We note how, since \(p_1\left(x_2,t_2\right)\) explicitly depends on \(t_2\), it is a non-stationary Markov process.

9.1 Wiener measure
The Chapman-Kolmogorov equation can be easily iterated by considering more intermediate points. For example, the propagator from \(\left(x_0,t_0\right)\) to \(\left(x_3,t_3\right)\) can be written as:
\[\begin{align*}
    p_{1|1}\left(x_3,t_3|x_0,t_0\right)&=\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_3,t_3|x_2,t_2\right)p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_0,t_0\right)dx_2=\\
    &=\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_3,t_3|x_2,t_2\right)\int_{\mathbb{R}}p_{1|1}\left(x_2,t_2|x_1,t_1\right)p_{1|1}\left(x_1,t_1|x_0,t_0\right)dx_1dx_2
\end{align*}\]
To extend to a generic number \(n\) of points, we formally introduce what is called the Wiener measure, expressed by the following differential:
\[\begin{equation}
    d\mathbb{P}_{t_1,\dots,t_n}\left(x_1,\dots,x_n|x_0,t_0\right)=\prod_{i=1}^nw\left(x_i,t_i|x_{i-1},t_{i-1}\right)dx_i
\end{equation}\]
The integration of this quantity can be interpreted as the calculation of the joint probability of finding the particle in an area \(A_1\) at time \(t_1\), in an area \(A_2\supseteq A_1\) at time \(t_2\) and so on:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \mathbb{P}=\int_{A_1}\int_{A_2}\dots\int_{A_n} d\mathbb{P}_{t_1,\dots,t_n}\left(x_1,\dots,x_n|x_0,t_0\right)dx_1dx_2\dots dx_n
\end{equation*}\]



Example of a stochastic process in which the time domain is divided into progressively increasing areas


Returning to the definition of the Wiener measure, putting together (eq:integrali-sui-cammini-misura-di-wiener-introduzione) and (eq:diffusione-soluzione-istante-di-tempo-iniziale-t0) we obtain the following expression:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{d\mathbb{P}_{t_1,\dots,t_n}\left(x_1,\dots,x_n|x_0,t_0\right)=\frac{1}{(2\pi D)^{\frac{n}{2}}}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\sum\limits_{i=1}^n\frac{\Delta x_i^2}{\Delta t_i}}\prod_{i=1}^n\frac{dx_i}{\sqrt{\Delta t_i}}}
\end{equation}\]
being \(\Delta x_i=x_i-x_{i-1}\) and \(\Delta t_i=t_i-t_{i-1}\).

9.1.1 Two-point correlation function
We can apply what has been written for the calculation of the two-point correlation function \(\left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle\); assuming that the random variable \(x(t)\) is relative to a Brownian process that starts at \(x\left(t_0\right)=x_0\), in fact, we will write:
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle&=\int_{\mathbb{R}}\int_{\mathbb{R}}x_1x_2d\mathbb{P}_{t_1,t_2}\left(x_1,x_2|x_0,t_0\right)=\\
    &=\frac{1}{2\pi D}\int_{\mathbb{R}}
    \int_{\mathbb{R}}\frac{x_1x_2}{\sqrt{\left(t_1-t_0\right)\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\left[\frac{\left(x_1-x_0\right)^2}{t_1-t_0}+\frac{\left(x_2-x_1\right)^2}{t_2-t_1}\right]}dx_1dx_2
\end{align*}\]
To find the solution, let’s change the variables in the following way:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x=x_1-x_0\\
        y=x_2-x_1
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow \
    \begin{cases}
        x_1=x+x_0\\
        x_2=y+x_1=y+x+x_0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\] \end{equation*}
To make the substitution we must also insert the determinant of the Jacobian:
\[\begin{equation*}
    J=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        \frac{\partial x_1}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial x_1}{\partial y}\\
        \frac{\partial x_2}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial x_2}{\partial y}
    \end{pmatrix}
    =
    \begin{pmatrix}
        1 & 0\\
        1 & 1
    \end{pmatrix}
    \ \Longrightarrow \ \det(J)=1
\end{equation*}\]
From which:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\frac{1}{2\pi D}\int_{\mathbb{R}}
    \int_{\mathbb{R}}\frac{\left(x+x_0\right)\left(x+y+x_0\right)}{\sqrt{\left(t_1-t_0\right)\left(t_2-t_1\right)}}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\left[\frac{x^2}{t_1-t_0}+\frac{y^2}{t_2-t_1}\right]}dxdy
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s focus on the numerator of the fraction of the integrand function:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left(x+x_0\right)\left(x+y+x_0\right)=x^2+xy+x_0x+x_0x+x_0y+x_0^2
\end{equation*}\]
The exponential function is an even function, so any odd term will give a null contribution. The only non-odd terms are \(x_2\) and \(x_0^2\), whose contributions we can easily calculate:
We therefore find:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=D\left(t_1-t_0\right)+x_0^2}
\end{equation}\]
which is exactly what was obtained in equation (eq:diffusione-valor-medio-variabile-al-quadrato), having assumed here \(v=0\).

*Calculate the two-point correlation function for a Wiener process with a generic initial distribution* $g\left(x_0\right)$.

To include the uncertainty on the initial position, distributed according to $g\left(x_0\right)$, it is necessary to average the correlation function with respect to this quantity:

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\int_{\mathbb{R}}g\left(x_0\right)\int_{\mathbb{R}}\int_{\mathbb{R}}x_1x_2d\mathbb{P}_{t_1,t_2}\left(x_1,x_2|x_0,t_0\right)dx_0
\end{equation*}

The calculations will therefore proceed in the same way as they were carried out in the paragraph. The only difference is given by the contribution due to the term $x_0^2$, which instead of giving $x_0^2$ will give $\left\langle x_0^2\right\rangle_g$. It will therefore result:

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=D\left(t_1-t_0\right)+\left\langle x_0^2\right\rangle_g
\end{equation*}

9.2 Wiener path integral
It is interesting to note how the formula for the differential obtained in (eq:integrali-sui-cammini-misura-di-wiener-differenziale) can be expressed in the limit for \(n\to\infty\), keeping in mind a couple of precautions.
First of all, it is necessary to set a maximum time \(T\) within which the process is considered to be evolving. Increasing the number of intervals \(\Delta t_i\), therefore, means decreasing the width of each of them, being
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\Delta t_i=T
\end{equation*}\]
Passing from a discrete to a continuous domain, we expect each single interval to converge to zero. We can formally guarantee this by assuming that the largest interval goes to zero in the limit, since, if this is the behavior of the largest interval, this will also apply to all the other intervals:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \lim_{n\to\infty}\max\left(\Delta t_i\right)=0
\end{equation*}\]



Examples of Riemann sums


Having made these premises, we can actually study the behavior at the limit. Let’s first understand how the exponent transforms:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\frac{\Delta x_i^2}{\Delta t_i}=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(\frac{\Delta x_i}{\Delta t_i}\right)^2\Delta t_i
\end{equation*}\]
What is written is none other than the Riemann sum for the derivative of \(x(t)\), that is, a type of numerical integration as shown in figure (fig:somma-di-riemann). It follows that, in the limit for \(n\to\infty\), it results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\left(\frac{\Delta x_i}{\Delta t_i}\right)^2\Delta t_i\to\int_0^T\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2dt
\end{equation*}\]
Considering a normalization constant \(N\), equation (eq:integrali-sui-cammini-misura-di-wiener-differenziale) becomes:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{d\mathbb{P}_W=Ne^{-\frac{1}{2D}\int_0^T\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2dt}\prod_{\tau=0^+}^Tdx(\tau)}
\end{equation}\]
The integration of any functional using this differential is called the Wiener path integral, as each possible trajectory - or , precisely - contributes with a certain weight to the overall calculation, since not all trajectories have the same probability of being realized.
It should be borne in mind that the formula written above is only formal and has no real meaning in itself: we note in fact that the function \(x(t)\) is by definition not differentiable at any point, since each point of the trajectory is randomly extracted from a distribution in the vicinity of the previous point, and therefore a trajectory is not followed. In practice - as we will see in the following example - the calculation is performed in discrete form starting from the differential associated with the Wiener measure, and only at the end is the limit for \(n\to\infty\) evaluated.

9.2.1 Mean of a functional of the trajectory
Our goal is to calculate the expected value of the following functional:
\[\begin{equation*}
    F\left(\int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt\right)
\end{equation*}\]
where \(x(t)\) is the sample trajectory of a Brownian motion, while \(a(t)\) and \(F\) are two smooth functions, that is, belonging to \(C^{\infty}\).
As anticipated, we will work with the discrete form of the expression, going to the limit only at the end of the calculation. The object of the function \(F\), therefore, will pass to
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt \ \longrightarrow \ \sum_{i=1}^nx_ia_i\Delta t_i
\end{equation*}\]
In the calculation that we will face, we will have to reduce to a Gaussian integral, and to do this we will need to make the interval \(\Delta x_i\) explicit. Let’s therefore rewrite the integral in \(dt\) by parts, choosing \(a(t)\) as the function to integrate
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt=x(t)\int_T^ta(t')dt'\bigg|_{t=0}^{t=T}-\int_0^T\frac{dx}{dt}\left(\int_T^ta(t')dt'\right)dt
\end{equation*}\]
having written the integral of \(a(t)\) in the form \(\int_\alpha^ta(t')dt'\) with \(\alpha=T\).
The first term on the right-hand side is zero, since:
\[\begin{equation*}
    x(t)\int_T^ta(t')dt'\bigg|_{t=0}^{t=T}=x(T)\cancel{\int_T^Ta(t')dt'}-\cancel{x(0)}\int_T^0a(t')dt'=0
\end{equation*}\]
By inverting the limits of the inner integral of the second term, therefore, it results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt=\int_0^T\frac{dx}{dt}\left(\int_t^Ta(t')dt'\right)dt
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s set:
\[\begin{equation*}
    A(t)=\int_t^Ta(t')dt' \ \Longrightarrow \ \int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt=\int_0^TA(t)\frac{dx}{dt}dt
\end{equation*}\]
We thus obtain the differential \(dx\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt=\int_0^TA(t)dx
\end{equation}\]
We can now move on to the discretization we need:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^TA(t)dx \ \longrightarrow \ \sum_{i=1}^nA_i\Delta x_i
\end{equation*}\]
We can now proceed with the calculations; indicating the mean of the discretized functional as \(\left\langle F_n\right\rangle\), we will use the Wiener measure to write:
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle F_n\right\rangle=\frac{1}{\left(2\pi D\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}}\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\sum\limits_{i=1}^n\frac{\Delta x_i^2}{\Delta t_i}}\prod_{i=1}^n\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Delta t_i}}F\left(\sum_{j=1}^nA_j\Delta x_j\right)dx_i
\end{equation}\]
Let’s perform the following change of variables:
\[\begin{equation*}
    y_i=\Delta x_i=x_i-x_{i-1}
\end{equation*}\]
From which it follows:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        y_1=x_1-x_0\\
        y_2=x_2-x_1\\
        y_3=x_3-x_2\\
        \vdots
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow \
    \begin{cases}
        x_1=x_0+y_1\\
        x_2=x_1+y_2=x_0+y_1+y_2\\
        x_3=x_2+y_3=x_0+y_1+y_2+y_3\\
        \vdots
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\] \end{equation*}
We can easily calculate the Jacobian:
\[\begin{equation*}
    J=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        \frac{\partial x_1}{\partial y_1} & \frac{\partial x_1}{\partial y_2} & \dots & \frac{\partial x_1}{\partial y_n}\\
        \frac{\partial x_2}{\partial y_1} & \frac{\partial x_2}{\partial y_2} & \dots & \frac{\partial x_2}{\partial y_n}\\
        \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
        \frac{\partial x_n}{\partial y_1} & \frac{\partial x_n}{\partial y_2} & \dots & \frac{\partial x_n}{\partial y_n}
    \end{pmatrix}
    =
    \begin{pmatrix}
        1 & 0 & \dots & 0\\
        1 & 1 & \dots & 0\\
        \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
        1 & 1 & \dots & 1
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{equation*}\]
This is a lower triangular matrix that has as its determinant the product of the elements on the main diagonal, equal to \(1\). Since \(\det(J)=1\), the integral will result
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle F_n\right\rangle=\frac{1}{(2\pi D)^{\frac{n}{2}}}\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\sum\limits_{i=1}^n\frac{y_i^2}{\Delta t_i}}\prod_{i=1}^n\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Delta t_i}}F\left(\sum_{j=1}^nA_jy_j\right)dy_i
\end{equation}\]
Since the variables \(y_i\) are inside the functional, which can have a generic form, the integral is not so directly solvable. Through a trick, however, we can write the dependence on \(y_i\) in exponential form; first of all, we can write the exponential through the Dirac delta in the following way:
\[\begin{equation*}
    F\left(\sum_{j=1}^nA_jy_j\right)=\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\delta\left(z-\sum_{j=1}^nA_jy_j\right)dz
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s recall the explicit form of the Dirac delta:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \delta(z)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{ixz}dx \ \Longrightarrow \ F\left(\sum_{j=1}^nA_jy_j\right)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{ix\left(z-\sum\limits_{j=1}^nA_jy_j\right)}dxdz
\end{equation*}\]
Substituting in (eq:integrali-sui-cammini-media-funzionale-calcolo-1):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle F_n\right\rangle=\frac{1}{2\pi(2\pi D)^{\frac{n}{2}}}\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\sum\limits_{i=1}^n\frac{y_i^2}{\Delta t_i}}\prod_{i=1}^n\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Delta t_i}}\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{ix\left(z-\sum\limits_{j=1}^nA_jy_j\right)}dxdzdy_i
\end{equation*}\]
Since the domains of the integrals are compatible with each other, we can exchange their order and move the terms inside as we please:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle F_n\right\rangle=\frac{1}{2\pi(2\pi D)^{\frac{n}{2}}}\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{ixz}\prod_{i=1}^n\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Delta t_i}}\red{\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\sum\limits_{j=1}^n\left(\frac{y_j^2}{\Delta t_j}+2iDxA_jy_j\right)}dy_j}dxdz
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s solve the innermost integral highlighted in red:
\[\begin{align*}
    \int_{\mathbb{R}^n}e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\sum\limits_{j=1}^n\left(\frac{y_j^2}{\Delta t_j}+2iDxA_jy_j\right)}dy_j&=\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}\prod_{j=1}^ne^{-\frac{1}{2D}\left(\frac{y_j^2}{\Delta t_j}+2iDxA_jy_j\right)}dy_j=\\
    &=\prod_{j=1}^n\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}e^{-\frac{y_j^2}{2D\Delta t_j}-ixA_jy_j}dy_j=\\
    &=\prod_{j=1}^n\sqrt{2\pi D\Delta t_j}e^{-\frac{1}{2}Dx^2A_j^2\Delta t_j}=\\
    &=(2\pi D)^{\frac{n}{2}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}Dx^2\sum\limits_{i=1}^nA_i^2\Delta t_i}\prod_{j=1}^n\sqrt{\Delta t_j}
\end{align*}\]
Substituting in the starting expression, the factor \(\frac{1}{(2\pi D)^{\frac{n}{2}}}\) will be simplified, as well as \(\prod\limits_{i=1}^n\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Delta t_i}}\). What remains is:
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle F_n\right\rangle&=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{ixz}e^{-\frac{1}{2}Dx^2\sum\limits_{i=1}^nA_i^2\Delta t_i}dxdz=\\
    &=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}D\left(\sum\limits_{i=1}^nA_i^2\Delta t_i\right)x^2+izx}dxdz
\end{align*}\]
The innermost integral in \(x\) is another Gaussian integral that we know how to solve. Setting \(\gamma_n=\sum\limits_{i=1}^nA_i^2\Delta t_i\) it results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle F_n\right\rangle=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{D\gamma_n}}e^{-\frac{z^2}{2D\gamma_n}}dz=\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi D\gamma_n}}e^{-\frac{z^2}{2D\gamma_n}}dz
\end{equation*}\]
Inside the integral we find a Gaussian distribution in the variable \(z\) centered at zero and with variance \(D\gamma_n\), which we can indicate with \(\mathcal{N}_z\left(0,D\gamma_n\right)\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle F_z\right\rangle=\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\mathcal{N}_z\left(0,D\gamma_n\right)dz
\end{equation}\]
This is the moment to calculate the limit, passing from the discrete to the continuous domain. The only explicitly discrete element is \(\gamma_n\) due to its definition, so we will only have to calculate its value at the limit:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \gamma_n=\sum_{i=1}^nA_i^2\Delta t_i \ \xrightarrow{n\to\infty} \ \int_0^TA(t)^2dt=\int_0^T\left(\int_t^Ta(t')dt'\right)^2dt
\end{equation*}\]
The final result is therefore the following:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\left\langle F\left(\int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt\right)\right\rangle_{BM}=\int_{\mathbb{R}}F(z)\mathcal{N}_z(0,DR(T))dz}
\end{equation}\]
having set
\[\begin{equation}
    R(T)=\int_0^T\left(\int_t^Ta(t')dt'\right)^2dt
\end{equation}\]
With \(F(z)=e^{hz}\) we obtain the moment generating function \(\phi(h)\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \varphi(h)\equiv\left\langle e^{h\int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt}\right\rangle_{BM}=\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{hz}\mathcal{N}_z(0,DR(T))dz
\end{equation}\]
By deriving \(n\) times with respect to \(h\), in fact, we have
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d^n\varphi}{dh^n}=\int_{\mathbb{R}}z^ne^{hz}\mathcal{N}_z(0,DR(T))dz
\end{equation*}\]
By calculating the derivative at \(h=0\) we find precisely the \(n\)-th order moment:
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{d^n\varphi}{dh^n}\bigg|_{h=0}=\int_{\mathbb{R}}z^n\mathcal{N}_z(0,DR(t))dz=\left\langle z^n\right\rangle
\end{equation}\]
Let’s therefore perform the calculation directly starting from (eq:integrali-sui-cammini-funzione-di-generazione-dei-momenti):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \varphi(h)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi DR(T)}}\int_{\mathbb{R}}e^{-\frac{z^2}{2DR(T)}+hz}=\frac{1}{\cancel{\sqrt{2\pi DR(T)}}}\cdot\cancel{\sqrt{2\pi DR(T)}}e^{\frac{h^2DR(T)}{2}}
\end{equation*}\]
From which:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\varphi(h)=e^{\frac{1}{2}DR(T)h^2}}
\end{equation}\]

Choosing \(F(z)=e^z\) and \(a(t)=h_1\delta\left(t_1-t\right)+h_2\delta\left(t_2-t\right)\), calculate the following quantities:


Solution. 
\begin{enumerate}
    \item By definition:

    \begin{equation*}
        A(t)=\int_t^Ta(t')dt'=h_1\int_t^T\delta\left(t_1-t'\right)dt'+h_2\int_t^T\delta\left(t_2-t'\right)dt'
    \end{equation*}

    Assuming that $t_1&lt;t_2$, we distinguish three cases:

    \begin{itemize}
        \item When $t\leqslant t_1$, both $t_1$ and $t_2$ belong to the interval $[t,T]$, so both integrals are non-zero.
        \item When $t_1&lt;t\leqslant t_2$, only $t_2$ belongs to the interval $[t,T]$, so the delta with $t_1$ will be zero.
        \item When $t&gt;t_2$, neither $t_1$ nor $t_2$ belong to the interval $[t,T]$, so both integrals are zero.
    \end{itemize}

    To summarize:

    \begin{equation*}
        A(t)=
        \begin{cases}
            h_1+h_2 \ &t\in[0,t_1]\\
            h_2 \ &t\in(t_1,t_2]\\
            0 \ &t\in(t_2,T]
        \end{cases}
    \end{equation*}

    \item Again, by definition:

    \begin{align*}
        R(T)&=\int_0^TA(t)^2dt=\int_0^{t_1}\left(h_1+h_2\right)^2dt+\int_{t_1}^{t_2}h_2^2dt+\int_{t_2}^T0dt=\\
        &=\left(h_1+h_2\right)^2t_1+h_2^2\left(t_2-t_1\right)=\\
        &=h_1^2t_1+2h_1h_2t_1\cancel{+h_2^2t_1}+h_2^2t_2\cancel{-h_2^2t_1}=\\
        &=t_1h_1^2+2t_1h_1h_2+t_2h_2^2
    \end{align*}

    \item Since $F(z)=e^z$, we can take up the formula (eq:integrali-sui-cammini-funzione-di-generazione-dei-momenti-finale) with $h=1$:

    \begin{equation*}
        \varphi\left(h_1,h_2\right)=e^{\frac{1}{2}DR(T)}=e^{\frac{1}{2}D\left(t_1h_1^2+2t_1h_1h_2+t_2h_2^2\right)}
    \end{equation*}

    Let's proceed with the derivatives:

    \begin{equation*}
        \frac{\partial\varphi}{\partial h_2}=\frac{1}{2}D\left(2t_1h_1+2t_2h_2\right)\varphi\left(h_1,h_2\right)=D\left(t_1h_1+t_2h_2\right)\varphi\left(h_1,h_2\right)
    \end{equation*}

    \small

    \begin{equation*}
        \frac{\partial^2\varphi}{\partial h_1\partial h_2}=Dt_1\varphi\left(h_1,h_2\right)+D\left(t_1h_1+t_2h_2\right)\cdot\frac{1}{2}D\left(2t_1h_1+2t_1h_2\right)\varphi\left(h_1,h_2\right)
    \end{equation*}

    \normalsize

    Setting $h_1=h_2=0$, the second term vanishes, so what remains is:

    \begin{equation*}
        \frac{\partial^2\varphi}{\partial h_1\partial h_2}\bigg|_{h_1=h_2=0}=Dt_1\varphi\left(h_1,h_2\right)\big|_{h_1=h_2=0}=Dt_1
    \end{equation*}

    Let's remember that the calculations were done assuming that $t_1&lt;t_2$. In the opposite case, it is easy to verify that the function $A(t)$ is the same with the subscripts inverted, and the same property is inherited by $R(T)$ and therefore by $\frac{\partial^2\varphi}{\partial h_1\partial h_2}$, which at $h_1=h_2=0$ will therefore be equal to $Dt_2$. It follows that, in general:

    \begin{equation*}
        \frac{\partial^2\varphi}{\partial h_1\partial h_2}\bigg|_{h_1=h_2=0}=D\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)
    \end{equation*}

    We obtain the same result seen in (eq:processi-stocastici-wiener-funzione-correlazione) for the two-point correlation function of a Brownian motion (in the general case with $D\neq1$). This is not a coincidence, in fact:

    \begin{align*}
        \int_0^Tx(t)a(t)dt&=h_1\int_0^Tx(t)\delta\left(t_1-t\right)dt+h_2\int_0^Tx(t)\delta\left(t_2-t\right)dt=\\
        &=h_1x\left(t_1\right)+h_2x\left(t_2\right)
    \end{align*}

    from which it follows that

    \begin{align*}
        \frac{\partial^2\varphi}{\partial h_1\partial h_2}\bigg|_{h_1=h_2=0}&=\frac{\partial^2}{\partial h_1\partial h_2}\left\langle e^{h_1x\left(t_1\right)+h_2x\left(t_2\right)}\right\rangle_{BM}\big|_{h_1=h_2=0}=\\
        &=\left\langle\frac{\partial^2}{\partial h_1\partial h_2}e^{h_1x\left(t_1\right)+h_2x\left(t_2\right)}\right\rangle_{BM}\bigg|_{h_1=h_2=0}=\\
        &=\left\langle \left[x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right]e^{h_1x\left(t_1\right)+h_2x\left(t_2\right)}\right\rangle_{BM}\big|_{h_1=h_2=0}=\\
        &=\left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle
    \end{align*}
\end{enumerate}

9.3 Analogy with quantum mechanics
Path integrals were first introduced by the physicist Richard Feynman in the context of quantum mechanics in Lagrangian formulation. In fact, quantum phenomena can be considered stochastic processes, as they are intrinsically probabilistic in their evolution before the collapse of the wave function.
The same Chapman-Kolmogorov law is easily obtained from the use of Dirac’s bra-ket notation:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \bra{x_2,t_2}\ket{x_0,t_0}=\bra{x_2,t_2}\mathds{1}\ket{x_0,t_0}=\int\bra{x_2,t_2}\ket{x_1,t_1}\bra{x_1,t_1}\ket{x_0,t_0}dx_1
\end{equation*}\]
Returning to path integration, according to Feynman’s notation which makes use of the measure \(\mathcal{D}x\), we will write the propagator from \(\left(0,0\right)\) to \(\left(x,T\right)\) as
\[\begin{equation}
    w\left(x,T|0,0\right)=\int_0^x\mathcal{D}x(\tau)e^{-\frac{1}{2D}\int_0^T\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2dt}
\end{equation}\]
In the Lagrangian formulation, this quantity is reported as
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^x\mathcal{D}x(\tau)e^{-S[x(s)]}
\end{equation*}\]
where \(S\) is the action of the system, which by definition is equal to the integral of the Lagrangian over time. From this similarity we understand that the Lagrangian \(\mathcal{L}\) of our diffusion system is
\[\begin{equation*}
    \mathcal{L}(x)=\frac{1}{2D}\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2
\end{equation*}\]
For a complete similarity between the two worlds, we can try to reduce to the expression of the Lagrangian of a free particle. In the first place, we know that we need a mass in the numerator, so certainly \(D\propto\frac{1}{m}\), and for dimensional reasons the proportionality constant must be equal to \(\hbar^2\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    D=\frac{\hbar^2}{m} \ \Longrightarrow \ \mathcal{L}(x)=\frac{m}{2\hbar^2}\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2
\end{equation*}\]
Substituting in (eq:integrali-sui-cammini-mq-propagatore):
\[\begin{equation*}
    w\left(x,T|0,0\right)=\int_0^x\mathcal{D}x(\tau)e^{-\frac{m}{2\hbar^2}\int_0^T\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2dt}
\end{equation*}\]
For this to make sense in quantum mechanics, it is necessary to introduce the factor \(\frac{i}{\hbar}\) in the exponent, so we introduce this quantity by passing from \(t\) to \(-i\hbar t\), obtaining:
\[\begin{equation*}
    w\left(x,T|0,0\right)=\int_0^x\mathcal{D}x(\tau)e^{\frac{im}{2\hbar}\int_0^{\tilde{T}}\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^2dt}
\end{equation*}\]
being \(\tilde{T}=-i\hbar T\) according to the substitution made.
Since we know the form of the propagator in Brownian motion, by substituting the values of \(D\) and \(t\) we will obtain:
\[\begin{equation*}
    w(x,T|0,0)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi DT}}e^{-\frac{x^2}{2DT}} \ \longrightarrow \ \sqrt{\frac{m(-i\hbar)}{2\pi\hbar^2\tilde{T}}}e^{-\frac{m(-i\hbar)}{2\hbar^2\tilde{T}}x^2}=\sqrt{\frac{m}{2\pi i\hbar\tilde{T}}}e^{\frac{im}{2\hbar\tilde{T}}x^2}
\end{equation*}\]
which corresponds to the Green’s function, which expresses the propagator of the Schrödinger equation relative to the problem of the free particle in quantum mechanics.

10.1 Gaussian white noise
Let’s take up (eq:processi-stocastici-prima-equazione-differenziale-stocastica) again and try to write it in the form of a differential equation by dividing both sides by \(dt\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{dx}{dt}=\mu+\sigma\frac{dB}{dt}
\end{equation}\]
having replaced \(\sqrt{D}\) with a generic function of the diffusion coefficient, indicated with \(\sigma\).
The question at this point is: what does the derivative of \(B(t)\) correspond to? As we have already stated in section (sec:integrale-sui-cammini-di-wiener), in reference to the formal expression written in equation (eq:integrale-sui-cammini-espressione-formale-differenziale-dP), a stochastic realization of Brownian motion is not differentiable at any point. Nevertheless, we can try to give a form to the derivative of \(B(t)\) starting from its statistical properties.
Let’s start from the finite expression, defining the following quantity:
\[\begin{equation}
    \xi_{\Delta,i}=\frac{\Delta B_i}{\Delta t}
\end{equation}\]
where \(\Delta B_i=B\left(t_i+\Delta t\right)-B\left(t_i\right)\).
Let’s remember that this difference follows a Gaussian distribution centered at zero, so the average value of the quantity just defined is:
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle\xi_{\Delta,i}\right\rangle=\left\langle\frac{\Delta B_i}{\Delta t}\right\rangle=\frac{\left\langle\Delta B_i\right\rangle}{\Delta t}=0
\end{equation}\]
Being identically equal to zero, this result will also hold in the limit for \(\Delta t\to0\).
Another fundamental aspect, to understand how successive instants of time are correlated, is the covariance. To calculate it, it is useful to consider a generic function \(f(t)\), which when discretized will assume the value \(f\left(t_i\right)\), and to make the following sum explicit:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_if\left(t_i\right)\left\langle\xi_{\Delta,i},\xi_{\Delta,j}\right\rangle\Delta t=\sum_if\left(t_i\right)\left\langle\frac{\Delta B_i}{\Delta t},\frac{\Delta B_j}{\Delta t}\right\rangle\Delta t=\sum_if\left(t_i\right)\frac{\left\langle \Delta B_i,\Delta B_j\right\rangle}{(\Delta t)^{\cancel{2}}}\cancel{\Delta t}
\end{equation*}\]
Since the increments are independent of each other, the covariance \(\left\langle \Delta B_i,\Delta B_j\right\rangle\), in general, is zero; the only exception is when \(i=j\), since in that case we are dealing with the variance which we know to be equal to \(t_i+\Delta t-t_i=\Delta t\).
We will have:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_if\left(t_i\right)\left\langle\xi_{\Delta,i},\xi_{\Delta,j}\right\rangle\Delta t=\sum_if\left(t_i\right)\frac{\delta_{ij}\cancel{\Delta t}}{\cancel{\Delta t}}=f\left(t_j\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Passing to the limit for \(\Delta t\to0\), therefore:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int f(t)\langle\xi(t)\xi(t')\rangle dt=f(t')
\end{equation*}\]
From which it follows that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \langle\xi(t)\xi(t')\rangle=\delta(t-t')
\end{equation*}\]
Although we cannot give an analytical form to \(\xi(t)\) - except as a limit of \(\xi_{\Delta,i}\) for \(\Delta t\to0\), which however has no real solution from a rigorous point of view - we were still able to find two characteristic aspects:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        \langle\xi(t)\rangle=0\\
        \langle\xi(t)\xi(t')\rangle=\delta(t-t')
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
A function that follows these two properties is called Gaussian white noise, or also \(\boldsymbol{\delta}\)-correlated noise. Having defined this function, we can rewrite the starting differential equation in the following form:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\frac{dx}{dt}=\mu+\sigma\xi(t)}
\end{equation}\]

10.3 Multiplicative noise
We can further generalize (eq:sde-equazione-di-langevin) by making \(\sigma\) no longer constant, but dependent on the coordinates \(x\) and \(t\):
\[\begin{equation}
    dx=\mu(x,t)dt+\sigma(x,t)dB
\end{equation}\]
A general solution of this equation has the following formula:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{x(t)=x_0+\int_0^t\mu(x(t'),t')dt'+\int_0^t\sigma(x(t'),t')dB(t')}
\end{equation}\]
If the trajectory \(B(t)\) is given, an explicit function of \(B(t)\) that satisfies the relation (eq:sde-soluzione-generale), together with the initial condition \(x(0)=x_0\), is called a strong solution:
\[\begin{equation*}
    x(t)\equiv\Phi\left(B(t') \ \text{with} \ t'&lt;t,x_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
From now on, our attention shifts to the last term on the right-hand side of (eq:sde-soluzione-generale): being the contribution of a stochastic nature, we will have to understand how to interpret this integral.
First of all, let’s understand why it is not a normal integral as we understand it in analysis; let’s consider for simplicity \(\mu(x,t)=0\) and \(\sigma(x,t)=B(t)\):
\[\begin{equation}
    x(t)=x_0+\int_0^tB(t')dB(t')
\end{equation}\]
What we expect is that \(\langle x(t)\rangle=x_0\), since Brownian motion introduces noise distributed symmetrically with respect to \(0\), and therefore that the average value of the integral written above is zero. By applying standard analysis, however, this average value results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle \int_0^tB(t')dB(t')\right\rangle=\left\langle\frac{B(t')^2}{2}\bigg|_0^t\right\rangle=\frac{\left\langle B(t)^2\right\rangle}{2}=\frac{t}{2}\neq0
\end{equation*}\]
The reason for this inconsistency will become clearer thanks to a theorem that we will see below; to prove this theorem, however, we first need to verify a lemma.

10.3.1 Lemma on finite quadratic variation
For this lemma we need to introduce the mean square limit, defined as follows:
\[\begin{equation}
    \mslim_{n\to\infty}x_n=x \ \iff \ \lim_{n\to\infty}\left\langle\left(x_n-x\right)^2\right\rangle=0
\end{equation}\]
We now have all the tools to state the lemma.

Given $t&gt;0$, let's partition the interval $[0,t]$ into $n$ sub-intervals:

\begin{equation*}
    P_n=\left\{t_0=0,t_1,t_2,\dots,t_{n-1},t_n=t\right\}
\end{equation*}

Let's use the following notation:

\begin{equation*}
    \abs{P_n}=\max_i\abs{t_i-t_{i-1}}
\end{equation*}

Let's assume that, in the limit for $n\to\infty$, it results $\abs{P_n}\to0$. If this is valid, setting

\begin{equation*}
    Q_n=\sum_{i=1}^n\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2
\end{equation*}

it results:

\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\mslim_{n\to\infty}Q_n=t}
\end{equation}

We will limit ourselves to proving this result, but it should be borne in mind that it is possible to prove something even stronger, namely the almost certain convergence of \(Q_n\) itself:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \lim_{n\to\infty}Q_n=t
\end{equation*}\]
This implies that, although \(Q_n\) is random for finite \(n\), it is no longer so in the limit for \(n\to\infty\).
Let’s proceed below with the proof.

As we have partitioned the set, the time $t$ can be rewritten as

\begin{equation*}
    t=\sum_{i=1}^nt_i-t_{i-1}
\end{equation*}

since the summation simplifies all the terms $t_i$ except for $t_n-t_0=t-0$.

It follows that

\begin{equation*}
    Q_n-t=\sum_{i=1}^n\left\{\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\right\}
\end{equation*}

What we must prove is that

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle\left(Q_n-t\right)^2\right\rangle\xrightarrow{n\to\infty}0
\end{equation*}

All that remains to be done, therefore, is to make this quantity explicit. Being

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle\left(Q_n-t\right)^2\right\rangle=\left\langle\left(Q_n-t\right)\left(Q_n-t\right)\right\rangle
\end{equation*}

then the average value can be written as:

\footnotesize

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle\sum_{i=1}^n\left\{\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\right\}\sum_{j=1}^n\left\{\left[B\left(t_j\right)-B\left(t_{j-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_j-t_{j-1}\right)\right\}\right\rangle
\end{equation*}

\normalsize

By the linearity of the average value with respect to the sum:

\footnotesize

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{j=1}^n\left\langle\left\{\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\right\}\left\{\left[B\left(t_j\right)-B\left(t_{j-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_j-t_{j-1}\right)\right\}\right\rangle
\end{equation*}

\normalsize

In the case where $i\neq j$, since the increments of Brownian motion are independent by definition, the average value of the product will be equal to the product of the average values; the generic term of the summations will be equal to

\footnotesize

\begin{align*}
    &\left\langle\left\{\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\right\}\left\{\left[B\left(t_j\right)-B\left(t_{j-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_j-t_{j-1}\right)\right\}\right\rangle=\\
    &=\left\langle\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\right\rangle\left\langle\left[B\left(t_j\right)-B\left(t_{j-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_j-t_{j-1}\right)\right\rangle=\\
    &=\left\{\left\langle\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2\right\rangle-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\right\}\left\{\left\langle\left[B\left(t_j\right)-B\left(t_{j-1}\right)\right]^2\right\rangle-\left(t_j-t_{j-1}\right)\right\}=\\
    &=\left\{\cancel{\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)}\cancel{-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)}\right\}\left\{\cancel{\left(t_j-t_{j-1}\right)}\cancel{-\left(t_j-t_{j-1}\right)}\right\}=0
\end{align*}

\normalsize

Of the two summations, only the contributions in which $i=j$ remain:

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\left\langle\left\{\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2-\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\right\}^2\right\rangle
\end{equation*}

Let's expand the square:

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\left\langle\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^4-2\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)+\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2\right\rangle
\end{equation*}

Dividing the average value among the three terms:

\small

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\left\{\left\langle\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^4\right\rangle-2\left\langle\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2\right\rangle\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)+\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2\right\}
\end{equation*}

\normalsize

The first term is the fourth-order moment relative to a Gaussian centered at zero and with variance $t_i-t_{i-1}$. The formula for finding the generic (even) order moment is (eq:integrali-gaussiani-formula-momento-n), from which we know that the result is equal to $3\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2$.

The final result will be:

\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^n\left\{3\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2-2\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2+\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2\right\}=2\sum_{i=1}^n\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2
\end{equation*}

Let's remember that this is none other than a rewriting of $\left\langle\left(Q_n-t\right)^2\right\rangle$. To obtain the thesis, let's try to majorize with respect to $\abs{P_n}$:

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle\left(Q_n-t\right)^2\right\rangle=2\sum_{i=1}^n\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2\leqslant2\max_i\abs{t_i-t_{i-1}}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)=2\abs{P_n}t
\end{equation*}

Since in the limit for $n\to\infty$ we have $\abs{P_n}\to0$, the thesis follows.



10.3.2 Theorem on the stochastic Riemann sum
Through the lemma just proved, we can prove the following theorem, which will allow us to understand the reason why the passage from discrete quantities to infinitesimal quantities in the limit is not as immediate as it is according to standard mathematical analysis.

Given $t&gt;0$, let's partition the interval $[0,t]$ into $n$ sub-intervals:

\begin{equation*}
    P_n\left\{t_0=0,t_1,t_2,\dots,t_{n-1},t_n=t\right\}
\end{equation*}

Let's use the following notation:

\begin{equation*}
    \abs{P_n}=\max_i\abs{t_i-t_{i-1}}
\end{equation*}

Let's assume that, in the limit for $n\to\infty$, it results $\abs{P_n}\to0$. If this is valid, given $\lambda\in[0,1]\subseteq\mathbb{R}$ and setting

\begin{equation*}
    X_n=\sum_{i=1}^nB\left(\lambda t_i+(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\right)\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]
\end{equation*}

it results:

\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\mslim_{n\to\infty}X_n=\frac{B(t)^2}{2}+(\lambda-\frac{1}{2})t}
\end{equation}

Before proving the theorem, it is useful to interpret the thesis right away. We note that the quantity \(\lambda t_i+(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\), being \(\lambda\in[0,1]\), is intermediate between \(t_i\) and \(t_{i-1}\): in fact, for \(\lambda=0\) it is equal to \(t_{i-1}\), while for \(\lambda=1\) it is equal to \(t_i\), so for all intermediate values it will be between the two.
In the \(X_n\) defined in the theorem, we therefore recognize the approximate form of the integral, which should return the exact integral in the limit according to the Riemann sum illustrated in figure (fig:somma-di-riemann). From what we know from mathematical analysis, this sum should not depend on the intermediate point chosen in the interval of the domain, but equation (eq:sde-teorema-somma-di-riemann-risultato) shows us a result that is dependent on \(\lambda\), and therefore on the choice of the intermediate point. This peculiar property is what mainly characterizes stochastic integrals and what substantially differentiates them from classical integrals.
Let’s proceed below with the proof of the theorem.

To simplify the writing, let's adopt the following notations:

\begin{align*}
    &B_i=B\left(t_i\right)\\
    &B_i^\lambda=B\left(\lambda t_i+(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\right)
\end{align*}

$X_n$ will therefore be equal to

\begin{equation*}
    X_n=\sum_{i=1}^nB_i^\lambda\left(B_i-B_{i-1}\right)
\end{equation*}

Working in the context of Brownian motion, it is always convenient to reduce to squares and squares of differences. For this reason, let's add and subtract $B_{i-1}$ to the first term and $B_i^\lambda$ to the second term:

\begin{equation*}
    B_i^\lambda\left(B_i-B_{i-1}\right)=\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}+B_{i-1}\right)\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda+B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)
\end{equation*}

Let's multiply the two parentheses as follows:

\footnotesize

\begin{align*}
    &\left(\orange{B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}}+\green{B_{i-1}}\right)\left(\red{B_i-B_i^\lambda}+\orange{B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}}\right)=\\
    &=\left(\orange{B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}}\right)\left(\red{B_i-B_i^\lambda}\right)+\left(\orange{B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}}\right)^2+\green{B_{i-1}}\left(\red{B_i-B_i^\lambda}\right)+\green{B_{i-1}}\left(\orange{B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}}\right)
\end{align*}

\normalsize

Let's focus on the last two terms:

\begin{equation*}
    B_{i-1}\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda\right)+B_{i-1}\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)=B_{i-1}B_i\cancel{-B_{i-1}B_i^\lambda}\cancel{+B_{i-1}B_i^\lambda}-B_{i-1}^2
\end{equation*}

Returning to the starting expression, we find:

\begin{equation*}
    B_i^\lambda\left(B_i-B_{i-1}\right)=\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda\right)+\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)^2+B_{i-1}B_i-B_{i-1}^2
\end{equation*}

We note that they are actually all squares or products of differences except for $B_{i-1}B_i$. To also write the latter in this form, let's try to reduce it to the double product of the square of a binomial:

\begin{align*}
    B_{i-1}B_i&=\frac{1}{2}\cdot2B_{i-1}B_i=-\frac{1}{2}\cdot(-2B_{i-1}B_i)=\\
    &=-\frac{1}{2}\left(B_i^2-2B_iB_{i-1}+B_{i-1}^2\right)+\frac{1}{2}B_i^2+\frac{1}{2}B_{i-1}^2=\\
    &=-\frac{1}{2}\left(B_i-B_{i-1}\right)^2+\frac{1}{2}B_i^2+\frac{1}{2}B_{i-1}^2
\end{align*}

We obtain the following expression for $B_i^\lambda\left(B_i-B_{i-1}\right)$:

\begin{equation*}
    \red{\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda\right)}+\orange{\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)^2}\green{-\frac{1}{2}\left(B_i-B_{i-1}\right)^2}+\blue{\frac{1}{2}\left(B_i^2-B_{i-1}^2\right)}
\end{equation*}

Let's now calculate the individual contributions of the four highlighted terms.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item $\red{\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda\right)}$

    Considering the average value of the square, we can write:

    \small

    \begin{equation*}
        \left\langle\left[\sum_{i=1}^n\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda\right)\right]^2\right\rangle=\sum_{i=1}^n\left\langle\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)^2\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda\right)^2\right\rangle
    \end{equation*}

    \normalsize

    In this step we have ignored the double products resulting from the expansion of the square, as the increments are independent and therefore, by distributing the average value over the individual differences, the expected values would have been zero, since these differences are distributed as Gaussians centered at the origin.

    Always for the same reason, that is, the independence of the increments in Brownian motion, we can distribute the average value in the remaining term:

    \begin{equation*}
        \sum_{i=1}^n\left\langle\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)^2\right\rangle\left\langle\left(B_i-B_i^\lambda\right)^2\right\rangle
    \end{equation*}

    Remembering that $B_i^\lambda=B\left(\lambda t_i+(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\right)$ it then follows that

    \begin{align*}
        &\sum_{i=1}^n\left[\lambda t_i+(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}-t_{i-1}\right]\left[t_i-\lambda t_i-(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\right]=\\
        &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left[\lambda t_i\cancel{+t_{i-1}}-\lambda t_{i-1}\cancel{-t_{i-1}}\right]\left[(1-\lambda)t_i-(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\right]=\\
        &=\sum_{i=1}^n\lambda\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)\cdot(1-\lambda)\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)=\lambda(1-\lambda)\sum_{i=1}^n\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2
    \end{align*}

    Let's majorize exactly as we did in the proof of the lemma on finite quadratic variation:

    \footnotesize

    \begin{equation*}
        \lambda(1-\lambda)\sum_{i=1}^n\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)^2\leqslant\lambda(1-\lambda)\max_i\abs{t_i-t_{i-1}}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(t_i-t_{i-1}\right)=\lambda(1-\lambda)\abs{P_n}t
    \end{equation*}

    \normalsize

    In the limit for $n\to\infty$ we have that $\abs{P_n}\to0$, so this contribution is zero.

    \item $\orange{\left(B_i^\lambda-B_{i-1}\right)^2}$

    Let's make both $B_i^\lambda$ and $B_{i-1}$ explicit:

    \begin{equation*}
        \sum_{i=1}^n\left[B\left(\lambda t_i+(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2
    \end{equation*}

    By the stationarity of the increments $B(t)-B(t')=B(t+\epsilon)-B(t'+\epsilon)$, so we can add the same quantity inside both functions while keeping the difference the same.

    That said, let's add $-(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}$:

    \begin{align*}
        &\sum_{i=1}^n\left[B\left(\lambda t_i\cancel{+(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}}\cancel{-(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}}\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}-(1-\lambda)t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2=\\
        &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left[B\left(\lambda t_i\right)-B\left(\cancel{t_{i-1}}\cancel{-t_{i-1}}+\lambda t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2=\sum_{i=1}^n\left[B\left(\lambda t_i\right)-B\left(\lambda t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2
    \end{align*}

    Let's set $\bar{t}_i=\lambda t_i$ obtaining the following limit from the lemma proved before:

    \begin{equation*}
        \mslim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{i=1}^n\left[B\left(\bar{t}_i\right)-B\left(\bar{t}_{i-1}\right)\right]^2=\bar{t}=\lambda t
    \end{equation*}

    \item $\green{-\frac{1}{2}\left(B_i-B_{i-1}\right)^2}$

    The result of the limit is immediate from the lemma on finite quadratic variation:

    \begin{equation*}
        -\frac{1}{2}\mslim_{n\to\infty}\left[B_i-B_{i-1}\right]^2=-\frac{1}{2}\mslim_{n\to\infty}\left[B\left(t_i\right)-B\left(t_{i-1}\right)\right]^2=-\frac{t}{2}
    \end{equation*}

    \item $\blue{\frac{1}{2}\left(B_i^2-B_{i-1}^2\right)}$

    In the summation all the terms will be simplified except for the first and the last:

    \begin{align*}
        \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(B_i^2-B_{i-1}^2\right)&=\frac{1}{2}\left(B_n^2-B_0^2\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left[B\left(t_n\right)^2-B\left(t_0\right)^2\right]=\\
        &=\frac{1}{2}\left[B(t)^2-\cancel{B(0)}^2\right]
    \end{align*}

    Being a finite quantity, $\frac{B(t)^2}{2}$ is the final result also in the limit for $n\to\infty$.
\end{enumerate}

Putting the four pieces together, it results:

\begin{equation*}
    \mslim_{n\to\infty}X_n=0+\lambda t-\frac{t}{2}+\frac{B(t)^2}{2}=\frac{B(t)^2}{2}+(\lambda-\frac{1}{2})t
\end{equation*}

just as predicted by the thesis.

10.5 Itô calculus
What we will derive below are two important laws, which define the main properties of infinitesimal analysis: the differentiation rule and the chain rule, the latter also called the Itô formula in the context in which we find ourselves.
In both cases we will refer to a fundamental relation that we have already expressed in the past, both in equation (eq:processi-stocastici-wiener-andamento-modulo-delta-B) and in equation (eq:sde-ito-relazione-collante), according to which
\[\begin{equation}
    \Delta B^2=\Delta t
\end{equation}\]
This relation, in a non-rigorous way, we can also write it in infinitesimal form through the differential:
\[\begin{equation}
    dB^2=dt
\end{equation}\]

10.5.1 Differentiation rule
Let’s consider a function \(u(B(t),t)\). The differential \(du\) will therefore be a function of \(dt\) and of \(dB\). Furthermore, since \(dB^2=dt\), the quadratic term \(dB^2\) of the expansion is not negligible, but we must include it in the expansion:
\[\begin{equation*}
    du=\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial B}dB+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial B^2}dB^2=\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial B}dB+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial B^2}dt
\end{equation*}\]
Ultimately, the differential \(du\) is equal to
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{du=\left(\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial B^2}\right)dt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial B}dB}
\end{equation}\]
Let’s take for example \(u=B^2\); not depending explicitly on \(t\), then \(\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}=0\), and what remains is:
\[\begin{equation*}
    du\equiv dB^2=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2\left(B^2\right)}{\partial B^2}dt+\frac{\partial\left(B^2\right)}{\partial B}dB=\frac{1}{\cancel{2}}\cdot\cancel{2}dt+2BdB
\end{equation*}\]
Integrating this relation we obtain:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^tdB(t')^2=\int_0^tdt'+2\int_0^tB(t')dB(t') \ \Longrightarrow \ B(t)^2=t+2\int_0^tB(t')dB(t')
\end{equation*}\]
It follows that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^tB(t')dB(t')=\frac{B(t)^2}{2}-\frac{t}{2}
\end{equation*}\]
which is precisely the Itô integral reported in equation (eq:sde-integrale-di-ito).

Show that the Itô differential for \(B^n\) is given by


Solution. \[\begin{equation*}
        dB^n=\frac{n(n-1)}{2}B^{n-2}dt+nB^{n-1}dB
    \end{equation*}\]
*Also show that*

\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^tB(t')^ndB(t')=\frac{B(t)^{n+1}}{n+1}-\frac{n}{2}\int_0^tB(t')^{n-1}dt'
\end{equation*}

Let's use the differentiation rule:

\begin{equation*}
    dB^n=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2\left(B^n\right)}{\partial B^2}dt+\frac{\partial\left(B^n\right)}{\partial B}dB=\frac{n(n-1)}{2}B^{n-2}dt+nB^{n-1}dB
\end{equation*}

To prove the second relation, let's integrate both members:

\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^tdB(t')^n=\frac{n(n-1)}{2}\int_0^tB(t')^{n-2}dt'+n\int_0^tB(t')^{n-1}dB(t')
\end{equation*}

The first member has as a result $B(t)^n$, so by isolating the last integral on the right we will write:

\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^tB(t')^{n-1}dB(t')=\frac{B(t)^n}{n}-\frac{n-1}{2}\int_0^tB(t')^{n-2}dt'
\end{equation*}

By passing from $n$ to $n+1$ we obtain the required relation.



10.5.2 Chain rule
Let’s consider a function \(x(t)\) that satisfies the following stochastic differential equation:
\[\begin{equation*}
    dx=\mu(x,t)dt+\sigma(x,t)dB
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s now consider a function \(u(x(t),t)\). Due to the dependence of \(dx\) on \(dB\), we will have to expand the differential of \(u\) up to the second order of \(x\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    du=\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}dx+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}dx^2=\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}(\mu dt+\sigma dB)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}(\mu dt+\sigma dB)^2
\end{equation*}\]
Obviously, to do this, we must explicitly assume that \(u\in C(t)^1\) and that \(u\in C(x)^2\).
In the expansion of the square, we only obtain terms of order higher than \(dt\), with the exception of \(dB^2\) which, as we know, corresponds to \(dt\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    du=\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}(\mu dt+\sigma dB)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}\sigma^2dt
\end{equation*}\]
By collecting with respect to \(dt\) and \(dB\) we obtain the chain rule, also called the Itô formula:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{du=\left(\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\mu+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}\sigma^2\right)dt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\sigma dB}
\end{equation}\]

Let \(x(t)\) and \(y(t)\) be two processes that satisfy the following two stochastic differential equations:
\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        dx=\mu_xdt+\sigma_xdB\\
        dy=\mu_ydt+\sigma_ydB
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}

*Using the Itô rules, show that, if* $u(x,y)\in C(x,y)^2$   extit{, then}

\footnotesize

\begin{equation*}
    du=\left(\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\mu_x+\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\mu_y+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}\sigma_x^2+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial y^2}\sigma_y^2+\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x\partial y}\sigma_x\sigma_y\right)dt+\left(\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\sigma_x+\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\sigma_y\right)dB
\end{equation*}

\normalsize

*Furthermore, starting from the differential of* $u(x,y)=xy$    extit{, deduce the correlation between the processes} $x(t)$ *and* $y(t)$   extit{.}

I premise that the formula written in the assignment by the professor, to be correct, must assume that $u(x,y)$ does not explicitly depend on time, since, otherwise, the derivative $\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}$ must also be included, which is instead absent.

That said, let's retrace what we saw in the derivation of the chain rule:

\begin{equation*}
    du=\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}dx+\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}dy+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}dx^2+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial y^2}dy^2+\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x\partial y}dxdy
\end{equation*}


Solution. Let’s calculate each single contribution, remembering to neglect any term of order higher than \(dt\) and that \(dB^2=dt\):
\begin{align*}
    &\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}dx=\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\mu_xdt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\sigma_xdB\\
    &\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}dy=\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\mu_ydt+\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\sigma_ydB\\
    &\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}dx^2=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}\left(\mu_xdt+\sigma_xdB\right)^2=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x^2}\sigma_x^2dt\\
    &\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial y^2}dy^2=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial y^2}\left(\mu_ydt+\sigma_ydB\right)^2=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial y^2}\sigma_y^2dt\\
    &\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x\partial y}dxdy=\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x\partial y}\left(\mu_xdt+\sigma_xdB\right)\left(\mu_ydt+\sigma_ydB\right)=\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial x\partial y}\sigma_x\sigma_ydt
\end{align*}

Summing all the terms we obtain the differential written in the assignment.

Let's now move on to the second part, first calculating $d(xy)$ starting from the rule we have just derived:

\begin{equation*}
    d(xy)=\left(y\mu_x+x\mu_y+\sigma_x\sigma_y\right)dt+\left(y\sigma_x+x\sigma_y\right)dB
\end{equation*}

Dividing both members by $dt$, remembering that $\frac{dB}{dt}=\xi(t)$, it results:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d(xy)}{dt}=y\mu_x+x\mu_y+\sigma_x\sigma_y+\left(y\sigma_x+x\sigma_y\right)\xi(t)
\end{equation*}

Let's move on to the average value on the left and on the right:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d\langle xy\rangle}{dt}=\mu_y\langle x\rangle+\mu_x\langle y\rangle+\sigma_y\langle x\xi(t)\rangle+\sigma_x\langle y\xi(t)\rangle+\sigma_x\sigma_y
\end{equation*}

Following the Itô convention, both $x(t)$ and $y(t)$ are independent of the increment $dB$, and therefore they are also independent of $\xi(t)$. It follows that:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d\langle xy\rangle}{dt}=\mu_y\langle x\rangle+\mu_x\langle y\rangle+\sigma_y\langle x\rangle\cancel{\langle\xi(t)\rangle}+\sigma_x\langle y\rangle\cancel{\langle\xi(t)\rangle}+\sigma_x\sigma_y
\end{equation*}

To derive $\langle x\rangle$ and $\langle y\rangle$ let's start from the SDEs:

\small

\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        \frac{dx}{dt}=\mu_x+\sigma_x\xi(t)\\
        \frac{dy}{dt}=\mu_y+\sigma_y\xi(t)
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        \frac{d\langle x\rangle}{dt}=\mu_x+\sigma_x\cancel{\langle\xi(t)\rangle}\\
        \frac{d\langle y\rangle}{dt}=\mu_y+\sigma_y\cancel{\langle\xi(t)\rangle}
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        \langle x\rangle=x_0+\mu_xt\\
        \langle y\rangle=y_0+\mu_yt
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}

\normalsize

Substituting:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d\langle xy\rangle}{dt}=\mu_yx_0+\mu_x\mu_yt+\mu_xy_0+\mu_x\mu_yt+\sigma_x\sigma_y=\mu_yx_0+\mu_xy_0+\sigma_x\sigma_y+2\mu_x\mu_yt
\end{equation*}

By integrating we obtain the correlation function:

\begin{equation*}
    \langle xy\rangle=\langle xy\rangle_{t=0}+(\mu_yx_0+\mu_xy_0+\sigma_x\sigma_y)t+\mu_x\mu_yt^2
\end{equation*}

11.1 Sample trajectory
Formally, the process is defined by the following differential equation:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        dx=-\mu xdt+\sigma dB\\        x(0)=x_0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
To find a general solution, it is useful to define the following function:
\[\begin{equation}
    y(t)=e^{\mu t}x(t)
\end{equation}\]
where \(x(t)\) is the solution of the equation. The reason why this is convenient is soon told by applying the chain rule (equation (eq:sde-chain-rule-ito)), having set \(\mu(x,t)=-\mu x\) and \(\sigma(x,t)=\sigma\) for consistency with the Langevin equation:
\[\begin{align*}
    dy&=\left(\frac{\partial y}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial y}{\partial x}\mu(x,t)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2y}{\partial x^2}\sigma^2\right)dt+\frac{\partial y}{\partial x}\sigma(x,t) dB=\\
    &=\left(\cancel{\mu e^{\mu t}x}\cancel{-\mu xe^{\mu t}}+0\right)dt+\sigma e^{\mu t}dB
\end{align*}\]
The remaining equation is easy to integrate:
\[\begin{equation*}
    dy=\sigma e^{\mu t}dB \ \Longrightarrow \ \ y(t)=y(0)+\sigma\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')
\end{equation*}\]
Returning to the expression in \(x(t)\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    e^{\mu t}x(t)=e^{\mu\cdot0}x(0)+\sigma\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')=x_0+\sigma\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')
\end{equation*}\]
We thus find the explicit form of the solution:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{x(t)=x_0e^{-\mu t}+\sigma e^{-\mu t}\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')}
\end{equation}\]

Calculate the solution of the following stochastic differential equation:
\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        dx=(\beta-\mu x)dt+\sigma dB\\           x(0)=x_0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}

We will have to follow the same procedure just carried out, with the only difference that this time $\mu(x,t)=-\mu x+\beta$. In this way the coefficient of $dt$ will not be canceled, since a surviving contribution equal to $\beta e^{\mu t}$ will remain:

\begin{equation*}
    dy=\beta e^{\mu t}dt+\sigma e^{\mu t}dB
\end{equation*}

Integrating both members:

\begin{equation*}
    y(t)=y(0)+\beta\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dt'+\sigma\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')
\end{equation*}


Solution. Let’s solve the first integral:
\begin{equation*}
    \int_0^te^{\mu t'}dt'=\frac{1}{\mu}e^{\mu t'}\bigg|_0^t=\frac{1}{\mu}\left(e^{\mu t}-1\right)
\end{equation*}

Let's now substitute $y(t)=e^{\mu t}x(t)$ and return to the complete solution:

\begin{equation*}
    e^{\mu t}x(t)=e^{\mu\cdot 0}x(0)+\frac{\beta}{\mu}\left(e^{\mu t}-1\right)+\sigma\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')
\end{equation*}

Let's therefore multiply both members by $e^{-\mu t}$ to obtain the final solution:

\begin{equation*}
    x(t)=x_0e^{-\mu t}+e^{-\mu t}\cdot\frac{\beta}{\mu}\left(e^{\mu t}-1\right)+\sigma e^{-\mu t}\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')
\end{equation*}

that is

\begin{equation*}
    x(t)=x_0e^{-\mu t}+\frac{\beta}{\mu}\left(1-e^{-\mu t}\right)+\sigma e^{-\mu t}\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')
\end{equation*}


11.1.1 Variance
We know that one of the main aspects of a realization of a stochastic process is its variance, in order to describe how fluctuations tend to change over time.
Let’s start from the calculation of the average value of \(x(t)^2\), which is obtained starting from the series expansion of the differential of \(x\) stopped at the second order, since - as already repeated several times - we have \(dB^2=dt\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    d\left(x^2\right)=\frac{d\left(x^2\right)}{dx}dx+\frac{1}{2}\frac{d^2\left(x^2\right)}{dx^2}dx^2=2xdx+\frac{1}{\cancel{2}}\cdot\cancel{2}dx^2
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s substitute the expression for \(dx\) given by the SDE:
\[\begin{equation*}
    d\left(x^2\right)=2x\left(-\mu xdt+\sigma dB\right)+\left(-\mu xdt+\sigma dB\right)^2
\end{equation*}\]
Of the square, only \(\sigma^2dB^2=\sigma^2dt\) remains:
\[\begin{equation*}
    d\left(x^2\right)=-2\mu x^2dt+2\sigma xdB+\sigma^2dt=\left(-2\mu x^2+\sigma^2\right)dt+2\sigma xdB
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s consider the expected value on both sides:
\[\begin{equation*}
    d\left\langle x^2\right\rangle=\left(-2\mu\left\langle x^2\right\rangle+\sigma^2\right)dt+2\sigma\langle xdB\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
According to the Itô convention \(\langle xdB\rangle=\langle x\rangle\cancel{\langle dB\rangle}=0\), from which the differential equation follows
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{d}{dt}\left\langle x^2\right\rangle=-2\mu\left\langle x^2\right\rangle+\sigma^2
\end{equation}\]
This is a non-homogeneous ordinary differential equation. To find a solution we must first solve the associated homogeneous equation:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d}{dt}\left\langle x^2\right\rangle=-2\mu\left\langle x^2\right\rangle \ \Longrightarrow \ \ \left\langle x(t)^2\right\rangle=ke^{-2\mu t}
\end{equation*}\]
To find the solution to the non-homogeneous equation ((eq:processo-u-o-varianza-equazione-non-omogenea)) we will have to add a constant contribution \(c\) to the solution found, such that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \cancel{\frac{d}{dt}c}=-2\mu c+\sigma^2 \ \iff \ 2\mu c=\sigma^2 \ \iff \ c=\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}
\end{equation*}\]
Summing the two contributions, we will find:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x(t)^2\right\rangle=ke^{-2\mu t}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}
\end{equation*}\]
It remains to find the constant \(k\) through the initial condition (\(\left\langle x(0)^2\right\rangle=x_0^2\)):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x(0)^2\right\rangle=k+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}=x_0^2 \ \Longrightarrow \ k=x_0^2-\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}
\end{equation*}\]
Ultimately:
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle x(t)^2\right\rangle=\left(x_0^2-\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\right)e^{-2\mu t}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}
\end{equation}\]
For the variance we must find \(\langle x(t)\rangle\), which is easily found starting from (eq:processo-u-o-soluzione-generale):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \langle x(t)\rangle=x_0e^{-\mu t}+\sigma e^{-\mu t}\left\langle\int_0^te^{\mu t'}dB(t')\right\rangle=x_0e^{-\mu t}+\sigma e^{-\mu t}\int_0^t\left\langle e^{\mu t'}\right\rangle\cancel{\langle dB(t')\rangle}
\end{equation*}\]
We can now calculate the variance associated with the process:
\[\begin{align*}
    Var[x(t)]&=\left\langle x(t)^2\right\rangle-\langle x(t)\rangle^2=\left(x_0^2-\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\right)e^{-2\mu t}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}-x_0^2e^{-\mu t}=\\
    &=\left(\cancel{x_0^2}-\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\cancel{-x_0^2}\right)e^{-\mu t}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}
\end{align*}\]
that is
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{Var[x(t)]=\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left(1-e^{-\mu t}\right)}
\end{equation}\]
This is a function that is zero for \(t=0\) and progressively increasing, stabilizing at the value \(\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\) for large \(t\).


11.1.2 Connected auto-correlation
Another important aspect is the correlation of the trajectory with itself at different instants of time, called auto-correlation:
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle
\end{equation}\]
If we remove the effects given by the global mean, we obtain what is called the connected auto-correlation:
\[\begin{equation}
    c\left(t_1,t_2\right)=\left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle-\left\langle x\left(t_1\right)\right\rangle\left\langle x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle
\end{equation}\]
Let’s calculate the first term by substituting (eq:processo-u-o-soluzione-generale):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\left\langle\left(x_0e^{-\mu t_1}+\sigma e^{-\mu t_1}\int_0^{t_1}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')\right)\left(x_0e^{-\mu t_2}+\sigma e^{-\mu t_2}\int_0^{t_2}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')\right)\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
From the products, the common factor \(e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\) emerges, which we can take out:
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\bigg\langle&x_0^2+\\
    &+x_0\sigma\int_0^{t_1}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')+\\
    &+x_0\sigma\int_0^{t_2}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')+\\
    &+\sigma^2\int_0^{t_1}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')\int_0^{t_2}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')\bigg\rangle
\end{align*}\]
Distributing the average value over the four terms, the two central ones will be zero, since \(\langle dB(t)\rangle\) is so. What remains is:
\[\begin{equation}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\left(x_0^2+\sigma^2\left\langle\int_0^{t_1}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')\int_0^{t_2}e^{\mu t'}dB(t')\right\rangle\right)
\end{equation}\]
To find the remaining expected value, it is useful to calculate more generally
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle\int_0^{t_1}f(t')dB(t')\int_0^{t_2}g(t')dB(t')\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s assume that \(t_2&gt;t_1\) and let’s discretize the interval \(\left[0,t_2\right]\) in the following way:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\{t_0=0,t_1,\dots,t_{m-1},t_m=\boldsymbol{t_1},t_{m+1},\dots,t_{n-1},t_n=\boldsymbol{t_2}\right\}
\end{equation*}\]
At this point, we can discretize the integrals as follows:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle\sum_{i=1}^mf_{i-1}\Delta B_i\sum_{j=1}^ng_{j-1}\Delta B_j\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s split the second summation into the intervals \([1,m]\) and \([m+1,n]\):
\[\begin{align*}
    &\left\langle\sum_{i=1}^mf_{i-1}\Delta B_i\left[\sum_{j=1}^mg_{j-1}\Delta B_j+\sum_{j=m+1}^ng_{j-1}\Delta B_j\right]\right\rangle=\\
    &=\left\langle\sum_{i=1}^mf_{i-1}\Delta B_i\sum_{j=1}^mg_{j-1}\Delta B_j\right\rangle+\left\langle\sum_{i=1}^mf_{i-1}\Delta B_i\sum_{j=m+1}^ng_{j-1}\Delta B_j\right\rangle
\end{align*}\]
The summations of the second term refer to different intervals, so they are uncorrelated quantities:
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle\sum_{i=1}^mf_{i-1}\Delta B_i\sum_{j=m+1}^ng_{j-1}\Delta B_j\right\rangle&=\left\langle\sum_{i=1}^mf_{i-1}\Delta B_i\right\rangle\left\langle\sum_{j=m+1}^ng_{j-1}\Delta B_j\right\rangle=\\
    &=\sum_{i=1}^m\left\langle f_{i-1}\right\rangle\cancel{\left\langle\Delta B_i\right\rangle}\sum_{j=m+1}^n\left\langle g_{j-1}\right\rangle\cancel{\left\langle\Delta B_j\right\rangle}=0
\end{align*}\]
What remains is therefore the first term, where the contributions of the summation can be divided into those in which \(i=j\) and those in which \(i\neq j\):
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle\sum_{i=1}^m\sum_{j=1}^mf_{i-1}g_{j-1}\Delta B_i\Delta B_j\right\rangle&=\left\langle\sum_{i=1}^mf_{i-1}g_{i-1}\Delta B_i^2\right\rangle+2\left\langle\sum_{i&gt;j}f_{i-1}g_{j-1}\Delta B_i\Delta B_j\right\rangle=\\
    &=\sum_{i=1}^m\left\langle f_{i-1}g_{i-1}\right\rangle\left\langle\Delta B_i^2\right\rangle+2\sum_{i&gt;j}\left\langle f_{i-1}g_{j-1}\right\rangle\cancel{\left\langle\Delta B_i\right\rangle}\cancel{\left\langle\Delta B_j\right\rangle}=\\
    &=\sum_{i=1}^m\left\langle f_{i-1}g_{i-1}\right\rangle\Delta t_i
\end{align*}\]
We thus find that, in the limit:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \sum_{i=1}^m\left\langle f_{i-1}g_{i-1}\right\rangle\Delta t_i \ \longrightarrow \ \int_0^{t_1}\langle f(t')g(t')\rangle dt'
\end{equation*}\]
If we had initially assumed \(t_1&gt;t_2\) we would have obtained the same result, but with the upper limit of integration equal to \(t_2\). It follows that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle\int_0^{t_1}f(t')dB(t')\int_0^{t_2}g(t')dB(t')\right\rangle=\int_0^{\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)}\langle f(t')g(t')\rangle dt'
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s go back to (eq:processo-u-o-auto-correlazione-calcolo-1) and substitute the result found:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\left(x_0^2+\sigma^2\int_0^{\min\left(t_1t_2\right)}e^{2\mu t'}dt'\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s solve the integral:
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle&=e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\left(x_0^2+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}e^{2\mu t'}\bigg|_0^{\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)}\right)=\\
    &=e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\left[x_0^2+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left(e^{2\mu\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)}-1\right)\right]
\end{align*}\]
Let’s substitute in (eq:processo-u-o-auto-correlazione-connessa-definizione), remembering that \(\langle x(t)\rangle=x_0e^{-\mu t}\):
\[\begin{align*}
    c\left(t_1,t_2\right)&=e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\left[x_0^2+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left(e^{2\mu\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)}-1\right)\right]-x_0e^{-\mu t_1}\cdot x_0e^{-\mu t_2}=\\
    &=\cancel{x_0^2e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left(e^{2\mu\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)}-1\right)e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\cancel{-x_0^2e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}}
\end{align*}\]
We find:
\[\begin{equation*}
    c\left(t_1,t_2\right)=\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left[e^{\mu\left(2\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)-t_1-t_2\right)}-e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\right]
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s evaluate the two cases:
\[\begin{align*}
    &\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)=t_1 \ \Longrightarrow \ 2t_1-t_1-t_2=t_1-t_2\\
    &\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)=t_2 \ \Longrightarrow \ 2t_2-t_1-t_2=-t_1+t_2
\end{align*}\]
This means that the exponent \(2\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)-t_1-t_2\) can be rewritten as \(-\abs{t_1-t_2}\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{c\left(t_1,t_2\right)=\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left[e^{-\mu\abs{t_1-t_2}}-e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\right]}
\end{equation}\]
We can find an even more general formula if we assume that at the initial instant the system is not entirely concentrated at \(x_0\) but is distributed according to a function \(p\left(x_0\right)\). In this case, we have that \(\langle x(t)\rangle=\left\langle x_0\right\rangle e^{-\mu t}\), so by substituting the results in (eq:processo-u-o-auto-correlazione-connessa-definizione) we will have:
\[\begin{align*}
    c\left(t_1,t_2\right)&=\left\langle x_0^2\right\rangle e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left[e^{-\mu\abs{t_1-t_2}}-e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\right]-\left\langle x_0\right\rangle^2e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}=\\
    &=\left(\left\langle x_0^2\right\rangle-\left\langle x_0\right\rangle^2\right)e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left[e^{-\mu\abs{t_1-t_2}}-e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\right]
\end{align*}\]
From which:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{c\left(t_1,t_2\right)=Var\left(x_0\right)e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left[e^{-\mu\abs{t_1-t_2}}-e^{-\mu\left(t_1+t_2\right)}\right]}
\end{equation}\]
We note that, in the limit for \(t_1,t_2\to\infty\) but keeping the difference \(t_1-t_2\) constant, we find the stationary connected auto-correlation, since it is independent of the individual values \(t_1\) and \(t_2\) but only of their difference in modulus:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{c_{stat}\left(t_1,t_2\right)=\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}e^{-\mu\abs{t_1-t_2}}}
\end{equation}\]

11.2 Propagator
Another fundamental characteristic of a stochastic process is its propagator, which tells us how the pdf evolves over time.
It can be found starting from the Fokker-Planck equation ((eq:fokker-planck-equazione)), which in our case is written as
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{\partial p}{\partial t}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(-\mu xp)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2}\left(\sigma^2p\right)=\mu\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xp)+\frac{\sigma^2}{2}\frac{\partial^2p}{\partial x^2}
\end{equation}\]
To find the solution, it is convenient to apply the Fourier transform to both members:
\[\begin{equation}
    \red{\mathcal{F}\left[\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}\right]}=\mu\orange{\mathcal{F}\left[\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xp)\right]}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2}\green{\mathcal{F}\left[\frac{\partial^2p}{\partial x^2}\right]}
\end{equation}\]
Let’s calculate the various transformations individually.
Let’s substitute the results obtained in (eq:processo-u-o-propagatore-equazione-differenziale-fourier):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{\partial\tilde{p}}{\partial t}=-\mu\omega\frac{\partial\tilde{p}}{\partial\omega}-\frac{\sigma^2}{2}\omega^2\tilde{p}(\omega,t)
\end{equation*}\]
This is a homogeneous first-order partial differential equation, in which \(\tilde{p}(\omega,t)\) is derived once with respect to \(t\) and another time with respect to \(t\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{\partial\tilde{p}}{\partial t}+\mu\omega\frac{\partial\tilde{p}}{\partial\omega}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2}\omega^2\tilde{p}(\omega,t)=0
\end{equation}\]
To solve this equation we will use a method known as the method of characteristics, which makes use of an auxiliary variable \(s\) such as to redefine the function in the following way:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{p}(s)\equiv\tilde{p}(\omega(s),t(s))
\end{equation*}\]
By deriving with respect to \(s\) we obtain:
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{d\tilde{p}}{ds}=\frac{\partial\tilde{p}}{\partial\omega}\frac{d\omega}{ds}+\frac{\partial\tilde{p}}{\partial t}\frac{dt}{ds}
\end{equation}\]
Referring to equation (eq:processo-u-o-propagatore-equazione-differenziale-post-fourier), we note that it can be rewritten in the following system of differential equations:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        \frac{d\omega}{ds}=\mu\omega\\       \frac{dt}{ds}=1\\       \frac{d\tilde{p}}{ds}+\frac{\sigma^2}{2}\omega^2\tilde{p}(s)=0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
We have thus passed from a partial differential equation to a system of ordinary differential equations. The method consists in identifying curves, also called characteristics, belonging to the space described by the coordinates \(\left(\omega,t,\tilde{p}\right)\) which are constrained on surfaces
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        u\left(\omega,t,\tilde{p}\right)=A\\       v\left(\omega,t,\tilde{p}\right)=B
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
where \(A\) and \(B\) are arbitrary constants.
The functions \(u\) and \(v\) are obtained directly from the differential equations written above. In particular, from the first we find:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int\frac{d\omega}{\omega}=\mu\int ds \ \Longrightarrow \ \omega=\omega(0)e^{\mu s}
\end{equation*}\]
From the third, instead:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int\frac{d\tilde{p}}{\tilde{p}}=-\frac{\sigma^2}{2}\int\omega^2ds=-\frac{\sigma^2\omega(0)^2}{2}\int e^{2\mu s}ds \ \Longrightarrow \ \tilde{p}=\tilde{p}(0)e^{-\frac{\sigma^2\omega(0)^2}{4\mu}e^{2\mu s}}
\end{equation*}\]
Since \(\omega(0)^2e^{2\mu s}=\omega^2\) then the two solutions are the following:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        \omega=\omega(0)e^{\mu s}\\       \tilde{p}=\tilde{p}(0)e^{-\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\omega^2}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
From the second equation of the system (eq:processo-u-o-sistema-equazioni-differenziali), finally, it results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \int dt=\int s \ \Longrightarrow \ t=t_0+s \ \iff \ s=t-t_0
\end{equation*}\]
This also means that \(\omega(s=0)=\omega\left(t=t_0\right)=\omega_0\), so finally by substituting:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        \omega=\omega_0e^{\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\\       \tilde{p}=\tilde{p}(0)e^{-\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
As said, the constraints must be constant. For this reason, by isolating \(\omega_0\) from the first and \(\tilde{p}(0)\) from the second, we obtain:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        \omega_0=\omega e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\\       \tilde{p}(0)=\tilde{p}e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
By setting \(A=\omega_0\) and \(B=\tilde{p}(0)\) we have found the functions \(u\) and \(v\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        u\left(\omega,t,\tilde{p}\right)=\omega e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\\       v\left(\omega,t,\tilde{p}\right)=\tilde{p}e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
It can be shown that \(u\) and \(v\) are related by the relation
\[\begin{equation}
    v=g(u)
\end{equation}\]
where \(g\) is an unknown functional to be found. Substituting:
\[\begin{equation}
    \tilde{p}e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}=g\left(\omega e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right) \ \Longrightarrow \ \tilde{p}(\omega,t)=e^{-\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}g\left(\omega e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)
\end{equation}\]
To find the functional \(g\) we must impose the initial condition:
\[\begin{equation}
    \tilde{p}(\omega,0)=e^{-\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}g(\omega) \ \Longrightarrow \ g(\omega)=\tilde{p}(\omega,0)e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}
\end{equation}\]
Assuming that the initial condition is \(p(x,0)=\delta\left(x-x_0\right)\), then \(\tilde{p}(\omega,0)\) is given by the Fourier transform:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{p}(\omega,0)=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}p(x,0)e^{i\omega x}dx=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\delta\left(x-x_0\right)e^{i\omega x}dx=e^{i\omega x_0}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s substitute in (eq:processo-u-o-funzionale-g-condizione-iniziale):
\[\begin{equation}
    g(\omega)=e^{i\omega x_0}e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}=e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2+ix_0\omega}
\end{equation}\]
Having found the expression for \(g(\omega)\) we can finally obtain \(\tilde{p}(\omega,t)\) in its explicit form starting from (eq:processo-u-o-espression-tilde-p-funzione-di-g):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \tilde{p}(\omega,t)=e^{-\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2}e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\omega^2e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}+ix_0\omega e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}}=e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\left(1-e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)\omega^2+ix_0e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\omega}
\end{equation*}\]
The propagator \(p(x,t)\) is none other than the inverse transform of \(\tilde{p}(\omega,t)\):
\[\begin{align*}
    p(x,t)&=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\tilde{p}(\omega,t)e^{-i\omega x}d\omega=\\
    &=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\left(1-e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)\omega^2+ix_0e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\omega}e^{-ix\omega}d\omega=\\
    &=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{\frac{\sigma^2}{4\mu}\left(1-e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)\omega^2-i\left(x-x_0e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)\omega}d\omega
\end{align*}\]
We recognize the form of the Gaussian integral that we know how to solve:
\[\begin{equation*}
    p(x,t)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left(1-e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)}}e^{-\frac{\left(x-x_0e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)^2}{2\cdot\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\left(1-e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)}}
\end{equation*}\]
Simplifying, we obtain the final form of the propagator:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p(x,t)=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{\pi\sigma^2\left(1-e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)}}e^{-\frac{\mu\left(x-x_0e^{-\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)^2}{\sigma^2\left(1-e^{-2\mu\left(t-t_0\right)}\right)}}}
\end{equation}\]
In the stationary limit, for \(t\to\infty\), we find
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p^{(st)}(x)=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{\pi\sigma^2}}e^{-\frac{\mu x^2}{\sigma^2}}}
\end{equation}\]
that is, a Gaussian centered at zero and with variance \(\frac{\sigma^2}{\mu}\).
The general formula was given by (eq:fokker-planck-soluzione-all-equilibrio-forma-finale), and we note that by substituting \(x_{min}=0\), \(\mu(x)=-\mu x\) and \(\sigma(x)=\sigma\) we obtain:
\[\begin{equation*}
    p^{(st)}(x)=\frac{1}{Z\sigma^2}e^{2\int_0^x\frac{-\mu x'}{\sigma^2}dx'}=\frac{1}{Z\sigma^2}e^{-\frac{\cancel{2}\mu}{\sigma^2}\cdot\frac{x^2}{\cancel{2}}}=\frac{1}{Z\sigma^2}e^{-\frac{\mu x^2}{\sigma^2}}
\end{equation*}\]
From which the normalization factor follows:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{1}{Z^2\sigma^2}\sqrt{\frac{\cancel{2}\pi}{\frac{\cancel{2}\mu}{\sigma^2}}}=1 \ \iff \ \frac{1}{Z\sigma^2}=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{\pi\sigma^2}}
\end{equation*}\]
which is exactly what we obtained in (eq:processo-u-o-propagatore-stazionario) by taking the propagator to the limit for \(t\to\infty\).

Show that the equation for the variance of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process obtained from the stochastic differential equation is the same as that obtained from the Fokker-Planck equation. Also verify that in the stationary limit it assumes the value \(\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}\).


Solution. We have already derived the equation for the variance through the differential equation, obtaining equation (eq:processo-u-o-varianza-equazione-non-omogenea).
As for the derivation with the Fokker-Planck equation, we will have to multiply both members of (eq:processo-u-o-equazione-fokker-planck) by $x^2$ and integrate:

\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2\frac{\partial}{\partial t}p(x,t)dx=\mu\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xp)dx+\frac{\sigma^2}{2}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2\frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2}p(x,t)dx
\end{equation*}

On the first member we can simply take the derivative out of the integral:

\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2\frac{\partial}{\partial t}p(x,t)dx=\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2p(x,t)dx
\end{equation*}

On the second member, instead, we will have to integrate by parts, the first term once and the second twice. The first will give:

\begin{equation*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xp)dx=\cancel{x^3p(x,t)\big|_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}-2\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2p(x,t)dx
\end{equation*}

The second, instead:

\begin{align*}
    \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2\frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2}p(x,t)dx&=\cancel{x^2\frac{\partial}{\partial x}p(x,t)\bigg|_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}-2\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x\frac{\partial}{\partial x}p(x,t)dx=\\
    &=-2\cancel{xp(x,t)\big|_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}+2\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}p(x,t)dx=2
\end{align*}

Substituting in the starting equation:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2p(x,t)dx=-2\mu\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2p(x,t)dx+\frac{\sigma^2}{\cancel{2}}\cdot\cancel{2}
\end{equation*}

Being by definition

\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x^2\right\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}x^2p(x,t)dx
\end{equation*}

we therefore find:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d}{dt}\left\langle x^2\right\rangle=-2\mu\left\langle x^2\right\rangle+\sigma^2
\end{equation*}

which is what is written in (eq:processo-u-o-varianza-equazione-non-omogenea).

In the stationary limit, the variance will be independent of time, therefore:

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{d}{dt}\left\langle x^2\right\rangle=0 \ \iff \ -2\mu\left\langle x^2\right\rangle+\sigma^2=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ \left\langle x^2\right\rangle=\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu}
\end{equation*}

just as predicted by the assignment.

12.1 Numerical solution
Intuitively, we must calculate how many trajectories randomly generated from the process \(x(t)\) are located between \(x\) and \(x+\Delta x\) at time \(t\).
Let’s therefore consider intervals of the same width that go from a minimum \(x_{min}\) to a maximum \(x_{max}\):
\[\begin{equation*}
\left\{[x_{\min},x_{\min}+\Delta x],\ldots,[x_{\max}-\Delta x,x_{\max}]\right\}
\end{equation*}\]
To write them as a function of a single index \(i\) we can define:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        i_{\min}=\dfrac{x_{\min}}{\Delta x}\\
        i_{\max}=\dfrac{x_{\max}}{\Delta x}
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow\qquad \left\{[x_i,x_i+\Delta x]\right\}_{i=i_{\min}}^{i_{\max}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s imagine we have performed \(N\) simulations, and we want to count how many of these fall into the interval defined by \(x_j\). In this regard, we can define the indicator function:
\[\begin{equation}
    I(a,A)=
    \begin{cases}
        1 \ \ \text{if} \ a\in A\\
        0 \ \ \text{if} \ a\notin A
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
In our case, the element \(a\) will be the \(j\)-th simulation at time \(t\), which we can indicate with \(x^{(j)}(t)\), while the interval is \(\left[x_i,x_i+\Delta x\right]\). Through the function just defined we can therefore count how many points among the total \(N\) fall into the interval, and finally normalize by \(N\).
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{1}{N}\sum_{j=1}^NI\left(x^{(j)}(t),\left[x_i,x_i+\Delta x\right]\right)
\end{equation*}\]
The probability relative to the \(i\)-th interval at time \(t\) can be obtained by taking the limit \(N\to\infty\):
\[\begin{equation}
    P\left(x_i,t\right)=\lim_{N\to\infty}\frac{1}{N}\sum_{j=1}^NI\left(x^{(j)}(t),\left[x_i,x_i+\Delta x\right]\right)
\end{equation}\]
The probability density is none other than the probability divided by the width of the considered interval, that is \(\Delta x\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    p\left(x_i,t\right)=\frac{P\left(x_i,t\right)}{\Delta x} \ \iff \ P\left(x_i,t\right)=p\left(x_i,t\right)\Delta x
\end{equation*}\]
We thus find:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p\left(x_i,t\right)=\lim_{N\to\infty}\frac{1}{N\Delta x}\sum_{j=1}^NI\left(x^{(j)}(t),\left[x_i,x_i+\Delta x\right]\right)}
\end{equation}\]
This formula is easily implementable at a computational level, since the indicator function is very easy to define and is not computationally very expensive. Obviously the result will be better approximated the larger \(N\) is, and also the smaller \(\Delta x\) is, since in this way the histogram tends to converge to the real distribution. At a theoretical level, in fact, we have that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \lim_{\Delta x\to0}\frac{I\left(x^{(j)}(t),\left[x_i,x_i+\Delta x\right]\right)}{\Delta x}=\delta\left(x_i-x^{(j)}(t)\right)
\end{equation*}\]
since the interval shrinks until it becomes infinitesimal, thus becoming to all intents and purposes a Dirac delta. Passing therefore from the discrete domain with \(x_i\) to the continuous one with the generic variable \(x\), we will write:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{p(x,t)=\lim_{N\to\infty}\frac{1}{N}\sum_{j=1}^N\delta\left(x-x^{(j)}(t)\right)}
\end{equation}\]
In the case of Brownian motion, for example, we must expect a histogram that, with a sufficiently high number of trajectories and a high discretization of the intervals, correctly approximates a Gaussian centered at the origin and with variance increasing with \(t\).

13.2 Boltzmann distribution
Let’s continue to consider the system described by the differential equation (eq:meccanica-classica-mezzo-ampio-equazione-differenziale) but let’s add a conservative contribution due to an external potential \(U(x)\):
\[\begin{equation}
    m\frac{d^2x}{dt^2}=-\gamma\frac{dx}{dt}\red{-\frac{dU}{dx}}+\sigma\zeta(t)
\end{equation}\]
Let’s also study this time the overdamped limit in which \(\frac{m}{\gamma}\to0\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{m}{\gamma}\frac{d^2x}{dt^2}=-\frac{dx}{dt}-\frac{1}{\gamma}\frac{dU}{dx}+\frac{\sigma}{\gamma}\zeta(t) \ \xrightarrow{\frac{m}{\gamma}\to0} \ -\frac{dx}{dt}-\frac{1}{\gamma}\frac{dU}{dx}+\frac{\sigma}{\gamma}\zeta(t)=0
\end{equation*}\]
Being in equilibrium conditions, we can make the coefficient of \(\zeta(t)\) explicit in terms of physical constants; it is, in fact, given by (eq:relazione-di-einstein-equazione-diffenziale-di-partenza) and therefore equal to \(\sqrt{2D}\), with \(D\) being given by the Einstein relation (equation (eq:relazione-di-einstein)):
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{\sigma}{\gamma}=\sqrt{2\cdot\frac{k_BT}{\gamma}}=\sqrt{\frac{2k_BT}{\gamma}} \ \Longrightarrow \ \frac{dx}{dt}+\frac{1}{\gamma}\frac{dU}{dx}-\sqrt{\frac{2k_BT}{\gamma}}\zeta(t)=0
\end{equation}\]
We thus find the following stochastic differential equation:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{dx=-\frac{1}{\gamma}\frac{dU}{dx}dt+\sqrt{\frac{2k_BT}{\gamma}}dB}
\end{equation}\]
We can identify the following two terms:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        \mu(x)=-\frac{1}{\gamma}\frac{dU}{dx}\\
        \sigma=\sqrt{\frac{2k_BT}{\gamma}}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
We can thus identify the equilibrium distribution from (eq:fokker-planck-soluzione-all-equilibrio-forma-finale):
\[\begin{equation*}
    p^{st}(x)\propto e^{\cancel{2}\int_0^x\left(-\frac{1}{\cancel{\gamma}}\frac{dU}{dx'}\right)\cdot\frac{\cancel{\gamma}}{\cancel{2}k_BT}dx'}=e^{-\frac{1}{k_BT}\int_0^x\frac{dU}{dx'}dx'}
\end{equation*}\]
Ultimately, we will have
\[\begin{equation}
    p^{st}(x)\propto e^{-\frac{1}{k_BT}U(x)}
\end{equation}\]
having assumed for simplicity that \(U(0)=0\).
We note that what we have found is none other than the Boltzmann distribution, widely studied in statistical mechanics as the distribution associated with the Maxwell-Boltzmann statistics, in which the temperature of the system is sufficiently high and the density low enough to be able to ignore quantum effects. The (eq:meccanica-classica-distribuzione-di-boltzmann-equilibrio-finale) is actually a simplified version in which only the position \(x\) is considered and the kinetic term \(K\) to which the momentum contributes is ignored.
From a purely physical point of view, we note that the distribution was derived starting from the Einstein relation, which is independent of the potential \(U\) useful for generating the external force: this further strengthens the idea that the coefficient \(D\) is an intrinsic characteristic of the system, not being modified in the presence of a potential that interferes from the outside.
It is also curious to note that the choice of a harmonic potential \(U(x)=\frac{1}{2}kx^2\) implies the following differential equation:
\[\begin{equation*}
    dx=-\frac{k}{\gamma}xdt+\sqrt{\frac{2k_BT}{\gamma}}
\end{equation*}\]
which is the one useful for defining the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process by substituting the appropriate coefficients.

13.2.1 Damped harmonic Brownian motion
We will now try to solve equation (eq:meccanica-classica-distribuzione-di-boltzmann-equazione-di-partenza) without going to the overdamped limit, but also including the second-order derivative.
For simplicity, we will consider the potential of the harmonic oscillator, which gives rise to the so-called damped harmonic Brownian motion:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\frac{d^2x}{dt^2}+\frac{\gamma}{m}\frac{dx}{dt}+\frac{k}{m}x=\frac{\sqrt{2\gamma k_BT}}{m}\zeta(t)}
\end{equation}\]
being \(\frac{dU}{dx}=kx\) and \(\sigma=\sqrt{2\gamma k_BT}\) (from (eq:meccanica-classica-distribuzione-di-boltzmann-calcolo-sigma-su-gamma)).
This is a non-homogeneous second-order differential equation. To solve it, we must first find the solution of the associated homogeneous equation:
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{d^2x}{dt^2}+\frac{\gamma}{m}\frac{dx}{dt}+kx=0
\end{equation}\]
It has as its solution an exponential of the type \(e^{\lambda t}\), from which the equation follows
\[\begin{equation*}
    e^{\lambda t}\left(\lambda^2+\frac{\gamma}{m}\lambda+\frac{k}{m}\right)=0
\end{equation*}\]
which gives rise to the characteristic equation
\[\begin{equation*}
    \lambda^2+\frac{\gamma}{m}\lambda+\frac{k}{m}=0
\end{equation*}\]
The solutions are
\[\begin{equation*}
    \lambda_\pm=\frac{-\frac{\gamma}{m}\pm\sqrt{\frac{\gamma^2}{m^2}-\frac{4k}{m}}}{2}=-\frac{\gamma}{2m}\pm\sqrt{\frac{\gamma^2}{4m^2}-\frac{k}{m}}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s denote by \(\gamma_r=\frac{\gamma}{2m}\) the reduced friction coefficient and by \(\omega_0=\sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}\) the characteristic frequency of the system:
\[\begin{equation}
    \lambda_\pm=-\gamma_r\pm\sqrt{\gamma_r^2-\omega_0^2}
\end{equation}\]
Finally, let’s denote the discriminant by \(\Omega=\gamma_r^2-\omega_0^2\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \lambda_\pm=-\gamma_r\pm\sqrt{\Omega}
\end{equation*}\]
We have three possible solutions depending on the sign of the determinant:
To solve the complete equation we also need to consider the second member, in which there is not a constant term but one dependent on time according to the Gaussian noise \(\zeta(t)\). To solve this type of equation it is necessary to use the Green’s function method, according to which the initial equation is rewritten in the form
\[\begin{equation*}
    \mathcal{L}[x(t)]=\frac{\sqrt{{2\gamma k_BT}}}{m}\zeta(t)
\end{equation*}\]
where \(\mathcal{L}\) is the differential operator \(\frac{d^2}{dt^2}+\frac{\gamma}{m}\frac{d}{dt}+\frac{k}{m}\).
Let’s rewrite the second member as a function of the Dirac delta:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \mathcal{L}[x(t)]=\frac{\sqrt{{2\gamma k_BT}}}{m}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\zeta(t')\delta(t-t')dt'
\end{equation*}\]
Restricting ourselves to the interval \([0,t]\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \mathcal{L}[x(t)]=\frac{\sqrt{{2\gamma k_BT}}}{m}\int_0^t\zeta(t')\delta(t-t')dt'
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s define the Green’s function \(G(t,t')\) as that function such that, once the operator \(\mathcal{L}\) is applied, the Dirac delta \(\delta(t-t')\) is returned:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \mathcal{L}[x(t)]=\frac{\sqrt{{2\gamma k_BT}}}{m}\int_0^t\zeta(t')\mathcal{L}[G(t,t')]dt'
\end{equation*}\]
Due to the linearity of the operator, we can take \(\mathcal{L}\) out of the integral, also including the multiplying coefficient:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \mathcal{L}[x(t)]=\mathcal{L}\left[\frac{\sqrt{{2\gamma k_BT}}}{m}\int_0^t\zeta(t')G(t,t')dt'\right]
\end{equation*}\]
The general solution thus follows
\[\begin{equation*}
    x(t)=x^{om}(t)+\frac{\sqrt{{2\gamma k_BT}}}{m}\int_0^t\zeta(t')G(t,t')dt'
\end{equation*}\]
being \(\mathcal{L}\left[x^{om}(t)\right]=0\) by how we defined it.
Finally, knowing that \(\zeta(t)dt=dB(t)\), we find the final formula
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{x(t)=x^{om}(t)+x^s(t)=x^{om}(t)+\frac{\sqrt{{2\gamma k_BT}}}{m}\int_0^tG(t,t')dB(t')}
\end{equation}\]
Green’s functions are known and tabulated,\footnote{Reference table: \url{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green

Finally, as we have done for all the stochastic processes studied, it is useful to derive the two-point correlation function \(\left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle\), which tells us how the coordinate of the system is correlated with itself at different times. Let’s make the solution explicit in terms of the homogeneous and stochastic contributions as done before:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x\left(t_1\right)x\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\left\langle\left[x^{om}\left(t_1\right)+x^s\left(t_1\right)\right]\left[x^{om}\left(t_2\right)+x^s\left(t_2\right)\right]\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
From which we obtain the following sum of average values:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x^{om}\left(t_1\right)x^{om}\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle+\left\langle x^{om}\left(t_1\right)x^s\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle+\left\langle x^s\left(t_1\right)x^{om}\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle+\left\langle x^s\left(t_1\right)x^s\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle
\end{equation*}\]
The are null due to the independence of the increments of Brownian motion:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left\langle x^{om}\left(t_1\right)x^s\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle=\frac{\sqrt{2\gamma k_BT}}{m}\left\langle x^{om}\left(t_1\right)\right\rangle\int_0^{t_2}\left\langle G\left(t_2,t'\right)\right\rangle\cancel{\langle dB(t')\rangle}=0
\end{equation*}\]
and the same applies to \(\left\langle x^{om}\left(t_2\right)x^s\left(t_1\right)\right\rangle\).
For the product of the stochastic terms, it is convenient to rewrite \(dB(t)\) as \(\zeta(t)dt\):
\[\begin{align*}
    \left\langle x^s\left(t_1\right)x^s\left(t_2\right)\right\rangle&=\frac{2\gamma k_BT}{m^2}\int_0^{t_1}\int_0^{t_2}\left\langle G\left(t_1,t'\right)G\left(t_2,t''\right)\right\rangle\langle\zeta(t')\zeta(t'')\rangle dt''dt'=\\
    &=\frac{2\gamma k_BT}{m^2}\int_0^{t_1}\int_0^{t_2}\left\langle G\left(t_1,t'\right)G\left(t_2,t''\right)\right\rangle\delta(t'-t'')dt''dt'\\
    &=\frac{2\gamma k_BT}{m^2}\int_0^{\min\left(t_1,t_2\right)}\left\langle G\left(t_1,t'\right)G\left(t_2,t'\right)\right\rangle dt'
\end{align*}\]
Let’s now study the three cases.

15.1 Irreversible binary systems
Let’s consider a substance of type \(X\) and a substance of type \(Y\) (reactants) that collide and react, producing a substance of type \(Z\) (product):
\[\begin{equation}
    n_XX+n_YY \ \xrightarrow{K} \ n_ZZ
\end{equation}\]
In the reaction, two important quantities are made explicit:

15.1.1 Law of mass action
To calculate the reaction rate, we must first make some assumptions about the system we are considering:
If all these conditions are met, we will say that we are at the dilute limit. Let’s indicate the concentrations of reactants and product with
\[\begin{equation*}
    x=\frac{n_X}{V}   y=\frac{n_Y}{V}   z=\frac{n_Z}{V}
\end{equation*}\]
For now we will only consider the case with stoichiometric coefficients equal to one; from section (sec:la-legge-di-azione-di-massa-generalizzata) we will extend to a generic number of molecules (or moles) different for the single reaction.
According to what we have written, the reaction rate \(r\) will be a function exclusively of \(x\) and \(y\). Furthermore, since the concentrations are small, we can expand with respect to \((x,y)=(0,0)\), thus approximating the function:
\[\begin{equation*}
    r(x,y)\simeq r(0,0)+\left(\partial_xr_0\right)x+\left(\partial_yr_0\right)y+\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{xx}^2r_0\right)x^2+\left(\partial_{xy}^2r_0\right)xy+\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{yy}^2r_0\right)y^2
\end{equation*}\]
having used the notation \(\partial_i r_0=\partial_i r\big|_{(x,y)=(0,0)}\) for simplicity.
We can set
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        r(x,0)=0   \forall x\\
        r(0,y)=0   \forall y
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
since both molecules of \(X\) and molecules of \(Y\) are necessary for the reaction to occur.
This implies that \(r(0,0)=0\). Furthermore, by substituting the two cases in the expansion, we obtain:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        r(x,0)\simeq\left(\partial_xr_0\right)x+\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{xx}^2r_0\right)x^2=0   \forall x\\
        r(0,y)\simeq\left(\partial_yr_0\right)y+\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{yy}^2r_0\right)y^2=0   \forall y
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
The fact that the first must hold for every value of \(x\) while the second for every value of \(y\) clarifies that these are identities, not equations. We will therefore have to set the individual coefficients to zero:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        \partial_xr_0=0,   \partial_{xx}^2r_0=0\\
        \partial_yr_0=0,   \partial_{yy}^2r_0=0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
Returning to the expansion, only one term survives:
\[\begin{equation*}
    r(x,y)\simeq\left(\partial_{xy}^2r_0\right)xy
\end{equation*}\]
Indicating the mixed derivative of the reaction rate calculated at the origin with \(K\), called the kinetic constant, we therefore find that
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{r(x,y)\simeq Kxy}
\end{equation}\]
We thus find what is called the law of mass action.

In a first approximation, the **rate** of any **chemical reaction** is proportional to the **product of the concentrations** of the reacting substances.

Let’s remember that this is valid only in the dilute limit regime, in which the \(X\) molecules all have the same probability \(P_{XY}\) of meeting and reacting with the \(Y\) molecules, and the same applies in reverse for \(P_{YX}\); these probabilities, moreover, are independent of each other.
What we have called the kinetic constant \(K\) is actually constant only with respect to the concentrations \(x\) and \(y\), but in general it can depend on other parameters of the system; in chemistry, for example, the Arrhenius equation is known, in which the constant is linked to the temperature \(T\) of the system by the following relation:
\[\begin{equation*}
    K=K_0e^{-\frac{E}{k_BT}}
\end{equation*}\]
Furthermore, since both the concentrations and the reaction rate are positive, then the kinetic constant must also necessarily be positive.


15.1.2 Evolution of concentrations
Starting from this law, it is possible to estimate the evolution of the concentrations of the reactants and the product of a reaction. Knowing the concentrations at time \(t\), in fact, those at time \(t+\Delta t\) will be given by
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x(t+\Delta t)=x(t)-r(x,y)\Delta t\\
        y(t+\Delta t)=y(t)-r(x,y)\Delta t\\
        z(t+\Delta t)=z(t)+r(x,y)\Delta t
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
since the reactants tend to decrease in concentration (being consumed), while the product tends to increase (being synthesized).
Let’s substitute the law of mass action:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x(t+\Delta t)\simeq x(t)-Kx(t)y(t)\Delta t\\
        y(t+\Delta t)\simeq y(t)-Kx(t)y(t)\Delta t\\
        z(t+\Delta t)\simeq z(t)+Kx(t)y(t)\Delta t
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        \frac{x(t+\Delta t)-x(t)}{\Delta t}\simeq-Kx(t)y(t)\\
        \frac{y(t+\Delta t)-y(t)}{\Delta t}\simeq-Kx(t)y(t)\\
        \frac{z(t+\Delta t)-z(t)}{\Delta t}\simeq Kx(t)y(t)
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
In the limit for \(t\to0\) it results:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=-Kx(t)y(t)\\
        y'(t)=-Kx(t)y(t)\\
        z'(t)=Kx(t)y(t)
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
Subtracting the first two equations member by member, we obtain:
\[\begin{equation*}
    x'(t)-y'(t)=0
\end{equation*}\]
This means that the derivatives of the two functions are equal, so the functions \(x(t)\) and \(y(t)\) differ only by a constant:
\[\begin{equation}
    x(t)-y(t)=c \ \iff \ y(y)=x(t)-c
\end{equation}\]
To calculate \(c\), just consider the boundary conditions; let’s set \(x(0)=x_0\) and \(y(0)=y_0\) obtaining
\[\begin{equation}
    y_0=x_0-c \ \iff \ c=x_0-y_0
\end{equation}\]
Substituting (eq:odes-x-funzione-di-y) in the differential equation relative to \(x\) we will find
\[\begin{equation}
    x'(t)=-Kx(t)[x(t)-c] \ \Longrightarrow \ \boxed{x'(t)=Kx(t)[c-x(t)]}
\end{equation}\]
The one found is a known differential equation, called the logistic equation. It is solvable by separating the variables:
\[\begin{equation}
    \frac{dx}{dt}=Kx(c-x) \ \iff \ \frac{1}{x(c-x)}dx=Kdt
\end{equation}\]
In order to integrate the first member, we must decompose \(\frac{1}{x(c-x)}\) into partial fractions:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{1}{x(c-x)}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{B}{c-x}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s multiply both members by the denominator of the first member:
\[\begin{equation*}
    1=A(c-x)+Bx=Ac-Ax+Bx \ \Longrightarrow \ Ac+(B-A)x=1
\end{equation*}\]
For the first and second members to be equal, it is necessary that
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        Ac=1\\
        (B-A)x=0
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        A=\frac{1}{c}\\
        B=A=\frac{1}{c}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
Returning to (eq:odes-equazione-differenziale-risoluzione-1) we will write:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{1}{c}\left(\frac{1}{x}+\frac{1}{c-x}\right)dx=Kdt \ \iff \ \left(\frac{1}{x}+\frac{1}{c-x}\right)dx=Kcdt
\end{equation*}\]
We can now integrate the two members:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \log\abs{x}-\log\abs{c-x}=Kct+c' \ \iff \ \log\abs{\frac{x}{c-x}}=Kct+c'
\end{equation*}\]
Bringing everything to the power of \(e\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{x}{c-x}=e^{Kct+c'}=e^{c'}e^{Kct}
\end{equation*}\]
By imposing \(x(0)=x_0\) we find the constant \(e^{c'}\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    e^{c'}=\frac{x_0}{c-x_0} \ \Longrightarrow \ \frac{x}{c-x}=\frac{x_0}{c-x_0}e^{Kct}
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s multiply both members by \(c-x\) to isolate \(x\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    x=\frac{x_0}{c-x_0}(c-x)e^{Kct}=\frac{cx_0}{c-x_0}e^{Kct}-\frac{x_0}{c-x_0}xe^{Kct}
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left(1+\frac{x_0}{c-x_0}e^{Kct}\right)x=\frac{cx_0}{c-x_0}e^{Kct}
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{c-x_0+x_0e^{Kct}}{\cancel{c-x_0}}x=\frac{cx_0e^{Kct}}{\cancel{c-x_0}}
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{x(t)=\frac{cx_0e^{Kct}}{c+x_0\left(e^{Kct}-1\right)}}
\end{equation}\]
We distinguish two different behaviors based on the sign of \(c\):
Obviously, by solving the differential equation with respect to \(Y\) we will find exactly the opposite behaviors.
It remains to consider the last case, in which \(c=0\), that is, when the molecules of the two substances are initially in the same number. To find the solution in this case, we just need to go back to the differential equation written in (eq:odes-equazione-differenziale-x), from which it follows
\[\begin{equation*}
    x'(t)=-Kx(x)^2 \ \Longrightarrow \ \frac{1}{x^2}dx=-Kdt \ \Longrightarrow \ -\frac{1}{x}=-Kt+c' \ \Longrightarrow x(t)=\frac{1}{Kt-c'}
\end{equation*}\]
In the limit \(t\to\infty\) it results \(x\to0\), therefore - as expected - the entire substance \(X\) is consumed, just as the entire substance \(Y\) is also consumed.
Returning to the differential equations, by summing \(x'(t)\) and \(z'(t)\) we obtain:
\[\begin{equation*}
    x'(t)+z'(t)=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ x(t)+z(t)=c'
\end{equation*}\]
By imposing the initial conditions we find \(c'\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    c'=x(0)+z(0)=x_0+z_0
\end{equation*}\]
Finally, by substituting (eq:odes-evoluzione-x) we find the formula that describes the evolution of the product concentration:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{z(t)=z_0+x_0-x(t)=z_0+x_0-\frac{cx_0e^{Kct}}{c+x_0\left(e^{Kct}-1\right)}}
\end{equation}\]
From the results seen above, we know that
\[\begin{align*}
    &c&gt;0 \ \Longrightarrow \ z\xrightarrow{t\to\infty}z_0+x_0-c\\
    &c\leqslant0 \ \Longrightarrow \ z\xrightarrow{t\to\infty}z_0+x_0
\end{align*}\]

15.2 Reversible binary systems
Let’s now consider systems of the type
\[\begin{equation}
    X + Y \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_+}}{\xleftarrow[K_-]{}} \ Z
\end{equation}\]
In this case we will not have a simple decrease in the quantity of reactants together with an increase in the quantity of product, but for each concentration we will find a contribution of growth and one of decrease.
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=-K_+x(t)y(t)+K_-z(t)\\
        y'(t)=-K_+x(t)y(t)+K_-z(t)\\
        z'(t)=K_+x(t)y(t)-K_-z(t)
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
To find the evolution of \(x(t)\) again this time, we will have to find a conservation law that links \(x\) with \(y\) and one that links \(x\) with \(z\). To do this, it will be sufficient to subtract the second equation from the first and then the third from the first:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)-y'(t)=0\\
        x'(t)+z'(t)=0
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        x(t)-y(t)=c_1\\
        x(t)+z(t)=c_2
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        y(t)=-\left[c_1-x(t)\right]\\
        z(t)=c_2-x(t)
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
Substituting in the differential equation relative to \(x(t)\):
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{x'(t)=K_+x(t)\left[c_1-x(t)\right]+K_-\left[c_2-x(t)\right]}
\end{equation}\]
This is known as the non-homogeneous logistic equation, since the known term \(K_-c_2\) is also added with respect to the one seen in irreversible systems. To solve this equation analytically, we must make the terms with respect to \(x(t)\) explicit and make sure to eliminate the known term to reduce to the solution seen previously (equation (eq:odes-evoluzione-x)):
\[\begin{equation*}
    x'(t)=-K_+x(t)^2+\left[K_+c_1-K_-\right]x(t)+K_-c_2
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s perform the substitution
\[\begin{equation*}
    \alpha(t)=x(t)+A \ \Longrightarrow \ \frac{d\alpha}{dt}=\frac{dx}{dt}
\end{equation*}\]
obtaining:
\[\begin{align*}
    \frac{d\alpha}{dt}&=-K_+[\alpha+A]^2+\left[K_+c_1-K_-\right][\alpha+A]+K_-c_2=\\
    &=-K_+\alpha^2-2K_+A\alpha\green{-K_+A^2}+K_+c_1\alpha\green{+K_+c_1A}-K_-\alpha\green{-K_-A+K_-c_2}
\end{align*}\]
where the terms independent of \(\alpha\) have been highlighted in green, which we want to eliminate. To do this, let’s solve the equation in \(A\) so as to cancel these contributions:
\[\begin{equation*}
    -K_+A^2+\left(K_+c_1-K_-\right)A+K_-c_2=0 \ \Rightarrow
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    \Rightarrow \ A=\frac{-K_+c_1+K_-\pm\sqrt{\left(K_+c_1-K_-\right)^2+4K_+K_-c_2}}{-2K_+}
\end{equation*}\]
Imposing
\[\begin{equation}
    B=\sqrt{\left(K_+c_1-K_-\right)^2+4K_+K_-c_2}
\end{equation}\]
we find the following value of \(A\):
\[\begin{equation}
    A=\frac{K_+c_1-K_-\mp B}{2K_+}
\end{equation}\]
Returning to the differential equation in \(\alpha\), what remains is
\[\begin{align*}
    \frac{d\alpha}{dt}&=-K_+\alpha^2+\left[K_+\left(c_1-2A\right)-K_-\right]\alpha\\
    &=-K_+\alpha^2+\left[K_+\left(c_1-\cancel{2}\frac{K_+c_1-K_-\mp B}{\cancel{2}K_+}\right)-K_-\right]\alpha=\\
    &=-K_+\alpha^2+\left[\cancel{k_+c_1}-\cancel{k_+c_1}+\cancel{K_-}\pm B-\cancel{K_-}\right]\alpha=K_+\alpha\left(\pm B-\alpha\right)
\end{align*}\]
Having reduced to (eq:odes-equazione-differenziale-x) we know that the solutions (equation (eq:odes-evoluzione-x)) are
\[\begin{equation*}
    \alpha(t)=\frac{\pm B\alpha(0)e^{\pm K_+Bt}}{\pm B+\alpha(0)\left[e^{\pm K_+Bt}-1\right]}
\end{equation*}\]
Remembering that \(\alpha(t)=x(t)+A\) the final result is
\[\begin{equation}
\boxed{x(t)=\frac{\pm B\,(x_0+A)\,e^{\pm K_+Bt}}{\pm B+(x_0+A)\left(e^{\pm K_+Bt}-1\right)}-A}
\end{equation}\]
where \(A\) and \(B\) are given by equations (eq:odes-reversibile-A) and (eq:odes-reversibile-B).
Knowing the relationship between \(x(t)\) and \(z(t)\), we therefore also know that
\[\begin{equation}
\boxed{z(t)=z_0+x_0-\frac{\pm B\left(x_0+A\right)e^{\pm K_+Bt}}{\pm B+\left(x_0+A\right)\left(e^{\pm K_+Bt}-1\right)}+A}
\end{equation}\]

15.2.1 Stationary concentrations
An interesting aspect of reversible reactions is to calculate what the concentrations will be in equilibrium conditions, that is, when
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{dx}{dt}=\frac{dy}{dt}=\frac{dz}{dt}=0
\end{equation*}\]
By stationarity we do not mean that no more reaction occurs, but that the fluctuations in concentrations are substantially negligible.
From the system of equations (eq:odes-sistemi-reversibili-equazioni) we will have
\[\begin{equation}
    K_+x\left(\bar{t}\right)y\left(\bar{t}\right)=K_-z\left(\bar{t}\right) \ \Longrightarrow \ \frac{x\left(\bar{t}\right)y\left(\bar{t}\right)}{z\left(\bar{t}\right)}=\frac{K_-}{K_+}
\end{equation}\]
Considering also the conservation laws that link \(x(t)\), \(y(t)\) and \(z(t)\) we can find the solutions:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        \frac{\bar{x}\bar{y}}{\bar{z}}=\frac{K_-}{K_+}\\
        \bar{y}=y_0-x_0+\bar{x}\\
        \bar{z}=z_0+x_0-\bar{x}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
having used for simplicity the notation \(\bar{x}=x\left(\bar{t}\right)\), \(\bar{y}=y\left(\bar{t}\right)\), \(\bar{z}=z\left(\bar{t}\right)\).
A second-degree equation will come out:
\[\begin{equation*}
        \frac{\bar{x}\left(y_0-x_0+\bar{x}\right)}{z_0+x_0-\bar{x}}=\frac{K_-}{K_+} \ \iff \ K_+\bar{x}^2+\left[K_+\left(y_0-x_0\right)+K_-\right]\bar{x}-K_-(x_0+z_0)=0
\end{equation*}\]
whose solutions are
\[\begin{equation*}
\bar{x}=\frac{K_+\left(x_0-y_0\right)-K_-\pm\sqrt{\left[K_+\left(y_0-x_0\right)+K_-\right]^2+4K_+K_-\left(x_0+z_0\right)}}{2K_+}
\end{equation*}\]

15.3 The generalized law of mass action
So far we have only considered cases in which the quantities of reactants and products were all in a \(1:1\) ratio with each other. To break this constraint we must introduce the stoichiometric coefficients:
\[\begin{equation}
    n_XX + n_YY \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_+}}{\xleftarrow[K_-]{}} \ n_ZZ
\end{equation}\]
To find the solution in this case we can start from a real case, that of the Haber process, through which it is possible to synthesize ammonia from nitrogen and hydrogen:
\[\begin{equation*}
    N_2 + 3H_2 \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_+}}{\xleftarrow[K_-]{}} \ 2NH_3
\end{equation*}\]
The equation will therefore be
\[\begin{equation*}
    X+3Y \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_+}}{\xleftarrow[K_-]{}} \ 2Z
\end{equation*}\]
According to the law of mass action, we will have to look at the product of the individual concentrations to obtain the variation of \(x\), \(y\) and \(z\). Let’s consider, for example, the substance \(X\): the written reaction tells us that for each molecule \(X\) the reaction with three molecules \(Y\) is necessary, so the product to consider will be \(xy^3\); similarly, the decay of two molecules \(Z\) is necessary, so the variation of \(x\) will be proportional to \(z^2\). Obviously this reasoning is valid for a single molecule, so in the case of the substance \(Y\) the same relationship must contain a factor of two, since each reaction produces two molecules.
Extending this reasoning we will obtain the following set of equations:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=-K_+x(t)y(t)^3+K_-z(t)^2\\
        y'(t)=-3K_+x(t)y(t)^3+3K_-z(t)^2\\
        z'(t)=2K_+x(t)y(t)^3-2K_-z(t)^2
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
We thus find a more general form of the law of mass action, extended to any ratio of quantities between reactants and products.

In a first approximation, the **rate** of any **chemical reaction** is proportional to the **product of the concentrations** of the reacting substances, each raised to its respective stoichiometric coefficient which must also be included in the rate with the appropriate sign.

At this point we can write the generic reversible reaction together with the relative differential equations:
\[\begin{equation}
    aX+bY \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_+}}{\xleftarrow[K_-]{}} \ cZ+dW \ \iff \
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=a\left(-K_+x^ay^b+K_-z^cw^d\right)\\
        y'(t)=b\left(-K_+x^ay^b+K_-z^cw^d\right)\\
        z'(t)=c\left(K_+x^ay^b-K_-z^cw^d\right)\\
        w'(t)=d\left(K_+x^ay^b-K_-z^cw^d\right)
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]} \end{equation}
At steady state we will have
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\frac{\bar{x}^a\bar{y}^b}{\bar{z}^c\bar{w}^d}=\frac{K_-}{K_+}}
\end{equation}\]
The conservation laws can be found as we have already done previously, that is, by adding and subtracting the differential equations so as to cancel the second member. The conservation laws with respect to \(x(t)\), for example, are given by
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        bx'(t)-ay'(t)=0\\
        cx'(t)-az'(t)=0\\
        dx'(t)-aw'(t)=0
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        bx-ay=bx_0-ay_0\\
        cx-az=cx_0-az_0\\
        dx-aw=dx_0-aw_0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\begin{cases}
        y=\frac{1}{a}\left[b\left(x-x_0\right)+ay_0\right]\\
        z=\frac{1}{a}\left[c\left(x-x_0\right)+az_0\right]\\
        w=\frac{1}{a}\left[d\left(x-x_0\right)+aw_0\right]
    \end{cases}}
\end{equation}\]

15.4 General chemical reactions
Now we have all the tools we need to study any set of chemical reactions related to a system.
Let’s consider a total of \(m\) substances \(X_1,\dots,X_m\) involved in a total of \(n\) reactions. The system as a whole will be described by
\[\begin{equation}
    \sum_{i=1}^ma_{ij}X_i \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_j^+}}{\xleftarrow[K_j^-]{}} \ \sum_{i=1}^mb_{ij}X_i   j=1,2,\dots,n
\end{equation}\]
where \(a_{ij}\) and \(b_{ij}\) are the stoichiometric coefficients relative to the \(i\)-th substance in the \(j\)-th reaction. If this substance is absent as a reactant then \(a_{ij}=0\), and similarly if it is absent as a product then \(b_{ij}=0\).
Let’s now try to write the evolutions of the concentrations through differential equations. Considering for now only the first reaction (\(j=1\)), we must take into account the difference between the stoichiometric coefficients relative to the substance as a product (\(b_{i1}\)) and to the substance as a reactant (\(a_{i1}\)), which must be factored in front of everything; for the rest we will have to consider two contributions:
Ultimately, we obtain
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left(b_{i1}-a_{i1}\right)\left(K_1^+\prod_{i=1}^mx_i^{a_{i1}}-K_1^-\prod_{i=1}^mx_i^{b_{i1}}\right)
\end{equation*}\]
We will have to consider the contributions from all the \(n\) reactions, so we will finally obtain
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\frac{dx_i}{dt}=\sum_{j=1}^n\left(b_{ij}-a_{ij}\right)\left(K_j^+\prod_{i=1}^mx_i^{a_{ij}}-K_j^-\prod_{i=j}^mx_i^{b_{ij}}\right)}
\end{equation}\]
We can write all the equations in compact form using vector notation, defining \(\vec{x}=\left(x_1,x_2,\dots,x_m\right)\), the stoichiometric matrix \(S\) whose elements \(S_{ij}\) are given by \(b_{ij}-a_{ij}\) and the function \(r_j\left(\vec{x}\right)\) such that
\[\begin{equation*}
    r_j\left(\vec{x}\right)=K_j^+\prod_{i=1}^mx_i^{a_{ij}}-K_j^-\prod_{i=j}^mx_i^{b_{ij}}
\end{equation*}\]
We will write:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\frac{d\vec{x}}{dt}=S\vec{r}\left(\vec{x}\right)}
\end{equation}\]

15.4.1 Conservation laws
A generic linear conservation law is defined by a constant vector \(\vec{c}\) such that
\[\begin{equation}
    \vec{c}^{\ T}\cdot\frac{d\vec{x}}{dt}=0
\end{equation}\]
Substituting equation (eq:odes-reazioni-chimiche-generali-forma-compatta):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \vec{c}^{\ T}\cdot S\vec{r}\left(\vec{x}\right)=0
\end{equation*}\]
If the conservation law is valid, the relationship written above must be valid regardless of the choice of \(\vec{r}\left(\vec{x}\right)\), so we will have to set \(\vec{c}^{\ T}S\) to zero, or equivalently:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{S^T\vec{c}=\vec{0}}
\end{equation}\]
Let’s remember that the set of vectors \(\vec{x}_i\) such that \(A\vec{x}_i=\vec{0}\) constitutes the kernel of the matrix \(A\). Similarly, the vectors \(\vec{c}\) such that \(S^T\vec{c}=\vec{0}\) constitute the kernel of \(S^T\). We can therefore state that

The **coefficients** relative to the **linear conservation laws** belong to the **kernel** of the **transposed stoichiometric matrix**

From this it also follows that the number of independent linear conservation laws is equal to the dimension of the kernel of \(S^T\).
To understand what has been written, we can start from a very simple example, such as the trivial irreversible relation
\[\begin{equation*}
    X+Y \ \longrightarrow \ Z
\end{equation*}\]
The stoichiometric matrix is given by
\[\begin{equation*}
    S=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        0-1\\
        0-1\\
        1-0
    \end{pmatrix}
    =
    \begin{pmatrix}
        -1\\
        -1\\
        1
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{equation*}\]
The kernel of \(S^T\) is
\[\begin{equation*}
    S^T\vec{c}=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        -1 & -1 & 1
    \end{pmatrix}
    \begin{pmatrix}
        c_1\\
        c_2\\
        c_3
    \end{pmatrix}
    =-c_1-c_2+c_3=0
\end{equation*}\]
One possibility is that
\[\begin{equation*}
    c_3=c_1+c_2 \ \Longrightarrow \ \vec{c}=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        c_1\\
        c_2\\
        c_1+c_2
    \end{pmatrix}
    =
    c_1
    \begin{pmatrix}
        1\\
        0\\
        1
    \end{pmatrix}
    +c_2
    \begin{pmatrix}
        0\\
        1\\
        1
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{equation*}\]
By arbitrarily setting \(c_1=c_2=1\) we will find the conservation laws
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x+z=0\\
        y+z=0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
Another possibility is the following:
\[\begin{equation*}
    c_1=-c_2+c_3 \ \Longrightarrow \ \vec{c}=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        -c_2+c_3\\
        c_2\\
        c_3
    \end{pmatrix}
    =c_2
    \begin{pmatrix}
        -1\\
        1\\
        0
    \end{pmatrix}
    +c_3
    \begin{pmatrix}
        1\\
        0\\
        1
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{equation*}\]
In this case the conservation laws are
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        -x+y=0\\
        x+z=0
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
which are the same ones we used in paragraph (sec:evoluzione-delle-concentrazioni).

15.5 Known models
As anticipated, all the reasoning done can be extended to dynamics completely different from that of actual chemical reactions, such as biological ecosystems, epidemic models, physiological mechanisms and so on. Below we will see some practical examples in which systems of ordinary differential equations come into play.

15.5.1 Lotka-Volterra model
A first system to study is the one related to the predator-prey dynamics. Indicating with \(X\) the prey and with \(Y\) the predator, we can consider three dynamics:
The system of reactions is therefore the following:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        X \ \xrightarrow{K_1} \ 2X\\
        X+Y \ \xrightarrow{K_2} \ 2Y\\
        Y \ \xrightarrow{K_3} \ \varnothing
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
It is important to understand that in this case these are not real reactions as they are understood in chemistry, since there is not necessarily an interaction between two different species as we observe in the first and third cases. We could in some way speak of an between the individual and the surrounding environment, such as the prey and the food useful for its survival and therefore its subsequent reproduction, but the food in question is not a real element involved in the dynamics of evolution of the species, but only something that is intrinsically part of the system and allows it to exist in the way we observe it.
In any case, the law of mass action can also be extended to cases like these; the differential equations that indicate the variations of the species, in fact, will be given by
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=K_1x(t)-K_2x(t)y(t)\\
        y'(t)=K_2x(t)y(t)-K_3y(t)
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \boxed{\begin{cases}
        x'(t)=\left[K_1-K_2y(t)\right]x(t)\\
        y'(t)=\left[K_2x(t)-K_3\right]y(t)
    \end{cases}}
\end{equation}\]
These equations are known in the literature as the Lotka-Volterra equations.
At steady state, excluding the trivial solution \(\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)=(0,0)\), it results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=0\\
        y'(t)=0
    \end{cases}
    \iff
    \begin{cases}
        K_1-K_2\bar{y}=0\\
        K_2\bar{x}-K_3=0
    \end{cases}
    \Longrightarrow
    \begin{cases}
        \bar{y}=\frac{K_1}{K_2}\\
        \bar{x}=\frac{K_3}{K_2}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
For the dynamics of a physical system of this type, it is useful to calculate the value assumed by the eigenvalue relative to the Jacobian at the stationary point; the possibilities are shown to be five:
Let’s try to evaluate the case of the predator-prey system by calculating the Jacobian of the system:
\[\begin{equation*}
    J=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        \frac{\partial x'}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial x'}{\partial y}\\
        \frac{\partial y'}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial y'}{\partial y}
    \end{pmatrix}
    =
    \begin{pmatrix}
        K_1-K_2y & -K_2x\\
        K_2y & K_2x-K_3
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{equation*}\]
At the stationary point the Jacobian becomes
\[\begin{equation*}
    J\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        K_1-K_2\cdot\frac{K_1}{K_2} & -K_2\cdot\frac{K_3}{K_2}\\
        K_2\cdot\frac{K_1}{K_2} & K_2\cdot\frac{K_3}{K_2}-K_3
    \end{pmatrix}
    =
    \begin{pmatrix}
        0 & -K_3\\
        K_1 & 0
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{equation*}\]
The eigenvalues of the matrix are
\[\begin{equation*}
    \det\left(J\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)-\lambda I\right)=
    \begin{pmatrix}
        -\lambda & -K_3\\
        K_1 & -\lambda
    \end{pmatrix}
    =\lambda^2+K_1K_3=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ \lambda=\pm i\sqrt{K_1K_3}
\end{equation*}\]
We are therefore in the last case, in which the system neither converges nor diverges but tends to stabilize in an orbit around the point defined by the kinetic constants \(K_1\), \(K_2\) and \(K_3\).
In this case, calculating the conservation law is not trivial; the quantity that is shown to be conserved is the Lyapunov function:
\[\begin{equation*}
    V(x,y)=K_2(x+y)-K_3\ln x-K_1\ln y
\end{equation*}\]
By deriving, in fact, we obtain
\[\begin{align*}
    \frac{dV}{dt}&=\frac{\partial V}{\partial x}\frac{\partial x}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial V}{\partial y}\frac{\partial y}{\partial t}=\\
    &=\left(K_2-\frac{K_3}{x}\right)\left(K_1-K_2y\right)x+\left(K_2-\frac{K_1}{y}\right)\left(K_2x-K_3\right)y=\\
    &=\left(K_2x-K_3\right)\left(K_1-K_2y\right)+\left(K_2y-K_1\right)\left(K_2x-K_3\right)=\\
    &=\left(K_2x-K_3\right)\left(\cancel{K_1}-\cancel{K_2y}+\cancel{K_2y}-\cancel{K_1}\right)=0
\end{align*}\]
Let’s always keep in mind that this model can hardly be applied in real contexts, because it ignores many aspects that are very important in an ecosystem that we know to be - in general - very delicate. A trivial example is the number of individuals of a species: according to this model, in fact, in principle a species can have a population of any size, but in reality we know that below a certain threshold a species becomes at serious risk of extinction. The Lotka-Volterra model is however useful as a starting point for developing more elaborate models that can describe real systems.


15.5.2 Brusselator
Another system associated with chaotic behaviors with limit cycles is the brusselator model, described by the following reactions:
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        A \ \xrightarrow{K_1} \ X\\
        B+X \ \xrightarrow{K_2} \ Y+D\\
        2X+Y \ \xrightarrow{K_3} \ 3X\\
        X \ \xrightarrow{K_4} \ E\\
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]
This model was introduced to study autocatalytic reactions, that is, those reactions that have as a product a catalyst capable of accelerating the same. It was conceived by the Nobel Prize winner for chemistry Ilya Prigogine, and was later studied in depth due to its chaotic dynamic characteristics and oscillatory behaviors.
The quantities \(A\), \(B\), \(D\) and \(E\) are considered constant. The remaining concentrations will follow the system of differential equations constructed as we know:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=K_1A-K_2Bx(t)+K_3x(t)^2y(t)-K_4x(t)\\
        y'(t)=K_2Bx(t)-K_3x(t)^2y(t)
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
which, by ordering the terms, becomes
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\begin{cases}
        x'(t)=K_1A-\left[K_2B-K_3x(t)y(t)+K_4\right]x(t)\\
        y'(t)=\left[K_2B-K_3x(t)y(t)\right]x(t)
    \end{cases}}
\end{equation}\]
Excluding the obvious solution for the equilibrium that would be had with \(x(t)=0\), as the only other possibility remains
\[\begin{equation*}
    K_2B-K_3\bar{x}\bar{y}=0 \ \iff \ \bar{y}=\frac{K_2B}{K_3\bar{x}}
\end{equation*}\]
in order to cancel \(y'(t)\). Substituting in the differential equation relative to \(x(t)\) results:
\[\begin{equation*}
    K_1A-\left(K_2B-\cancel{K_3}\bar{x}\frac{K_2B}{\cancel{K_3}\bar{x}}+K_4\right)\bar{x}=0 \ \iff \ K_1A\cancel{-K_2B\bar{x}}\cancel{+K_2B\bar{x}}-K_3\bar{x}=0
\end{equation*}\]
The stationary point will therefore be
\[\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases}
        \bar{x}=\frac{K_1}{K_4}A\\
        \bar{y}=\frac{K_2K_4}{K_1K_3}\frac{B}{A}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]


15.5.3 Michaelis-Menten kinetics
Moving to the biological field, we can consider an enzymatic reaction, in which an enzyme \(E\) binds to a substrate \(S\) forming what is called an intermediate complex \(ES\), which can subsequently release the same enzyme together with the synthesized protein \(P\):
\[\begin{equation}
    E+S \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_+}}{\xleftarrow[K_-]{}} \ ES \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{C_+}}{\xleftarrow[C_-]{}} \ E+P
\end{equation}\]
This model is called Michaelis-Menten kinetics because of the two chemists who first proposed it in 1913. We can rewrite it for simplicity as
\[\begin{equation*}
    X+Y \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{K_+}}{\xleftarrow[K_-]{}} \ Z \ \genfrac{}{}{-3pt}{}{\xrightarrow{C_+}}{\xleftarrow[C_-]{}} \ X+W
\end{equation*}\]
We thus find the following equations:
\[\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
        x'(t)=-K_+xy+K_-z+C_+z-C_-xw\\
        y'(t)=-K_+xy+K_-z\\
        z'(t)=K_+xy-K_-z-C_+z+C_-xw\\
        w'(t)=C_+z-C_-xw
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}\]
which ordered become
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\begin{cases}
        x'(t)=-\left(K_+y+C_-w\right)x+\left(K_-+C_+\right)z\\
        y'(t)=-K_+xy+K_-z\\
        z'(t)=\left(K_+y+C_-w\right)x-\left(K_-+C_+\right)z\\
        w'(t)=-C_-xw+C_+z
    \end{cases}}
\end{equation}\]
At equilibrium, the rate of formation of the enzyme-substrate complex must equal the rate of its decomposition, so \(z\) must not change:
\[\begin{equation*}
    z'(t)=0 \ \iff \ z=\frac{K_+y+C_-w}{K_-+C_+}x
\end{equation*}\]
Furthermore, from the equations we note that
\[\begin{equation*}
    x'(t)-z'(t)=0 \ \Longrightarrow \ x-z=x_0-z_0 \ \iff \ x=z+x_0-z_0
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s substitute:
\[\begin{equation*}
    z=\frac{K_+y+C_-w}{K_-+C_+}\left(z+x_0-z_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Let’s calculate \(z\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    \left(1-\frac{K_+y+C_-w}{K_-+C_+}\right)z=\frac{K_+y+C_-w}{K_-+C_+}\left(x_0-z_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    \frac{K_-+C_+-K_+y-C_-w}{K_-+C_+}z=\frac{K_+y+C_-w}{K_-+C_+}\left(x_0-z_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
\[\begin{equation*}
    z=\frac{K_+y+C_-w}{K_-+C_+-K_+y-C_-w}\left(x_0-z_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Dividing the numerator and denominator by \(K_+y+C_-w\):
\[\begin{equation*}
    z=\frac{1}{\frac{K_-+C_+}{K_+y+C_-w}-1}\left(x_0-z_0\right)
\end{equation*}\]
Indicating the fraction in the denominator with \(K(y,w)\) we can write:
\[\begin{equation}
    \boxed{z=\frac{1}{K(y,w)-1}\left(x_0-z_0\right)}
\end{equation}\]
